<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Hoffman     06-17 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hoffman,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activist To Host '60s Ball To Raise Money For Anti-Nuclear Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abbie Hoffman, who gained fame 20
years ago at protests at the Democratic National Convention in
Chicago, plans to be host of a nostalgic ball Sunday to raise money
for anti-nuclear advertising.
   The ``'60s Revival Ball'' at the Pearl Street nightclub here
will feature such entertainment as a musician playing the sound of
a nuclear disaster on his harmonica and free copies of Hoffman's
``Steal This Book'' for the first 10 partygoers who come with their
fathers. Admission is $10.
   Hoffman said he has become fond of Northampton since a local
jury cleared him in April 1987 of disorderly conduct and
trespassing charges stemming from his arrest at a demonstration
against CIA recruiting at the nearby University of Massachusetts.
   Hoffman and 14 other protesters, including Amy Carter, daughter
of former President Jimmy Carter, had argued that they broke minor
trespassing laws to prevent the graver harm of spy agency
recruiting.
   ``I'm not really big on nostalgia, but I do about 20 benefits a
year because raising money on our side of the fence isn't that
easy,'' Hoffman said. ``We're not like the PTL where they can turn
around and raise $12 million by auctioning off Costa Rica.''
   The Northampton benefit was organized by Al Giordano, the moving
force behind a November ballot referendum aimed at closing
Massachusetts' two nuclear power plants by outlawing nuclear waste.
   The money raised by the ball will go to the Anti-Nuclear Media
Fund to buy ad time on behalf of anti-nuclear initiatives
nationwide.
   Filmmaker Douglas Trumball, whose special-effects credits
include ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' ``Close Encounters of the Third
Kind'' and ``E.T.,'' will help design the anti-nuclear ads,
Giordano said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
