<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Wrather     06-17 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Wrather,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bonita Wrather Honored with Gallery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Bonita Granville Wrather, retiring
chairwoman of the American Film Institute, was honored by actor
Jack Lemmon and others who helped dedicate an art gallery in her
name.
   ``In making her name a permanent part of the AFI campus, the
trustees gratefully acknowledge her generosity to the film and
television arts _ as actress, businesswoman, philanthropic leader,
cultural emissary and exemplary friend and advocate of the
institution,'' AFI Director Jean Firstenberg said Thursday.
   The Bonita Granville Wrather Gallery, featuring film and
television-related art, is located on the first floor of the Warner
Communications Building on the AFI campus.
   Ms. Wrather, 65, was nominated at age 12 for an Academy Award
for her performance in the film ``These Three,'' starring Lillian
Hellman and William Wyler. She went on to appear in more than 55
films and television shows.
</TEXT>
