<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmCredit     06-17 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Credit,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Senators Rip Into Goodies for Executives at Failed Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Free cars and lavish office furnishings for
executives of the failed Federal Land Bank in Jackson, Miss., are
drawing sharp criticism from Farm Belt senators.
   ``If even a fraction of what we've heard about today is true,
some type of punitive action will have to be taken against those
who are responsible,'' said Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., after a
report from regulators Thursday.
   They said 133 automobiles were found at the Jackson institution,
one of 12 land banks in the $50 billion Farm Credit System, a
network of borrower-owned cooperatives that together make up the
nation's largest farm lender.
   Forty other new cars were on order May 20 when the bank ran out
of operating capital, closed its doors and went into receivership,
they said. They said even newly hired lending officers were
authorized to use the autos for personal driving of up to 1,000
miles a month.
   A $60,000 bill arising from credit cards issued to bank
executives also was pending, according to the system's chief
regulator, Frank Naylor, chairman of the Farm Credit Administration.
   Naylor stessed that no basis had been established to suggest
wrongdoing by anyone. He said his agency's investigators were
continuing their efforts to sort out the situation.
   He acknowledged that one former bank officical had been
permitted to take home some of his office furnishings. But he said
this was not uncommon in private industry in settlements between
companies and departing executives.
   Senators, however, were more critical.
   ``At a time when farmers are living on the edge of bankruptcy, I
find it appalling that the funds of farmer-borrowers were being
used to decorate the walls with Persian rugs and high-priced
paintings,'' Boren said.
   Boren himself said that oriental rugs and opulent art works and
furnishings had adorned a number of offices and that ``there are
some nails on the wall with nothing hanging on them now.''
   The report prompted Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., to call for an FBI
investigation.
   ``What we've heard here is utterly outrageous,'' Conrad said.
``What we've heard is going to shake confidence in the Farm Credit
System.''
   Boren stopped short of calling for an FBI probe but urged Naylor
to make initial contact with the FBI while continuing his own
investigation.
   Authorities say one reason several Farm Credit System banks got
into trouble is that they became locked into high-priced borrowing
themselves early in the 1980s before the farm economy went into the
doldrums.
   Competing institutions lowered interest rates. But Farm Credit
System banks could not follow suit because they were locked into
high credit costs.
   For that reason, their most creditworthy customers were lured
away while other loans increasingly became delinquent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
