<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CovertOperations     06-17 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Covert Operations,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Reagan Will Veto Notification Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will veto any bill requiring
him to notify Congress within 48 hours of the start of a covert
operation, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci told a House
committee considering such legislation.
   Carlucci told the House Foreign Affairs Committee on Thursday he
believes that if Reagan is compelled to reject such a measure, the
resulting constitutional confrontation between the White House and
Congress would cause a harmful and long-lasting lack of trust
between the two branches.
   But several House members said they believe presidents must be
held to a some standard of notification to prevent abuses of the
kind exposed by the Iran-Contra affair.
   Sen. William S. Cohen, R-Maine., co-chairman of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, testified that he and his colleagues have
concluded ``that either you establish a time certain _ 48 hours or
whatever _ or it ends up being a matter of presidential
discretion.''
   ``There really is no middle ground,'' Cohen said.
   Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., said that while he views
requiring a notice of covert operations within 48 hours as ``a
rather modest proposal,'' there are those in the administration
``who think it's deadly.''
   Carlucci said he has ``no doubt'' Reagan will veto the bill if
it reaches his desk in its present form.
   ``I respectfully urge the members to reflect on the wisdom of
the president's position and, beyond this, to consider the effect
of provoking a presidential veto on legislation governing the
entire realm of intelligence activities,'' Carlucci said.
   ``If trust, candor and accountability are the remedy to the
problems that brought about the Iran-Contra affair,'' he said,
``...the Congress risks undermining all of these goals and
reintroducing again an unhealthy adversarial basis to the oversight
process for years to come.
   ``I can think of no step by the Congress which would do more
harm to the process of rebuilding an atmosphere of trust and candor
between the branches.''
   The defense secretary said Reagan believes holding him to a
strict notification timetable would undermine his constitutional
authority as commander in chief and deprive him of essential
flexibility.
   He noted that the Canadian government offered its help in 1980
to spirit six American diplomats out of Iran only on condition that
Congress not be told.
   Had a 48-hour notification law been in effect, he said, the
White House would have had no choice but to reject the Canadian
offer to free Americans in peril.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
