<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoccerInvasion 2ndLd-Writethru   06-17 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Invasion, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0404,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Soccer Rowdies Wreck Bars, Government Proposes Crackdown</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with British proposals
against soccer hooliganism. Pick up 5th pvs, `England's
Football...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roving groups of English soccer
fans, some singing ``God Save the Queen,'' overturned a car,
smashed windows and furniture in bars and fought with German pub
patrons early Friday, police said.
   On Thursday, the British government proposed barring England's
national team from the World Cup, the Olympics and other
international events in a five-part crackdown on soccer hooliganism.
   Several people were slightly injured in the violence in
Frankfurt's ``Apple Wine'' district and near the city's main train
station, police said.
   Seven Britons were arrested out of about 60 troublemakers, they
said.
   More than 100 English soccer fans have been arrested in clashes
during the European Soccer Championships, which West Germany is
hosting.
   British Home Secretary Douglas Hurd unveiled the proposals after
a 75-minute ``soccer summit'' at Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
10 Downing Street home.
   ``We were all appalled by what has happened in Germany,'' Hurd
said. ``We were clear that present arrangements are not enough and
have got to be strengthened.''
   Hurd also proposed travel restrictions on fans involved in
violence, tighter controls over who gets into matches, tougher
licensing laws outside soccer stadiums to cut down on fans getting
drunk before and after matches and stepped-up police surveillance.
   England's Football Association, reacting to the wave of
violence, on Thursday withdrew its application for readmission to
European club soccer tournaments next season.
   English clubs were banned from competing in Europe after 39
people were killed in May 1985 in a rampage by Liverpool fans
through Heysel Stadium in Brussels, Belgium. Most of the victims
were fans of Juventus, from Turin, Italy.
   A state official said Thursday that West Germans, and not
English fans, were the initiators of violence Tuesday and Wednesday
in Duesseldorf, in which 371 people were arrested, 18 of them
English fans and most of the others West Germans. Most were
released after a few hours in jail.
   ``These (West German) hooligans were not soccer fans, but just
thugs who could not stomach the thought that English fans had a
reputation for being more brutal than themselves,'' said the
official, Herbert Schnoor, interior minister of the North-Rhine
Westphalia state, in a radio interview.
   ``There is no nation that can afford to have a policeman
stationed right next to every thug'' at soccer games, Schnoor said.
His ministry said the special police deployment at the game cost
about $900,000.
   About 22,000 Dutch and 8,500 English fans jammed into
Duesseldorf for the Wednesday night match, in which the Netherlands
defeated England 3-1.
   Federal border police, meanwhile, said they had seized hundreds
of truncheons, knives, whips, chains, baseball bats, fireworks and
other potential weapons from fans entering West Germany for the
championship series.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0152EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra Bjt   06-17 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Judge Strikes Key Defense Argument By North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stressing the prosecution's ``good faith'' in
safeguarding the rights of Oliver L. North and three co-defendants,
a federal judge says it's time for the Iran-Contra cases to go to
trial.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on Thursday cleared the
way for the four separate trials he has ordered by rejecting
defendants' claims that prosecutors violated their constitutional
rights.
   Gesell still must rule on defense motions that unprecedented
volumes of classified material will make trials impossible. But his
ruling left virtually no doubt that he plans to proceed.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh has chosen North, the
fired National Security Council staffer who directed the
Iran-Contra affair, to be tried first. Gesell is expected to set a
trial date in the next few weeks.
   ``We are, of course, pleased with Judge Gesell's ruling,'' Walsh
said. ``We are prepared to go forward as directed by the court.''
   Thursday's ruling centered on defense contentions that Walsh
built his case on testimony given to Congress by three of the
defendants under grants of limited immunity from prosecution.
   Congress grants the immunity in order to compel testimony of
reluctant witnesses _ in this case, North, former National Security
Adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealer Albert Hakim. The fourth
defendant, businessman Richard V. Secord, testified without
immunity.
   As a tradeoff for the immunity, the prosecution in a criminal
case is barred from using the compelled testimony, except to show
perjury. The defense claimed that Walsh violated the immunity law
by building his case from the immunized testimony.
   Gesell rejected the claim, and praised Walsh for taking
extraordinary measures to make sure the prosecution staff, grand
jury witnesses, and grand jurors were not exposed to the immunized
testimony.
   ``Nothing has developed in the court's preliminary inquiry ...
which suggests the defendants who received use immunity have had
their Fifth Amendment rights impaired in a manner that
significantly affects their right to a fair trial,'' Gesell ruled.
   ``The good faith of independent counsel cannot be questioned on
this record,'' Gesell said, adding, he was left with ``no doubt''
that Walsh followed ``a vigorous program aimed at minimizing the
exposure of himself and his prosecutorial staffs to immunized
testimony.''
   ``Given these factual circumstances, it is not difficult to
reach a preliminary decision that the case should proceed to
trial.''
   The defendants sought to have the case dismissed, or,
alternatively, a full-blown pre-trial hearing on the issue. Gesell
said the tainted testimony question could be pursued after the
Iran-Contra trials are over.
   Gesell had ordered separate trials for the four defendants
several weeks ago, to preserve a defendant's usual trial privilege
of cross-examining other defendants. This would allow the
defendants to use each other's immunized testimony.
   The defendants are charged with a broad conspiracy to carry out
a secret operation of aiding the Nicaraguan Contra rebels when such
assistance was banned by law. To do so, the grand jury charged,
they illegally used profits from arms sales to Iran authorized by
President Reagan. Some of those profits also went for personal
gain, the indictment said.
   According to Gesell, there was ``ample probable cause'' for each
count of the indictment.
   He said ``the great bulk of the evidence was clearly known'' to
Walsh before any defendant received immunity. Ironically, he said,
much of Walsh's independent evidence came from Secord, who ``went
into extraordinarily comprehensive detail'' about the case, and
provided prosecutors ``with valuable leads and other background
information for its case.''
   Gesell said the grand jurors were so keenly aware of the tainted
evidence problem that the foreman had told prosecutors jurors would
walk out of the room if immunized testimony were presented.
   Walsh has admitted in pre-trial hearings that at times he and
his staff became inadvertently exposed to media coverage of the
testimony. All such incidents were reported to one of his staffers,
whose only role was to keep a log of the 75 incidents. Only two or
three had ``any semblance of meaningful significance,'' the judge
found.
   Gesell said defendants, ``in their zeal,'' believed ``even the
tiniest exposure to a witness or grand juror constituted exposure
to an incurable disease. Such is clearly not the case. Exposure to
a fleeting snippet means nothing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
