<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-17 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Wants More Than Praise From Democrats</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: First Jackson event midafternoon EDT; may stand for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says it's fine that the
Democrats shower him with praise for his contributions to the
party, but he expects something more than accolades in return.
   He met with a roomful of Democratic senators on Thursday in
search of what he considers his fair share of so-called super
delegates for the party's convention this summer.
   But only Sen. Ernest Hollings, from Jackson's home state of
South Carolina, stood by him with a pledge to support his
presidential candidacy at the convention.
   Hollings said he would do so even though Michael Dukakis is now
the ``obvious winner'' of the party's nomination because of his
delegate majority.
   Jackson contends party leaders should support him because he has
helped them by working on voter registration, and believes he is
due a substantial share of super delegates because he came in
second in the primary contests. The super delegates are Democrats
who become delegates because of their elected or party leadership
positions.
   But Jackson emerged from the meeting with some 30 senators to
tell reporters that ``Only Sen. Hollings among the senators has
endorsed me. No Democratic state chair has, except Washington D.C.''
   Jackson was making campaign appearances today in Texas.
   He indicated Thursday he is weary of getting only verbal strokes
from the party but no delegate support.
   The ``basic party leadership while accepting my investment in
the party to make it strong has not been as reciprocal as it ought
to be,'' Jackson said.
   ``If in fact I have invested nothing in the party, I should
expect no return. If I invest, I should reasonably expect return.
   ``So I appreciate the accolades that I am the voter registration
champion for the party, that I have led the drive to return the
Senate back to the Democrats, that I have won states that no one
said I could win.
   ``If I have done all of that, then I simply say let's be fair,''
Jackson said.
   Hollings said he was urging other super delegates whose
districts or states Jackson won to follow the senator's lead ``for
the good of the party.''
   ``Coming from my home state, he won my home state, he certainly
has earned my vote'' at the convention, Hollings said.
   One senator who attended the meeting, Sen. Bob Graham of
Florida, later said he did not intend his endorsement of Dukakis to
be ``a negative reflection on Rev. Jackson'' but he saw no reason
to change any rules so that Jackson could get more delegates.
   Jackson contends his share of the super delegate total should
more closely reflect his 29 percent of the popular vote.
   As of Thursday, he had 52 of the 643 super delegates while
Dukakis had 350, according to The Associated Press tally.
   Hollings said Jackson has run ``a winning campaign'' this year
in contrast to his 1984 race when he ``frightened the bejesus'' out
of people.
   This time Jackson has not frightened anyone, Hollings said.
   ``He's charmed them in all of those different debates and in his
own right has leveled off,'' said the senator, who also sought the
presidency in 1984.
   Jackson was praised earlier Thursday by members of the Senate
Labor and Human Resources Committee. Committee Chairman Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., and other senators thanked Jackson for his years
as an outspoken leader against drugs and for his work with young
people.
   Jackson told the committee that U.S. military forces should not
be used as the primary drug interdiction force, but rather should
be used for backing up other agencies and providing intelligence.
   ``We must be careful, however, to avoid involving the military
in any police actions against citizens or arrests,'' he said. ``We
should not lead with our military forces in drugs or any other
aspect of foreign policy.''
   Later Kennedy joined Jackson at a rally outside the Capitol
denouncing South Africa as a terrorist state. Jackson urged support
for anti-apartheid legislation.
</TEXT>
