<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Haiti Bjt   06-17 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti, Bjt,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Praises Army For Accepting Civilian Supremacy Over
Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ President Leslie Manigat
congratulated the army for pledging allegiance to his government
after he apparently defused his first major power struggle with
military leaders.
   ``We are in a period of democratic apprenticeship'' and
``adjustment to a framework of civilian supremacy and
constitutional principle,'' Manigat said Thursday in a regularly
scheduled press conference.
   The president said he met for four hours Wednesday with members
of the army general staff before they issued a statement
recognizing his authority and pledging loyalty to the government.
   ``The civil power and military institution have given together .
.. a lesson in patriotism and democracy which permits us to be
optimistic,'' he said. ``I pay homage to the military for having
done their duty.''
   Manigat overruled his top army commander Wednesday by rescinding
an order transferring and retiring high-ranking officers, including
Col. Jean-Claude Paul, indicted on drug trafficking charges this
year by a grand jury in Miami.
   ``It is not a question of individuals; it is a question of
principle ... the eminently democratic principle of supremacy of
the civilian authority over the military,'' Manigat said when asked
if his decision amounted to a personal defense of Paul.
   Manigat, widely alleged to be the army's candidate in junta-run
elections last January, maintains that he rules independently from
the army.
   His decision Wednesday to rescind an order from Army
Commander-in-Chief Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy resulted in the first
crisis between Haiti's new civilian government and the military,
which has traditionally held power in this impoverished Caribbean
nation.
   Namphy had ordered Paul transferred from commander of the
700-man Dessalines Barracks, the most feared army unit in Haiti, to
assistant chief of staff, a largely administrative post. Paul
reportedly refused to accept the transfer.
   It was unclear why Namphy ordered the transfer, whether the
order signified a power struggle within the army or whether the
transfer was linked to charges of drug-running against Paul, who
has denied the charges.
   ``There is absolutely no split in the armed forces, none at
all,'' Col. Gary Leon, general secretary of the army general staff,
said in a telephone interview.
   Soldiers under Paul's command have been blamed for widespread
violence against voters that forced the cancellation of last
November's independently adminstrated general elections and left
more than 30 people dead.
   Army Chief-of-Staff Gen. Carl Nicolas denied earlier this year
that Paul was involved in drug trafficking and accused the foreign
press of singling out the 49-year-old colonel for attack.
   By rescinding Namphy's order, Manigat, the nominal
commander-in-chief of the armed forces, appeared to have sided with
Paul.
   ``The president simply said that government authority is
essentially civilian, and passed instructions to the army to
rectify certain decisions,'' said Louis Noisin, president of the
Senate. ``From a parliamentary point of view, the problem is
resolved. Now it's up to the army to do its internal house
cleaning.''
   Namphy was president of the junta that ruled Haiti from the time
Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in 1986 until Manigat took
office in February.
   Namphy and his general staff backed down Wednesday by issuing
what appeared to be a face-saving statement ``tentatively''
accepting Manigat's decision and pledging loyalty to the government.
   But it remained unclear how long the military will continue to
tolerate Manigat's interventions in military decisions.
   ``Everyone fears a standoff between the Dessalines Batallion and
other sectors of the army,'' Gregoire Eugene, leader of the Haitian
Social Christian Party, said in an interview.
   ``It is true that if Paul had been promoted to assistant chief
of staff, as is reported, he would have lost control over his
troops. The Dessalines Barracks is traditionally a key factor in
power plays,'' said Eugene, once a presidential candidate.
   When asked if the army accepts Manigat's authority as the the
nominal head of the armed forces, Leon said: ``Yes. It's written in
the constitution.''
</TEXT>
