<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TVMarti     06-17 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV Marti,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broadcasters Group Complains About Plan To Beam American TV To
Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broadcasters trade group says a Senate
proposal to beam American television programs to Cuba has become a
``political deal'' that is ignoring the concerns of American radio
and TV stations.
   The National Association of Broadcasters charges that TV Marti
advocates are trying to squelch their concerns that the proposed
government TV version of Radio Marti could interfere with U.S.
broadcasts.
   NAB officials said they were denied copies of engineering
studies on the proposed TV Marti before the Senate Appropriations
Committee voted Thursday on a spending bill that earmarks $7.5
million for the service in the 1989-90 budget of the U.S.
Information Agency.
   ``It's a political deal,'' NAB lobbyist James May said of the
committee's action on the proposal to transmit American news and
entertainment programs to Cuba from a blimp over the Florida Keys.
   The budget bill goes next to the full Senate.
   May said the NAB was rebuffed by the staff of the Senate
Appropriations subcommittee that approved the TV Marti
appropriation last week and by Stewart Sweet, who is lobbying on
behalf of TV Marti advocates.
   Sweet's Washington firm of Black, Manafort, Stone & Kelly has
links to the Republican presidential campaign of Vice President
George Bush. Charles Black, a principal of the firm, is an adviser
to the campaign.
   Bush has been a vocal supporter of TV Marti and has backed the
proposal in speeches aimed at gaining votes from the Cuban-American
community of southern Florida.
   But TV Marti is also being pushed by Democratic Sen. Ernest
Hollings of South Carolina, the Appropriations subcommittee
chairman.
   May said Sweet refused to give copies of the feasibility studies
to NAB officials because of ``national security concerns.''
   Sweet declined to comment, and when asked about his interest in
the matter said, ``I just happen to think that TV Marti is a good
idea. Let's just leave it at that.''
   Warren Kane, a Hollings staffer on the Appropriations
subcommittee, said none of the reports is classified. He said he
gave NAB on Wednesday two of six feasibility studies on the
proposal and told an NAB lobbyist he could read the other four,
including the engineering analyses, in the subcommittee's office.
   May acknowledged the offer was made but said Kane refused to
allow the NAB representative to copy the report so he could show it
to NAB engineers.
   ``This is a cover for a very disturbing process,'' May said.
   The feasibility studies were done by the Radio Marti advisory
board, headed by Jorge Mas Canosa, who also chairs the Cuban
American National Foundation. A secretary in Mas' Miami office said
he was not in Thursday afternoon and he did not return the call
seeking comment.
   May said the NAB is concerned about interference to American TV
stations in South Florida from the TV Marti signal as well as to
American AM radio stations from Cuban retaliatory jamming. Cuban
transmitters can blast a signal that would interfere with stations
in 30 states, May said.
   In addition, the TV Marti signal could be jammed easily by the
Cubans, preventing the signal from being viewed where it is
intended, he said.
   The Senate proposal includes no money to compensate U.S.
stations that are harmed by Cuban retaliation, as did the
legislation that created Radio Marti, which began broadcasting in
May 1985.
</TEXT>
