<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SEC-Harassment     06-17 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-Harassment,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Who Complained Of Sex Harassment At SEC To Get Back Pay,
Promotion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Securities and Exchange Commission lawyer
claimed victory following settlement of her 4-year-old claim that
she was threatened with dismissal for complaining of sexual
harassment in the office.
   Under terms of the settlement, approved Thursday by U.S.
District Judge John H. Pratt, attorney Catherine Broderick will
receive a promotion, back pay and compensation for psychological
counseling.
   Also as part of the settlement, the SEC agreed to hire an equal
employment opportunity expert to review current commission policies
on sexual harassment and make recommendations for any needed
changes.
   The SEC also said it would hire an impartial third party to
investigate what, if any, disciplinary action should be taken
against Ms. Broderick's former supervisors. The commission said it
would evaluate the results of the investigation and ``take
appropriate disciplinary action,'' then report its actions to the
court and to Ms. Broderick's lawyers.
   In a statement, the SEC said that it ``intends to send a strong
message that it will not tolerate employment discrimination or
harassment of any kind.''
   Ms. Broderick was smiling broadly Thursday after Pratt's action.
She said that she was ``pleased with the settlement. It's
definitely a victory.''
   Pratt ruled last month that Ms. Broderick, who worked for five
years in the SEC's Washington regional office, had suffered sexual
harassment by being forced to work in a hostile environment.
   Following Pratt's ruling, Ms. Broderick told reporters that her
former supervisors had used the office as a ``sexual playground.''
   ``The affairs were carried on at the office and flaunted in
front of other employees,'' Ms. Broderick said at the time. ``They
went out for three-hour lunches and used the office for rendezvous
after work and on weekends.''
   Pratt found that female employees who had sexual or other social
relationships with managers of the regional office's enforcement
division received promotions, positive evaluations and cash bonuses.
   But, the judge said, Ms. Broderick received negative
evaluations, threats of dismissal and eventually a transfer when
she complained.
   Under the settlement worked out by attorneys for the SEC and Ms.
Broderick and approved by Pratt, Ms. Broderick will be moved up two
steps in the federal government's salary listing and will receive
back pay based on salary increases she would have been entitled to
had she received regular promotions. The amount of back pay still
has to be calculated.
   In addition, the SEC agreed to remove any remaining negative
evaluations from her personnel files and to offer her positions in
the division of enforcement and the office of the general counsel.
The SEC also agreed to help pay for psychological counseling
sessions.
   The commission said it also had agreed to help Ms. Broderick
obtain outside employment and pay reasonable costs of out-placement
services if she should decide to look for a job outside the SEC.
   In a statement, SEC Chairman David Ruder noted that the
commission ``for many years, has been a leader in the promotion of
women in the corporate and securities field.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
