<DOCNO> AP880617-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0227EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MonogamyEvolution     06-17 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monogamy Evolution,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Suggest Animal Monogamy, Sibling Altruism Genetically
Related</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two California scientists believe that among
animals, the gene that causes siblings to help and protect each
other may be related to the gene that causes their mother to
practice monogamy.
   A mathematical model created by Marc W. Feldman and Joel R. Peck
of Stanford University and published today in Science magazine
shows a correlation between the altruism that animal brothers and
sisters show for each other and the tendency of their mothers to
mate with only one male.
   The math model suggests that altruism and monogamy ``are a good
combination that produces a situation where the individuals who
carry this combination have more offspring,'' said Feldman in a
telephone interview.
   He said the theory does not apply to humans because altruism
among humans is a learned tendency, but it does apply to animals
where the behavior is instinctive or genetically directed.
   Altruism among animals is an instinct that causes an individual
to support others in the family or group, or even sacrifice life
for the benefit of the others.
   Examples, said Feldman, are bees and wasps that will work to
feed larvae or will attack when the nest is threatened. Other
examples include elephants that will work together to protect the
young of the herd, and mountain gorillas that will defend the
family group.
   Monogamy, the tendency of a female to stay with one mate, is
common in the animal kingdom, said Feldman, and scientists have
long been puzzled how it developed.
   Mating for life occurs among some mammals, such as elephants,
among birds, such as geese and bald eagles, and even among some
fish.
   ``There isn't a very good basis in evolutionary theory for the
(development) of monogamy,'' said Feldman. ``It is a really poorly
understood phenomenon.''
   In the math model, Feldman said, he and Peck demonstrate that
``there is a correlation between the genes that cause altruism and
those that affect mating behavior.''
   He said the two behaviorial genes are linked in such a way that
``if there is a situation for genetic altruism then that is
sufficient to cause an increase in the frequency of genes that
promote monogamy.''
   In effect, said Feldman, ``if you see altruism among siblings,
it helps you to promote monogamy.''
   This, he said, produces the ``Darwinian advantage,'' a reference
to the evolutionary theory put forth by Charles Darwin in the 19th
century that the genetic charactistics that promote the most
reproductive success will tend to become the dominant
characteristics of a species.
   Feldman said his theory has never been tested in the field by
scientists who observe animal behavior, but he hopes they will now
look for evidence that may relate altruism to monogamy.
   He said monogamous birds, rodents and even primates would be
good subjects for observational scientists to test the correlation.
   Feldman is a professor of biology and director of the institute
for population and resources studies at Stanford. Peck is a
researcher in biology at the same institution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
