<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     06-17 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Empathizes With Columnist Who Shot Intruder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, an opponent of gun
control, says he empathizes with Carl Rowan, the syndicated
columnist who shot and wounded a back yard intruder, even though he
doesn't agree with his views.
   ``It's all easy to second-guess now: this was some skinny-dipper
in the Jacuzzi and all. Let others debate that one out there,''
Bush told reporters Thursday.
   Rowan, who has written columns favoring stricter gun control,
shot the trespassing teen-ager _ who had been swimming with a group
of friends in Rowan's back yard pool _ with a pistol police said
was unregistered.
   ``I kind of empathize with what he was going through when
somebody was coming at him,'' Bush said. Rowan has said he fired
the shot after the teen-ager lunged at him, and that the incident
did nothing to soften his support for strict gun control laws.
   Bush spoke with reporters on Air Force Two as he returned to
Washington from Richmond, Va., where he had given a speech on drug
abuse.
   Asked if he had any advice for Rowan, the vice president said:
``No, I don't think I have any advice for him. I'm not having much
fun out of it. I think it's a matter where I can't make much of a
contribution by saying anything....
   ``Let him think it out, sort it out. He doesn't need my
editorial help, just like sometimes I don't need his,'' Bush said.
   Bush also challenged Democrat Michael Dukakis, whom he is nearly
certain to face in the November election, to come up with a price
tag for his proposal for a buildup in conventional forces. Bush
said the Massachusetts governor's proposals could jeopardize
efforts to reach a strategic arms treaty with the Soviets.
   ``Where do you go when you get into the most expensive side of
this of all, which is conventional forces?'' the vice president
asked.
   Jim Steinberg, deputy issues director for the Dukakis campaign,
said halting the administration's Strategic Defense Initiative
would free up funds to pay for strengthening conventional defense.
   Dukakis called for the scrapping of SDI in a foreign policy and
defense speech in Washington earlier this week.
   On other matters, Bush:
   _Said he sees ``no conflict at all'' in the fact that the
lobbying firm headed by his newly named communications adviser,
James H. Lake, represents Japanese auto-parts and electronics
companies. Noting that Lake was an unsalaried volunteer, Bush said:
``Are we going to go now and look at every client for every law
firm for every volunteer?''
   _Contended he had no recollection of ever having met former
Wedtech Corp. President Anthony Guariglia, who testified at the
Wedtech corruption trial this week in New York that he sought
Bush's help as part of an effort to obtain a Navy pontoon contract
in exchange for raising $200,000 for President Reagan's 1984
re-election campaign.
   ``Was the guy ever at a fund raiser or something? Maybe. But I
don't remember anything, the name or anything about him,'' Bush
said.
   _Said he didn't favor relocating the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv
to Jerusalem, which the Israelis claim as their capital.
``Jerusalem should never be divided again, but it should be a
matter that should be part of the negotiations to bring peace to
the Middle East,'' Bush said.
   Dukakis has said he favors relocating the embassy, but later
denied saying he accepted Israel's claim to sovereignty over all of
Jerusalem.
   _Said he favors action by Congress in including a repeal of the
windfall profits tax on oil in a new stripped-down trade bill
designed to avoid another presidential veto, but still has problems
with parts of the bill ``that erode presidential power.''
   Bush was to spend today in Washington. On Saturday, he was to
visit a family farm near Springfield, Ill., and attend Republican
rallies in Springfield and in Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
