<DOCNO> AP880617-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0305EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Britain     06-17 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Britain,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Official Predicts Huge Debt Break for Poor Nations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan's Finale, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's chief financial official predicted the
leading industrialized nations will agree to grant major debt
relief to the poorest countries at an economic summit next week.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson also said Britain will
press at the seven-nation meeting for a freeze on the huge
subsidies rich countries pay their farmers.
   The official of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
government said Britain has a three-point plan for debt concessions
to help the poorest countries, mainly Africa's sub-Saharan nations.
   ``For the first time, I feel we are close to an agreement,''
Lawson said this week.
   He said resistance to major concessions to the Africans at
previous summits was based partly on fears of touching off demands
by the biggest debtors, the Latin American nations, for similar
concessions.
   ``That resistance is now crumbling,'' said Lawson. ``People do
now accept it is necessary to address the problems of these nations
(the Africans) separately.''
   Lawson's plan is one of several proposals on how to tackle the
overwhelming debts of the poorest countries. The plans will be put
forward at the June 19-21 summit of the United States, Canada,
Japan, Britain, West Germany, France and Italy.
   The British plan envisages writing off long-standing government
aid loans to the poorest countries, rescheduling other debts and
granting concessionary interest rates.
   In a separate initiative, French President Francois Mitterrand,
a Socialist, announced last week he will propose the seven nations
wipe out one-third of the debts owed to them by the poorest
countries, or slash interest rates, or extend repayment periods.
   Mrs. Thatcher has led attempts in the European Economic
Community, a 12-nation trading bloc, to curb a runaway farm budget.
   In Toronto, Britain was likely to fall in its views midway
between the United States, which has proposed eliminating farm
subsidies by the year 2000, and the other Europeans, who envisage
controls on continuing subsidies.
   Lawson said statistics showed Japan subsidized its agricultural
production by 75 percent in 1986, up from 54 percent in 1980.
   He said the European Community subsidy was 49 percent in 1986,
the latest year available, up from 36 percent in 1980, and the
United States 35 percent, up from 15 percent.
   In a television interview in Washington, U.S. Secretary of State
George Shultz said farm subsidies were costing the United States,
Western Europe and Japan $150 billion a year.
   Speaking on the U.S. Information Agency TV program ``Worldnet,''
he described the situation as ``crazy,'' and said, ``Let the market
rule.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
