<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AgFunds     06-17 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ag Funds,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$44.1 Farm Spending Blueprint Clears House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $44.1 billion blueprint for next year's farm
spending has won House approval and now is headed for the Senate,
where a slightly more expensive version is in the works.
   Urban grumbling about farm program costs preceded 343-54 House
approval of the measure, which is $2.5 billion below the
administration's request and $12 billion below this year's level.
   Complaints were less strident, though, than last year's outcry
following disclosures of million-dollar payments to huge
agribusiness concerns as part of programs supposedly designed to
rescue family farmers.
   Criticism was muted somewhat by fresh curbs imposed by Congress
on the size of individual farm payments.
   Meanwhile, expanded U.S. exports plus a revival in the farm
economy have reduced program outlays from a peak of $26 billion in
1986 to a current level estimated at about $17 billion.
   The House measure calls for outlays of $44.1 billion for the
fiscal year that starts Oct. 1. A rival measure still being
fashioned by the Senate would produce an additional $3 billion in
spending.
   Contained in the House measure are $16.3 billion for food and
nutrition programs, $12.4 billion for rural development and $6.8
billion to replace losses of the government-owned Commodity Credit
Corp., which operates USDA's price and income support programs.
   The level for covering Commodity Credit Corp. losses was $14.3
billion below the amount approved last year and represented the
major savings in the bill. Some critics said the plan appeared
overly optimistic and that a supplemental appropriation might be
needed later.
   ``It appears to me that there are lots of mirrors on the ceiling
and lots of smoke coming from the cloakroom,'' said Rep. Robert
Walker, R-Pa.
   Declines in program costs did not completely mute urban critics
of the farm program.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., complained about the Targeted
Export Assistance program, which subsidizes advertising and
promotion of U.S. farm exports. He said a report from the General
Accounting Office showed mismanagement.
   He lauded the Appropriations Committee for rejecting a proposed
increase in the program, and Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said
there would be Agriculture Committee hearings on the issue later in
the summer.
   The House spent two hours debating a proposal by Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi, R-N.Y., to bar new Farmers Home Administration loans to
borrowers already in default. In a brief parliamentary skirmish,
farm lawmakers then prevented DioGuardi from bringing the measure
to a vote.
   They received lopsided support from most of their urban
colleagues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
