<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoLibrary Bjt   06-17 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Library, Bjt,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Sponsors Competition To Build New Library</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's central library, burned down in the
great fire of 1871 and housed over the next 100 years in an old
water tank and a warehouse, will get a new $140 million home
designed in a yearlong contest.
   An 11-member committee is expected to announce Monday its choice
of one of five teams competing to design and build the Harold
Washington Library Center, honoring the city's first black mayor,
who died in November.
   The jury includes Vincent Scully of Yale University's History of
Art Department and architect Henry Cobb of the architectural firm
I.M. Pei & Partners of New York.
   Proposals for the design of the 700,000-square-foot library
range from a bold, futuristic look to a more traditional 11-story
office building.
   Inside, the library will offer international television programs
picked up by satellite, a 400-seat theater and a 2.3-million-volume
book collection.
   The Chicago Public Library Board of Directors plans to vote June
28 to accept or reject the jury's recommendation.
   Crowds have pored over the proposed models and sketches on
display in the former central library, now a cultural center.
   About 15,000 people filled out comment cards in the exhibit's
first 10 days, forcing the city to print 70,000 additional cards,
said Elizabeth Hollander, Chicago's commissioner of planning.
   She refused to reveal any of the comments, which were forwarded
to the jury. But each design has ``attracted passionate opinions
both for and against,'' she said.
   In addition to the architectural goals, the city has a practical
one. With its scheduled completion in 1991, Chicago's central
library will be adequately housed for the first time in decades.
   After the fire of 1871 destroyed the library along with most of
the city, the library was housed in an old water tank. A central
library was constructed in 1897, but it was deemed inadequate
within two decades.
   To make way for the cultural center, the city moved the central
library collection into a warehouse in 1974. Though the materials
are accessible to the public, the city doesn't consider the
facility a central library.
   A number of sites were proposed for the library _ including an
abandoned State Street department store _ and in 1986, the city
finally decided on a site in the south Loop.
   The design competition has been compared to the famed 1922
Tribune Tower contest, which drew hundreds of entries from
architects worldwide to design the home of the Chicago Tribune. But
only five teams submitted designs for the library.
   The Chicago chapter of the American Institute of Architects
blames the dirth of competitors on the contest's strict rules,
which require an architect and contractor to team up to submit
plans that include designing and building. The process is intended
to avoid cost overruns, and establishes a strict timetable for
completion.
   ``We endorse design-build competition as a process,'' said John
Syvertsen, vice president of the Chicago AIA board. But ``a
design-build competition is inappropriate for a building of this
complexity.''
   Toronto architect Arthur Erickson of the John Buck Company
developed a design that employs bold geometric shapes and a huge
outdoor plaza.
   Adrian Smith of the Chicago firm of Skidmore Owings & Merrill
designed a cube-like building that blends traditional library looks
with contemporary architecture for the Library '88 Partnership
entry.
   Chicago architect Dirk Lohan of the Metropolitan-Lohan Team also
employed a cubic style that has the look of an office building.
   Architect Helmut Jahn of Chicago designed for the
Paschen-Tishman-Jahn team a building that is elevated 80 feet, with
several structures underneath.
   Chicagoan Thomas Beeby, dean of the Yale School of Architecture,
designed a cube that is faced with brick on three sides and glass
on the fourth.
   Despite the differing designs, the jury will be concerned about
more than looks.
   ``It's like a beautiful woman,'' said Norman Ross, a former vice
president of the First National Bank of Chicago and jury chairman.
``It's nice to be attracted to what's on the outside. (But) if
you're not more concerned about what's on the inside, then you're
in trouble.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
