<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     06-17 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Warns Political Opposition Not To Interfere With Economic
Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega told domestic
critics they were ``playing with fire'' by opposing new economic
measures to heal the war-ravaged economy and warned of a crackdown
if the criticism continued.
   Ortega said Thursday that opponents of his program, which
includes a drastic devaluation of the national currency and a big
increase in the price of gasoline, ``could disappear if they don't
respond with the patriotism our country demands.''
   Ortega's leftist Sandinista government announced Wednesday a
major devaluation of the cordoba, Nicaragua's currency. One U.S.
dollar is now worth 80 cordobas at the official rate. Before the
devaluation, it was worth 13 cordobas.
   The president announced an end to government control of wages
and prices in a speech on Tuesday. He said the Nicaraguan economy
was a ``free market in a revolutionary state oriented toward
socialism.''
   The government also nearly doubled the price of gasoline on
Wednesday.
   Ortega told factory workers on Thursday that the Superior
Council of Private Enterprise, the conservative newspaper La Prensa
and opposition political parties ``were playing with fire'' in
opposing the changes.
   The government was prepared ``to strike and barricade the
political space to those who aren't in agreement with the economic
measures,'' Ortega said.
   ``We saw ourselves obligated to take measures that we did not
want to take,'' he said in explaining the reforms to the workers.
But he added the program was not ``a concession in political
ideology, nor is it a return to capitalism.''
   On Tuesday, the president said the changes were needed to spur
production and enable the economy to survive the damage inflicted
by the more than 6-year-old war with the U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   The United States has accompanied its assistance to the rebels
with severe economic sanctions against Nicaragua. The Sandinistas
say the war has caused $3 billion in damages to the economy.
   The government last enacted economic reforms in February, when
it set monthly wages at between $50 and $70 and official prices for
nearly all basic products.
</TEXT>
