<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit Spouses,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Spouses Face Busy Cultural Agenda in Toronto</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan's Finale, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While world leaders wrestle with the global
economy at next week's summit, most of their spouses will eye
designer outfits, listen to children read stories, and browse
landscape paintings.
   Many spouses will accompany leaders to the summit of seven top
industrialized nations next week in Toronto.
   Mila Mulroney, wife of Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney,
will host a welcoming dinner for spouses Sunday at the Royal
Ontario Museum in downtown Toronto. A gala fashion show will follow
with 13 top designers, including Alfred Sung and Wayne Clark, who
have created new outfits for the occasion.
   On Monday, 150 elementary school children will read stories for
the spouses in a program organized by Frontier College, a national
non-profit institution that combats illiteracy.
   In the evening, the spouses will visit one of Canada's greatest
treasures: the collection of landscape paintings by the early 20th
Century artists known as the Group of Seven. The paintings are
housed at the McMichael Gallery in Kleinburg, an hour north of
Toronto.
   The spouses join their husbands at a luncheon hosted by Canadian
Governor General Jeanne Sauve at the Art Gallery of Ontario on
Tuesday, the final day of the summit.
   Those on the guest list include Nancy Reagan; Naoko Takeshita,
wife of Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita; Anna Maria de
Mita, wife of Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco de Mita; and Hannelore
Kohl, wife of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Denis Thatcher, husband of British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, is not coming to the summit, organizers said.
   French President Francois Mitterrand's wife, Danielle, is also
staying home as is the wife of Jacques Delors, president of the
Commission of the 12-nation European Community.
</TEXT>
