<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bolivia-Drugs     06-17 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bolivia-Drugs,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Says Drug Lords Trying to Assume Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lower house of Congress accused
cocaine kingpins of trying to take over the government and called
for a united front to preserve democracy.
   The declaration was approved unanimously Thursday in response to
allegations that top government and military officials are being
paid by the drug lords.
   On Wednesday, the government closed a radio station and a
television station that broadcast a talk show with convicted
cocaine trafficker Roberto Suarez Gomez. The government accused the
stations of violating the law and of slandering the government and
the president.
   The congressional statement said, ``The international drug mafia
is not hesitating to use all its resources to dirty the honor of
(government) institutions.''
   It said cocaine traffickers are ``trying to undermine the
democratic system for the purpose of assuming political power.''
   Bolivia, a country of 6.7 million in the heart of South America,
produces a third of the cocaine that reaches U.S. and European
markets.
   In recent weeks Congress has been investigating a series of
videotaped meetings in 1985 between Suarez Gomez and a top
congressmen, a retired general and other political figures.
   A special session of Congress has been deliberating a stringent
anti-drug bill that would declare most of the country's coca
plantations illegal, but the investigation has delayed a vote on
the proposed law.
   In the first three months of this year, Bolivian police and U.S.
drug agents confiscated four tons of cocaine paste, the same amount
confiscated during all of last year.
   The U.S. government has said part of its economic assistance to
South America's poorest country depends on passing the tough drug
bill.
   Coca leaf farmers have marched and organized road blocks to
protest the proposed outlawing of coca leaf growing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
