<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Drought     06-17 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Drought,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Names Committee to Deal With Drought Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan may visit the parched
Midwest, although no such trip is yet on his public schedule,
Reagan's spokesman said after announcing an interagency panel
appointed by the president to deal with the widespread drought.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater also said he expected the drought to
be on the agenda for the seven-nation economic summit June 19-21 in
Toronto, at least for discussion with Canada and probably with
other countries as well.
   Fitzwater said the task force will ``study current federal
programs that address the situation to determine their adequacy and
effectiveness.''
   He said the task force will include Agriculture Secretary
Richard Lyng, Interior Secretary Donald Hodel and representatives
of the vice president's office, the Army Corps of Engineers, the
Energy Department, the Tennessee Valley Authority, the Office of
Management and Budget and the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   When asked if emergency assistance to drought-stricken farmers
would be expedited, Fitzwater said no decisions had been made but
the emergency management agency was included because of its role in
providing such relief.
   The group will be known as the Interagency Drought Policy
Committee.
   After making an initial report in two weeks on the immediate
situation, the group is to make an additional report in 30 days on
more long-range problems.
   ``The president is very concerned about the current drought and
wants to make certain that everything that the federal government
can do to assist will be done,'' said Fitzwater, who grew up on a
farm in Kansas.
   A spokesman for Vice President George Bush said Bush is visiting
Chicago and Springfield, Ill., on Saturday and might visit drought
areas.
   When asked if he could put the drought in a personal context
based on his own experience, Fitzwater said:
   ``There is no more hopeless or helpless feeling than seeing your
crops dry up, because there is no alleviating that disaster. If you
are a farmer and you've secured big loans for your crops, you've
borrowed money to put that seed in the ground, and you know it's
not going to yield you anything.''
   Fitzwater also spoke of a visit to Kansas at the end of May and
said, ``You could already see the wheat and corn had been stunted;
in many fields, normal wheat would be up about three feet high, and
the wheat was thin, sparse and about six inches.''
</TEXT>
