<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Fighting,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Charge Contras Kill Two Soldiers, Kidnap Civilians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels killed two government soldiers
in an ambush violating a cease-fire and kidnapped six civilians
around the country, the Defense Ministry said.
   Two army soldiers were killed and three wounded when U.S.-backed
Contra rebels attacked three army trucks in northern Jinotega
province on Wednesday, the ministry reported Thursday in a
statement.
   It said the six civilians were kidnapped in various parts of the
country but provided no details.
   The rebels made no statement about the killings or abductions.
   The leftist Sandinista government and the rebels suspended
offensive military operations on March 21, two days before they
agreed to negotiate a permanent cease-fire to the 6{-year-old civil
war.
   The latest round of talks broke down last week, and each side
has accused the other of violating the truce.
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega accused the Contras of
``flagrant violations of the cease-fire'' in a letter sent Thursday
to Joao Baena Soares, secretary-general of the Organization of
American States, and Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo,
the archbishop of Managua.
   Soares and Obando y Bravo served as witnesses to the
Sandinista-Contra peace talks and are responsible for verifying the
cease-fire accords.
   Ortega also complained that Contra leaders were seeking renewed
military aid from the United States in violation of the agreements.
   In Washington, Alfredo Cesar, a member of the Contra
directorate, told reporters Thursday the Reagan administration had
pledged to seek bipartisan Congressional support for a new military
aid package for the rebels.
   The United States has funded, equipped and trained the rebels,
who began their fight to topple the Sandinistas in 1981.
   Ortega asked Soares and Obando y Bravo to investigate the
civilian kidnappings and criticized a rebel proposal to include
President Oscar Arnulfo Arias of Costa Rica in future peace talks.
   Arias received last year's Nobel Peace Prize for writing a
Central American peace plan signed by the region's presidents in
August.
</TEXT>
