<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WelfareOverhaul-Glance     06-17 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Welfare Overhaul-Glance,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Welfare Overhaul Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a comparison of the current welfare
system and the welfare overhaul bills passed by the House and
Senate. Negotiators will reconcile differences in the two bills
before sending a measure to the White House, where it is not clear
whether President Reagan will sign it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WORK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: States are required to offer job-related services
and may develop innovative welfare approaches under the $93 million
Work Incentive (WIN) program. They also may offer job search,
subsidized jobs and community work experience or workfare. Mothers
of children over age 6 must register.
   House: Requires states to offer comprehensive education,
training and employment activities. Federal government pays 90
percent of costs up to the state's 1987 WIN allocation, 65 percent
above that. No limit on federal money available. Mothers of
children under age 3 (1 at state option) are exempt.
   Senate: Requires states to offer comprehensive education,
training and employment activities. Federal government pays 90
percent of costs up to the state's 1987 WIN allocation, above that,
60 to 80 percent depending on state benefit rate. Bill authorizes
$500 million in 1989, rising to $1 billion in 1992. Same age
requirements as House.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CHILD CARE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: States subsidize up to $160 a month for welfare
recipients earning some income; no transition coverage.
   House: Guaranteed child care for participants in education,
employment and training programs and for 12 months during the
transition into the workforce, up to $175 or $200 a month
(depending on age of child) matched at state benefit rate.
   Senate: Guaranteed child care for participants in education,
employment and training and for nine months of transition, matched
at state benefit rate up to local market rates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEDICAL ASSISTANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: Medicaid must be extended for four months when
recipient's earnings increase.
   House: No provisions.
   Senate: States must provide six months of continued Medicaid
coverage when recipients enter the workforce, and another six
months of medical assistance with a modest premium.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WORK INCENTIVES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: Benefit calculation disregards $30 of income for 12
months and one-third of remaining income for four months.
   House: Benefit calculation disregards $100 for work expenses
plus 25 percent of additional earnings, no time limit.
   Senate: Same as current law.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TWO-PARENT FAMILIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: States may give welfare benefits to two-parent
families in which the principal wage-earner is unemployed, defined
as working less than 100 hours a month. Twenty-six states do so.
   House: Mandated two-parent coverage.
   Senate: Mandated two-parent coverage, but states can limit
benefits to six months in a 12-month period.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CHILD SUPPORT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: Each state must develop guidelines for child
support award amounts. Welfare recipients are required to cooperate
with state in establishing paternity of children born out of
wedlock.
   House: Guidelines must be used in determining awards. Mandatory
wage withholding immediately upon awarding of payments. Tougher
paternity determination requirements.
   Senate: Similar to House.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BENEFIT IMPROVEMENTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   House: Higher federal matching rate for states that increase
benefits.
   Senate: Periodic re-evaluation of need and payment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMONSTRATION AUTHORITY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Current Law: Unlimited waivers of federal program requirements
allowed after strict, lengthy review process.
   House: Permits several specific demonstration projects.
   Senate: No provisions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
