<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Record High, Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange finished at a
new high for the third consecutive trading day Friday, while the
U.S. dollar weakened against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average finished the day's session at
28,342.46 points, up a sharp 195.14 points or 0.69 percent.
   The dollar ranged from 125.62 yen to 125.81 yen, before closing
the week at 125.73 yen, down 0.25 yen from Thursday's finish. The
rate was, however, higher than its opening level of 125.68 yen.
   ``The dollar weakened on overnight declines abroad and
yen-buying prompted by the release of better-than-expected figures
for the Japanese economy's growth,'' said a currency dealer at a
major commercial bank.
   On Thursday, the Japanese government reported the nation's
economy grew an inflation-adjusted 2.7 percent in the first quarter
of this year, or 11.3 percent on a real annualized basis.
</TEXT>
