<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Task Force: Take Time Making Vice Presidential Choices</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ A panel that included several former presidential
aides says presidential candidates should take their time deciding
who will be their running mates because the person who occupies
that office will be a hearbeat away from the White House.
   ``All too often you end up making the decision at 2 a.m.,'' said
James Cannon, a former aide to President Ford who contributed to
the task force report commissioned by the 20th Century Fund, a
non-profit research organization.
   On balance, the group, composed of aides to former Presidents
Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon, Ford and Carter Thursday said the vice
presidency is a healthy if imperfect institution with the incumbent
acting as an adviser to the president and as a representive of the
United States abroad.
   But three panel members, Hugh Heclo, a professor at George Mason
University in Fairfax, Va., Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr., Kennedy's
former aide, and Henry F. Reuss, former chairman of the Joint
Economic Committee, suggested the vice presidency does more harm
than good and should be abolished.
</TEXT>
