<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-Bonfires     06-17 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Bonfires,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Longest Chain of Bonfires to Circle Continent for 200th
Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Runners bearing Olympic torches will
light a chain of bonfires 10,000 miles around the continent's
coastline in a blazing tribute to Australia's bicentennial.
   Organizers said more than 750,000 Australians will be involved
Saturday in creating what they say will be the world's longest
chain of bonfires.
   ``There will also be hundreds of other fires in the outback,''
said Claudio Celiz, who originated the project. ``There is an
enormous number of other people who want to take part.''
   The fires, about 20 to 30 miles apart, will start at dusk on the
shore of Botany Bay, site of the first landing in 1788 of British
convict ships. The chain will go south to Tasmania, then back to
the mainland on a route through Melbourne, Adelaide, Perth, Darwin,
down through Brisbane and back to Sydney.
   Veliz, professor of sociology at La Trobe University, said Papua
New Guinea, Kiribati and several other South Pacific island nations
were joining the celebration by lighting bonfires of their own.
   Each beacon will be lit by runners moving in relay with an
Olympic torch. Greece will darken the Acropolis in Athens and then
floodlight it as the celebration gets under way down under, Veliz
said.
   He said organizers were seeking a listing in the Guinness Book
of World Records for the longest chain of bonfires in history and
for the the biggest single bonfire ever, a 120-foot stack to be set
alight in Dover, Tasmania.
</TEXT>
