<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-US     06-17 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-US,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kampelman Thanks Honduras for Supporting US in Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to President Reagan
thanked Honduras for its support of U.S. policy in Central America,
especially in neighboring Nicaragua.
   Max Kampelman, who also is the chief U.S. arms control
negotiator, said Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government did not
appear serious about negotiating a permanent cease-fire with
U.S.-supported Contra rebels.
   ``Let me say that the people and government of Honduras have
been extremely cooperative of this struggle for freedom and
democracy in Nicaragua,'' he said at a brief news conference after
a two-hour meeting with President Jose Azcona Hoyo.
   ``And I know that this has caused some difficulties and has been
a burden, and all of us who support democracy are appreciative of
the fine way in which Honduras has assumed that burden,'' Kampelman
said.
   The Honduran government has provided tacit support to the
Contras since they began their war to topple the Sandinista
government in 1981, including allowing the rebels to maintain base
camps in Honduran territory.
   But anti-U.S. sentiment flared after the forced extradition of
Juan Ramon Matta, an alleged drug trafficker, from his Tegucigalpa
home to the United States in April. The Honduran Constitution
forbids the extradition of Honduran nationals.
   A mob sacked and burned the U.S. consulate to protest the
incident and the presence of the Contras.
   Kampelman was accompanied by Morris Busby, on his 14th visit to
Honduras as special U.S. envoy to Central America, and other top
White House aides.
   The U.S. group met Wednesday with Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias in San Jose, that country's capital.
   Arias said he had urged both sides in the Nicaraguan conflict to
continue negotiating for a permament truce and ``a real
democratization'' in that country.
</TEXT>
