<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Students,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Stage Demonstrations At Rangoon Campus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators at the Rangoon Arts and
Science University have demanded the government release detained
students, reinstate those expelled for taking part in earlier
protests and legalize student unions.
   Beginning early this week, students have held meetings and stuck
posters outlining their demands to walls at the university's main
campus.
   The students had demanded that their requests be granted by
today.
   The authoritarian regime of military strongman Ne Win was rocked
by student demonstrations last March which Western diplomats said
may have left as many as 100 dead.
   A government panel later announced that two students were shot
by riot police and 625 were arrested. A large number of these have
since been released, the government has said.
   For most of this week, student activists, mostly masked with
handkerchiefs, have protested outside classrooms of the Arts and
Science University. Teachers persuaded them to refrain from
violence.
   Attendance at classes was scant throughout the week.
   Student-led protests have erupted periodically during Ne Win's
26 years in power.
   Student unions have been banned since July 1962 after nearly 20
students were killed and more than 40 others wounded when military
units dispersed student rioters at Rangoon Arts and Science
University.
</TEXT>
