<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Again Hit Record High, Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged to a new
high today, and the dollar weakened in trading against the Japanese
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed the week
at 28,342.46 points, up 195.14 points or 0.69 percent. It was the
Nikkei's third consecutive record high close, surpassing its
previous high of 28,147.32 points reached Thursday.
   ``Expectation is running high among investors that share prices
will rise further,'' an official at a major Tokyo securities house
said on condition of anonymity.
   Volume was a moderate 1.7 billion shares, up from 1.4 billion
shares Thursday.
   The market was led mainly by large-capital steels and heavy
industries, but buying was active and spread across many other
issues, he said.
   Advancing issues included textiles, papers and foodstuffs, while
some electricals and pharmaceuticals fell.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar finished the
week in sluggish trading at 125.73, down 0.25 yen from Thursday's
close. The rate was slightly higher than its opening of 125.68 yen.
   ``The dollar started lower on selling prompted by
higher-than-expected Japanese GNP figures. But it was stable the
rest of the day without new incentives to direct the market,'' said
a currency dealer at a major commercial bank, also speaking
privately.
   On Thursday, the government reported that the nation's economy
grew an inflation-adjusted 2.7 percent in the first quarter of this
year, or 11.3 percent on a real annualized basis.
</TEXT>
