<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Japan     06-17 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Japan,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Approves Science Pact With US For Summit Signing
^With PM-Reagan's Finale, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet today approved a science pact with the
United States to open up Japanese laboratories to American
researchers and limit the publication of joint research on
technology with possible military uses.
   The Agreement on Cooperation in Science and Technology will be
endorsed when President Reagan and Japanese Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita meet privately at the seven-nation economic summit June
20 in Toronto, said Foreign Ministry Spokesman Yoshifumi Matsuda.
   U.S. and Japanese officials finished 10 months of negotiations
with a new five-year agreement to replace a pact that was
temporarily renewed five times since it expired in 1985.
   Under the new agreement, Japan will open up its public and
private laboratories to American researchers and increase funding
for scientists and engineers coming to Japan.
   Private industry accounts for 80 percent of the funds Japan
invests in research and development, compared to 50 percent in the
United States. As a result, the U.S. government has been pushing
for more access to private laboratories where the bulk of Japanese
research takes place.
   U.S. negotiators also won a major concession in talks to renew
the pact when Japan agreed to restrict publication of sensitive
material on jointly developed technology.
   The Japanese government has come under attack for what critics
say are lax controls on exports of sensitive technology to
communist nations in violation of a Western accord.
   Last year, U.S. officials disclosed that Toshiba Machine Co., a
subsidiary of the major Japanese electronics maker Toshiba Corp.,
had been exporting submarine-silencing equipment to the Soviet
Union.
   Under the new pact, due to take effect when the current
three-month extension ends this month, both countries also agree to
protect intellectual rights and determine rights to patents arising
from joint research before the start of laboratory work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
