<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose Tightening OSHA Regulations In Wake Of Apartment
Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Connecticut lawmakers say they have
drafted a bill to toughen federal construction regulations and
increase penalties against contractors to avoid accidents like the
one that killed 28 workers in their state a year ago.
   The legislators said Thursday the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration has taken little action since the April 23, 1987
collapse of the L'Ambiance Plaza in Bridgeport, Conn., the worst
construction accident in New England history.
   ``It has been more than a year since L'Ambiance collapsed,''
said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., the chief House sponsor.
``Tragically, we have seen little movement to change any of the
factors that contributed to the accident.''
   Shays proposal would stiffen OSHA fines, tighten accident
reporting requirements, mandate a professional engineer to oversee
construction projects, make negligent employers liable to stiff
prison terms and give the agency authority to shut down a work site
to investigate an accident.
</TEXT>
