<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     06-17 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sri Lankan Official Says Peace Could be Close</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels have realized the
government has offered the best deal they can get and may soon sign
a peace accord, a Cabinet minister said today.
   The statement by Lands Minister Gamini Dissanayake added to
speculation that India and ethnic Tamil rebel leaders have agreed
in principle on a way to end the Tamils' five-year insurgency in
Sri Lanka.
   On Thursday, five people, including three policemen, were killed
in southern Sri Lanka in attacks blamed on the People's Liberation
Front.
   The group of extremists from the majority Sinhalese contends
that an agreement last year makes too many concessions to the
Tamils and has pledged to killed anyone who supports it.
   Dissanayake said today that talks between the Indian government
and Tamil separatists have reached a ``very hopeful stage'' and
could soon produce an agreement.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and Sri Lankan President
Junius R. Jayewardene signed a peace accord July 29 aimed at ending
the Tamils' guerrilla war for an independent homeland. The
agreement called for increased autonomy under regional governing
bodies.
   But the rebels rejected the pact and continued their
independence struggle. India has sent more than 50,000 troops to
the island off its southern coast to enforce the accord.
   Dissanayake, believed to be one of the authors of last year's
accord, told The Associated Press today that the rebels ``have now
realized the ... peace package offered to the Tamils under the
provincial council system of government ... is the best deal the
Tamils ever hoped to get.''
   But sources in Madras, India, who insisted on anonymity,
cautioned that several major hurdles remained.
   One Indian official said the Tamils were asking for $770,000 in
payments to help their fighters make the transition from military
to civilian life.
   The official and a Tamil rebel source, who also spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the plan has not yet been approved by
Velupillai Prabhakaran, leader of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam.
   Prabhakaran, who heads the island's strongest militia, has been
in hiding since Indian peacekeeping troops drove his men out of
their northern Jaffna Peninsula strongholds in October.
   Officials in India and Sri Lanka have said that Gandhi may fuel
progress toward a final settlement this weekend during a visit to
the southern Indian state of Tamil Nadu, whose state capital is
Madras.
   The officials say Gandhi may announce a temporary cease-fire to
allow talks on the pact to reach conclusion.
   Government officials in New Delhi have said that contacts are
under way but have declined further comment.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, claim they are discriminated against by
majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the government and
military.
   More than 8,500 people have died since the Tamil insurgency
began in 1983.
   India is involved because many of its own 60 million ethnic
Tamils are sympathetic to the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     06-17 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnapped Children Released; Palestinian Guerrillas Clash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three children of a wealthy Lebanese
jeweler were released today, three days after they were kidnapped
in Syrian-controlled Moslem west Beirut by gunmen seeking ransom
money, police said.
   It was not known whether Zuheir Ariss, owner of a plush jewelry
shop and a money exchange company, paid the $3 million that was
demanded to secure the release of his 14-year-old daughter Dana,
and two sons _ Samer, 9, and Ramzi, 5.
   A separate police report said automatic weapon clashes between
rival Palestinian guerrillas wounded seven people today, but the
exchanges in the two embattled refugee camps were markedly less
intense than those of the previous day.
   The new casualties brought the overall toll to 31 killed and 137
wounded since fighting for mastery of Chatilla and Bourj
el-Barajneh erupted last week.
   The battles pitted guerrillas loyal to Palestine Liberation
Orgnization chairman Yasser Arafat and Syrian-backed mutineers.
   A police spokesman said two Libyan observers entered Chatilla
today to join a guerrilla force drawn from factions that were not
involved in the fighting in an effort to enforce a cease-fire. Two
other Libyans were to enter Bourj el-Barajneh later in the day.
   Libya is an ally of both Arafat and Syrian President Hafez
Assad. Its leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, had played a key role in
bringing Assad and Arafat together in a reconciliation effort in
April.
   Arafat and Assad had been bitter enemies for five years, since
Syria backed a mutiny in Fatah, the PLO's mainstream faction, in
May 1983.
   Last week, Arafat's loyalists dislodged the mutineers of Col.
Saeed Mousa from the two shantytowns. Fighters of Mousa, also known
as Abu Mousa, regrouped in a Syrian-controlled area on the fringes
of the camps and mounted a counter-attack this week.
   A police spokesman said Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud, the Syrian
army's intelligence chief for the Beirut area, brought Ariss' three
children to their home at 5:30 a.m.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with police
regulations, said ``mediators'' from the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God, ``found the three children in south Beirut and
handed them over to the Syrian forces.'' He did not elaborate.
   Interior Minister Abdullah Rassi told The Associated Press that
the kidnappers ``have not been arrested.''
   ``The case is not closed. I insist that the kidnappers be
arrested, brought to justice and punished,'' Rassi said.
   Ariss, in a statement broadcast by the Moslem Voice of Nation
radio, expressed ``gratitude to all those who helped secure the
release of my children.''
   ``We thank God because this ordeal was brought to an end. We
thank God for the safe return of our three children,'' he said.
   Police chief Col. Issam Abu Ziki refused to say whether ransom
was paid.
   Six gunmen armed with silencer-equipped pistols grabbed Ariss'
children from the family car as they were being driven to school
Tuesday morning.
   Police said the kidnappers later telephoned Ariss and demanded a
$3 million ransom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
