<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Carbide     06-17 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Carbide,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Seeks Injunction Against Carbide On Settlements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India has asked the Bhopal District Court
to block Union Carbide Corp. from reaching out-of-court settlements
in the United States with victims of the 1984 gas disaster, court
officials said today.
   The request was made Thursday at a hearing that focused on a
Union Carbide request that District Judge M.W. Deo excuse himself
from the case. Deo rejected the request.
   Union Carbide, a multinational based in Danbury, Conn., will be
given an opportunity to respond to India's request at a hearing
scheduled June 29, the officials said.
   It was unclear, however, if an Indian court could issue an
injunction blocking legal agreements reached in the United States.
   The government petition said Union Carbide was considering
settlements in the United States that would undercut the
government's $3 billion lawsuit on behalf of the gas victims.
   India has passed a law making it the sole representative of the
victims.
   Nearly 3,000 people were killed and thousands were injured when
lethal methyl isocyanate leaked from a Union Carbide subsidiary's
pesticide plant in this central Indian city on Dec. 3, 1984.
   ``Many other gas victims who are plaintiffs in the courts in the
U.S.A. are seeking settlement of the claim with the Union Carbide
Corp., and the (corporation) is attempting to settle the claims for
a pittance to defeat the claim in the Bhopal court,'' the
government's petition said.
   ``If the individual plaintiffs are allowed to enter into any
compromise with the (corporation) without the consent of the Union
of India, such a compromise will be invalid.''
   The damage suit was filed in India on Sept. 5, 1986, after U.S.
District Judge John Keenan ruled four months earlier that India,
not the United States, was the proper venue for the case.
   India has accused Union Carbide of negligence in the gas leak.
Union Carbide contends the plant was sabotaged.
</TEXT>
