<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Ex-AstronautCharged     06-17 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ex-Astronaut Charged,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Astronaut Accused of Punching Bail Bondsman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former astronaut Walter Cunningham was charged
with misdemeanor assault after punching a man at a traffic light
and speeding away, authorities said.
   Van Vannerson, a bail bondsman, filed a complaint claiming
Cunningham pulled up next to him Tuesday, made an obscene gesture
and cursed him before speeding away.
   Vannerson said he later pulled his Rolls-Royce behind
Cunningham's Porsche at a traffic light and said Cunningham jumped
out, punched him in the chin through his open window, then sped off.
   Cunningham has been romantically linked with Vannerson's
estranged wife, Dot, said the former astronaut's attorney, Michael
Leebron.
   Leebron denied Cunningham made obscene gestures to Vannerson and
contended the only contact between the two men occurred after
Vannerson's car hit Cunningham's car near the attorney's office.
   ``Walt is very despondent about all this,'' Leebron said. ``He
was arrested for an assault ... that never happened.''
   Sheriff's deputies on Wednesday picked up Cunningham at his
office on the misdemeanor assault charge. He was released on his
own recognizance.
   Cunningham, who flew aboard Apollo 7 in 1968 and is now managing
general partner of a capital venture firm, is suing his wife, Lo,
for divorce. Vannerson's wife is suing Vannerson for divorce.
   Cunningham has been romantically involved with Mrs. Vannerson,
according to Leebron, who said Vannerson is making a mistake in
assuming that Cunningham stole his wife.
   ``It's really a love story,'' he said of Cunningham and Mrs.
Vannerson.
