<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Boston-HousingDeseg     06-17 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boston-Housing Deseg,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Group Will Pursue Lawsuit Despite Boston Fair Housing
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights group says it will pursue a lawsuit
against the city despite the unveiling of a new plan to desegregate
about 17,000 public housing units in 69 developments operated by
the Boston Housing Authority.
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
filed the suit seeking to stop the administration of Mayor Raymond
L. Flynn from engaging in discriminatory housing practices.
   On Thursday, Flynn announced an agreement with the federal
Department of Housing and Urban Development to integrate the city's
public housing and find apartments for anyone who was the victim of
discrimination in the past five years.
   Despite the announcement, the Lawyer's Committee for Civil
Rights, which is handling the suit for the NAACP, plans to pursue
the case, said attorney Alan Rom, because some victims of
discrimination deserve monetary damages as well as immediate
housing.
   ``However much may have been remedied by that plan, there's
still plenty left over,'' Rom said. ``This (agreement) is not
sufficient to make whole the people who were injured by the acts of
discrimination.''
   The agreement between Flynn, the Boston Housing Authority and
HUD follows an October 1987 HUD report that found a clear pattern
of steering whites to white housing projects and isolating blacks
and other minorities in projects where their own race predominated.
   The proposal has drawn sharp responses from white neighborhoods
and civil rights groups. But the furor comes nowhere near the
tension that gripped the city in the mid-1970s, when Boston began
busing students under a court-ordered school desegregation plan.
   Flynn touched on the federal school desegregation case at a news
conference Thursday.
   ``This agreement is designed to ensure fair and equal access for
public housing throughout Boston,'' Flynn said. ``It is intended to
keep decision-making at the local level and away from a federal
court.''
   Flynn lives in the South Boston section of the city, a
predominantly white neighborhood that was the scene of racial
violence during the school desegregation years. His neighbors have
criticized him severely for his support of desegregated public
housing.
   ``I am asking the people of Boston for their personal support,''
Flynn said.
   Under the agreement, the housing authority would identify people
who have been victims of discriminatory public housing practices
and place them near the top of the priority housing list. Only
emergency cases, such as a family on the verge of homelessness,
would receive a higher priority for receiving a unit.
   Anyone passed over because of race or national origin since Oct.
1, 1983, would be considered such a victim.
   Flynn emphasized that no current resident of public housing
would be forced to move as a result of the agreement.
   Boston's housing authority is the largest in the country to
enter into an agreement to voluntarily comply with fair public
housing practices, said Robert LaPlante, HUD's regional director
for fair housing.
   A second key aspect of the plan requires HUD approval. It calls
for the housing authority to offer housing applicants a choice of
apartments from a citywide list or from an individual project. If
HUD rejects that system, the authority would have to use a
HUD-developed plan in which there would be no opportunity for an
applicant to specify a housing development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0078 </DOCNO>
