<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     06-17 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Mother's Body Arrives At Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARRAT, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Ferdinand Marcos
supporters today thronged the streets to pay respects to the ousted
president's mother when her body arrived in the Marcos' hometown 44
days after her death.
   Since Josefa Edralin-Marcos died in a Manila hospital at the age
of 95, her body has become a rallying point for Marcos supporters
who want the government to allow Marcos to return from exile to
bury her.
   President Corazon Aquino, who is traveling in Europe, has
refused to allow him to return for security reasons.
   No burial date has been set for Mrs. Edralin-Marcos, who died
May 4.
   About 10,000 people welcomed the cortege as it entered this
sleepy town in Ilocos Norte province, 250 miles north of Manila.
Thousands more lined the 50-mile route from Vigan, where the body
stayed overnight, and chanted Marcos' name as the cortege passed.
   The cortege left Manila on Wednesday after a five-hour march by
thousands of Marcos supporters who shouted slogans demanding their
leader be allowed to return.
   Marcos fled to Hawaii during the February 1986 civilian-military
revolt that ended his 20-year rule and swept Mrs. Aquino to power.
   Many among the crowds in Sarrat, especially older people, wept
as the province's two congressmen, several town mayors and the
provincial governor carried Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' casket from the
hearse to the living room of her former home, a two-story
Spanish-style house.
   Marcos turned the house into a museum, and the bed where he was
born 70 years ago is the main attraction.
   Original plans called for Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' body to lie in
state in Sarrat, where she was born, for two days. But Marcos'
sister, Fortuna Marcos-Barba, said Wednesday that it may stay there
a week.
   The body was then to be transferred to the provincial capital,
Laoag, where it was to be kept for a day before being moved to the
nearby town of Batac for burial at an undetermined date. Mrs.
Edralin-Marcos raised her family in Batac.
</TEXT>
