<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireTestDeath     06-17 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Test Death,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Dies After Taking Endurance Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fire Department has suspended giving its
physical endurance test to aspiring firefighters after a man died
and eight others collapsed while taking it on a warm afternoon, a
newspaper reported today.
   Department officials would not release the name of the dead
24-year-old man, who collapsed Saturday after taking the test at
the New York Coliseum, the New York Post reported in today's
editions.
   None of the eight others was seriously injured, according to
department personnel spokeswoman Margaret Gandasegui.
   ``When several (recruits) became ill after taking the test and
had to be taken to the hospital and one subsequently died, it was
decided that we would suspend'' the test, she said. ``We're going
to take a day to compile all the facts and review everything.''
   Candidates are required to wear 40 pounds of gear as they scale
walls, carry a 145-pound dummy, break down a door and drag 400
pounds of hose.
   ``It's a simulation of the job and really should only be
attempted by those who are physically or medically fit,'' Ms.
Gandasegui said.
   The cancellation affects roughly 500 would-be firefighters who
have already passed the written test but were told Thursday they
would have to wait to go through the physical endurance test.
</TEXT>
