<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0487,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Foreign Minister To Parley With Three Cambodian Rebel
Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details and quotes. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of
Vietnam said today he would meet with representatives from
Cambodian rebel groups in talks aimed at ending the 10-year-old
civil war in Cambodia.
   Vietnam has said before it would send a representative to the
informal talks beginning July 25 in Jakarta, Indonesia, but this
was the first announcement that Thach himself would be going.
   ``There is no doubt that I will be there,'' Thach told a news
conference.
   Thach and his Thai counterpart, Siddhi Savetsila, also said the
United States and the Soviet Union should act as guarantors of any
agreement to end the conflict.
   Thach and Savetsila held separate news conferences after a
45-minute meeting today. On Thursday, they held their first talks
since July 1986.
   They reportedly discussed Vietnam's plans to withdraw 50,000
Vietnamese troops from Cambodia, the problem of Vietnamese refugees
and the danger that the Khmer Rouge may return to power if Vietnam
pulls all its troops out of Cambodia.
   Thailand, along with the United States and China, backs a
three-party guerrilla coalition fighting the Vietnamese in
Cambodia. The three are the ultra-radical Khmer Rouge, the
Western-leaning Khmer People's National Liberation Front and
followers of Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Vietnam, backed by the Soviet Union, invaded Cambodia in late
1978, driving the pro-Chinese Khmer Rouge from power. The Khmer
Rouge killed millions of people during its attempt to impose
radical agrarian communism on Cambodia after it took over in 1975.
   Hanoi has promised to pull out all its forces, currently
estimated at 120,000, by 1990. The partial withdrawal of 50,000
troops is scheduled to begin June 30 and continue through the rest
of the year.
   Thach said representation at the Jakarta talks would include the
pro-Hanoi government in Cambodia under President Heng Samrin.
   He said Sihanouk, Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan and
liberation front head Son Sann would attend.
   Although the format has yet to be clearly spelled out, the four
Cambodian factions are to meet first. Other parties, such as
Vietnam, Laos and Southeast Asian countries opposed to Vietnam's
occupation of Cambodia, will join at later stages of the
discussions.
   Siddhi said Thailand would not send a representative to the
meeting and would instead wait until ``the initial meeting has
firmed up to some kind of political settlement.''
   Thach praised the informal structure of the upcoming meeting and
compared it to a cocktail party.
   ``In a cocktail party there is no fixed chair for anyone so we
can move freely. I hope for the best,'' Thach said when asked
whether he would prefer to meet any particular member of the
anti-Vietnamese coalition.
   He urged full support for the talks. ``If others are not in a
hurry they'll miss the train. And missing the train is not a happy
thing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0082 </DOCNO>
