<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with gold, silver prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned in a mixed performance in
moderately active European trading early today, while gold bullion
fell.
   Dealers said that closure of banks and financial markets in West
Germany for a national holiday and a lack of commercial orders
curtailed activity on European markets. They expected no major
changes in dollar rates through the session.
   Traders in Italy said the dollar's advance on the coattails of
surprisingly good U.S. April trade figures had been definitively
halted by fears of central bank intervention and the possibility
that West Germany or Japan might raise interest rates.
   Mid-morning dollar rates in Europe compared with late Thursday:
   _ 1.7509 West German marks, up from 1.7505
   _ 1.4555 Swiss francs, down from 1.4580
   _ 5.9050 French francs, up from 5.9005
   _ 1.9684 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9650
   _ 1,300.50 Italian lire, up from 1,299.50
   _ 1.2133 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2160
   The British pound fell to $1.7815 from $1.7900.
   In Tokyo, the dollar weakened against the Japanese yen, closing
at 125.73 Japanese yen, down from 125.98 yen. In London trading
later today, the dollar traded at 125.65 yen.
   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price of
$449.80 a troy ounce, down from $452.80 late Thursday.
   Gold was bid in Zurich at $450.40, down from $452.50.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $452.15, down from
$454.52.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $7.11 a troy ounce,
down from $7.21.
