<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-17 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Dampen Many Parts Of The Nation As Heat Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms dampened many parts of the nation
today after storms produced large hail and high winds as a heat
wave continued elsewhere.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed early today along a cold
front from Maine to the middle Atlantic Coast and the upper Ohio
Valley.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed along the same cold front
over western Oklahoma and north-central Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed along a cold front
crossing Idaho and eastern Oregon, while storms continued over
southern South Dakota and northern Nebraska.
   On Thursday, the heat wave continued in many parts of the
nation, with readings in the low to mid-90s from the lower
Mississippi and Tennessee valleys through central Virginia,
northern New Jersey and into New England.
   But cooler weather prevailed from the northern Plains into the
upper Great Lakes. Readings were in the 70s across much of the
region with temperatures in the 50s and 60s across northern
Minnesota and Michigan.
   The high for the nation Thursday was 114 at Buckeye, Ariz.
   Rain fell Thursday in drought-stricken sections of the nation
but provided little relief from the dry spell that is wilting
crops, stranding hundreds of river barges and endangering cattle.
   Strong thunderstorms Thursday in the middle Missouri Valley
produced severe weather in South Dakota, including golf ball-size
hail and 2{ inches of rain near Winner, and strong winds that blew
the roof off a mobile home at Butte.
   A few showers fell over southern and central Minnesota.
   Scattered thunderstorms produced high winds Thursday night in
parts of Utah. Wind gusted to 42 mph at Cedar City and 67 mph
during a thunderstorm near Delta.
   Heavier rainfall for the six-hour period ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included 1 1@3 inches at Wichita Falls, Texas, and three-quarters
of an inch at Roanoke, Va.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from New England to the Middle Atlantic States, the Tennessee
Valley and the lower Mississippi Valley to southeast Texas; widely
scattered thunderstorms in the afternoon and evening in the
mountains of the West and in western portions of the central and
southern Plains; a few showers and thunderstorms from the upper
Mississippi Valley across western Iowa to eastern Kansas; and
showers and thunderstorms widely scattered over southern Florida.
   Highs were forecast in the 80s to mid-90s across much of the
nation, except in the 60s or 70s along the Pacific Coast; the 70s
from the Great Lakes region to the northern Atlantic Coast states;
95 to about 100 over western portions of the northern Plains,
southwest Idaho, portions of Utah, southwest Texas and southern New
Mexico; and 100-114 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 34 at
Marquette, Mich., to 96 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 78 cloudy; Boston 65 hazy; Buffalo 54 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 65 foggy; Cincinnati 66 foggy; Cleveland 55 fair;
