<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     06-17 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>19 Killed In Clash Between Troops And Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAGAYAN DE ORO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops fought
communist rebels for two hours in the southern Philippines, and 12
rebels and seven soldiers were killed, a military spokesman said
today.
   Lt. Col. Edgar Centino, spokesman for the 4th Infantry Division,
said government troops claimed they saw a white man acting as a
``military consultant'' to the insurgents during the battle
Thursday in Surigao del Sur province.
   Centino said 15 rebels and six soldiers were wounded in the
fighting, which began when troops on patrol spotted a rebel camp
near the mountain village of Diatagon, 540 miles southeast of
Manila.
   He said the soldiers fired mortar rockets onto the camp, which
was estimated to house 70 New People's Army guerrillas, and the
rebels fought back.
   The rebels belonged to a guerrilla unit led by Francisco
Navarro, a defrocked Roman Catholic priest, but the military did
not know if he was in the camp during the battle, Centino said.
   He said the troops also did not elaborate exactly what the
Caucasian ``military consultant'' was doing.
   ``Our soldiers were not certain of the nationality of the
Caucasian, but they insist he was a foreigner,'' Centino said.
   The report comes at a time of growing claims by the military
that foreigners are helping train the rebels and taking part in
raids on military detachments and other government installations.
   Last week, the military arrested a Swede and a West German on
charges they were seen taking part in a rebel raid on the town of
San Francisco on Luzon island's Quezon province last February.
   The two, Stellan Hermansson, president of the Swedish Young
Communist League, and Klaus Schmidt, a Protestant minister, have
denied the charges.
</TEXT>
