<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-17 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida Power & Light Co. is asking customers with
dogs whether their pets' tastes include meter readers in a
high-tech effort to keep those workers in one piece.
   Questionnaires on dogs have been mailed out with this month's
power bills.
   ``We just want to know which ones are dangerous,'' John Centore,
a Dade County supervisor of 20 of Florida Power & Light's 130 meter
readers, said recently.
   Each meter reader will be equipped with a hand-held computer
containing the information from dog owners and other meter readers.
When a reader approaches a house with a protective pooch, the
computer will flash a ``dog alert'' on its screen and beep.
   The utility has already received some dog surveys back, like the
one for two pit bulls named Clint and Lady that claimed they ``will
chew your legs off up to your butt.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fund-raising project is offering ties
that are only $2.50 apiece, but Dad would have a hard time wearing
one on Father's Day.
   Business and government leaders attempting to resurrect a
vintage railroad line between three southern Saginaw County towns
are ``selling'' 1,100 ties needed to repair parts of track in order
to raise money for the project.
   Purchasers don't actually get a tie, just the knowledge that
they've helped revive the 20-mile line between Chesaning, St.
Charles and Owosso.
   Organizers hope to have the line, complete with a steam
locomotive and cars with space for up to 400 passengers, running on
Labor Day weekend.
   ``It will bring gifts of American history, nostalgia and
mystery,'' said St. Charles Manager Thomas Barwin. ``It is quite a
trip back into time.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials are putting together a
$235,000 museum that will pay tribute to one of the most important
things in Kalamazoo County history _ celery.
   ``Celery really kind of put Kalamazoo on the map,'' said
Michigan historian Larry Massie. ``From 1890 until the 1920s, the
Kalamazoo area was one of the world leaders in the production of
celery.''
   Dutch settlers began growing celery in Kalamazoo in the early
19th century, and their success spurred celery farms in Portage,
Massie said.
   However, in the 1930s celery farming gave way to paper mills.
   Work on the museum, called the Celery Flats Interpretive Center,
is scheduled to begin in August, and is to be completed by April
1989.
   The museum will offer historic and working displays on celery
farming. Portage officials said they have gathered enough artifacts
for the center but are looking for more objects, such as celery
washers and railroad carts.
   ``It's been difficult finding items because it (celery farming)
happened so long ago and no one locally has a good collection of
artifacts,'' Clifford Mulder, an assistant to Portage City Manager
Michael Stampfler said recently.
   The project was made possible by a $100,000 grant from
Kalamazoo-based Upjohn Co.; a $100,000 donation from the Kalamazoo
Foundation; and a $25,000 grant from the state.
</TEXT>
