<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Dien     06-17 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Dien,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Who Defied Communists Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese Archbishop Philippe Nguyen
Kim Dien, who defied communist attempts to control his country's
Roman Catholic Church, has died. He was 67.
   The official Vietnam News Agency, in a report monitored in
Bangkok today, said Dien died of an illness on June 8 at Cho Ray
Hospital in Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon. It did not give the
exact disease.
   Dien was barred from work as a priest and put under house arrest
in 1984 for urging priests not to join the Committee for Solidarity
of Patriotic Vietnamese Catholics. The state had formed the group
the previous year, and critics said it was designed to control the
church.
   The clergyman spent his last years under house arrest. Dien
continued to circulate letters among his parishioners, however, and
authorities apparently made no serious attempt to replace him.
   In 1986, cardinals and bishops from 40 countries issued a
protest letter when Vietnam barred Dien from traveling to Rome to
attend the Vatican's Congregation for the Evangelization of Peoples.
   The Vatican said Kim was born in March 1921 in Vinh Long. The
city was a traditional center of the Catholic Church in the Mekong
River Delta in southern Vietnam.
   He was ordained in July 1947 and became a bishop in 1961, the
Vatican said. The Vatican, Vietnamese refugees and other sources
charge that after the communists came to power in 1975, they closed
seminaries, jailed priests and took other steps to systematically
repress the Catholic Church. Catholicism was identified with French
colonialism and the U.S.-backed South Vietnam government of the
Vietnam War era.
   Authorities have made some steps toward reconciliation since
pragmatist Nguyen Van Linh became Communist Party chief in December
1986.
   There are 4-5 million Catholics among Vietnam's largely Buddhist
population of about 63 million.
   A Vatican spokesman said today the Vatican has sent a telegram
to Cardinal Trinh Van Can, archbishop of Hanoi, saying that Pope
John Paul II praised Dien for his courage. The telegram was signed
by Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, Vatican secretary of state.
   ``The Holy Father joins in the sorrow of the bishops and of all
the Catholic community in Vietnam,'' the telegram said. ``He
commends to the Lord the courageous pastor who faithfully testified
the Gospel in a life of untiring service for the people of God.''
   A memorial service for Dien was held Monday in Hue, where Dien
was archbishop. The Ho Chi Minh City archbishop, Nguyen Van Binh,
held a funeral service in the city two days later.
   Communist Party and government officials involved with religious
affairs attended the services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
