<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Paraguayan     06-17 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Paraguayan,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Paraguayan Army Captain Receives Aslym in Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Paraguayan former army captain described
by human rights groups as one of Latin America's longest-held
political prisoners arrived in Madrid today to receive political
asylum.
   Napoleon Ortigoza, 56, was freed last December after serving a
25-year prison term in the 1962 slaying of army cadet Alberto
Benitez.
   He had been under house arrest since his release, but was
allowed to leave Wednesday for Argentina after spending 83 days in
the Colombian embassy in Asuncion, the Paraguayan capital.
   The Paraguayan Human Rights Commission had long demanded
Ortigoza's release, claiming his imprisonment was a flagrant
violation of the law and that he was frequently subjected to
torture.
   Both Spain and Colombia had offered him asylum.
   On Wednesday, the Paraguayan government granted Ortigoza a
safe-conduct pass to Argentina. From Buenos Aires, he flew to
Madrid.
   Ortigoza told reporters at Madrid's Barajas Airport that the
prison sentence he received was ``arbitrary and political.'' He
denied any involvement in the killing.
   At the time of his 1962 conviction, it was reported that the
cadet had uncovered a plot by Ortigoza and two other men to
overthrow President Alfredo Stroessner, 75, who has ruled Paraguay
with an iron fist since 1954.
   ``The accusation against me in the killing of Cadet Benitez was
just a pretext for setting off a chain of arrests of 20 military
officers, including me, who were opposed to military men being
involved in political activities,'' Ortigoza told reporters.
   Ortigoza said he expected to be joined soon in Madrid by his
wife, a daughter and her husband, who are in Asuncion. He has said
he hopes to work with international human rights groups.
</TEXT>
