<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan-Islam     06-17 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Islam,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Balks at Decree on Islamic Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Benazir Bhutto
denounced a presidential decree imposing Islamic law and said Islam
was being used to oppress the people of Pakistan.
   President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq put the law, known as Shariah,
into effect Wednesday night in a televised address to the nation.
   The decree makes Islam ``the supreme law of Pakistan'' but will
not affect the rights of non-Moslems or the country's business
contracts with other nations, Zia said.
   Ms. Bhutto, leader of the Pakistan People's Party, said Zia had
``no right to impose his will on the people of Pakistan,''
according to a report today in the English-language Daily Muslim.
   ``Islam, like in the past, is again being used to perpetuate
oppressive rule,'' she was quoted as telling journalists Wednesday.
   ``We believe it is not the business of a caretaker government or
an individual to impose their views on the nation,'' Ms. Bhutto
said. ``Like in the past, we will resist any such move.''
   Zia, who also is chief of the army, fired his entire civilian
government May 29 and dissolved the national assembly.
   He claimed that in three years in power, they failed to enact
the Islamic code and to battle deteriorating law and order.
   Zia hinted that elections would be announced within 90 days but
has yet to set a date.
   Zia ousted Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, in a 1977 military coup and had him hanged two years later
for complicity in a murder plot.
   After ruling eight years under martial law, Zia allowed a
civilian government to form in 1985.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, repeated her call for free elections and denied
reports that her advancing pregnancy would prevent her from
preaching the party's platform of popular socialism.
   She was married to Karachi businessman Asif Zardari last
December and is expecting her first child in December.
</TEXT>
