<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupermanExpo     06-17 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superman Expo,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Superman Exposition Honors Man of Steel's 50th
Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wonder Woman, Luke Skywalker, Sherlock Holmes
and even Rocky and Bullwinkle are taking a break from their
adventures this weekend to help celebrate Superman's 50th birthday.
   A four-day International Superman Exposition opened Thursday and
was expected to attract up to 30,000 visitors. Although fans know
the Man of Steel was born on the planet Krypton, Superman has
strong ties to this city _ he was created by Clevelanders Jerry
Siegel and Joe Shuster.
   Superhero devotees have come to browse through comic books,
watch science fiction movies, and shop for memorabilia ranging from
dinosaur dolls to rare Superman prints, said Tim Gorman of
Neverending Battle Inc., which is sponsoring the event.
   Gorman said the non-profit organization was founded in 1986 to
honor Siegel and Shuster. The two men, graduates of Glenville High
School, created the material for the first Superman comic book in
June 1938.
   A copy of that book could bring more than $1,000, depending on
its condition, said Randy Poling, operator of Collector's Warehouse
in Cleveland.
   On Thursday, Gorman unveiled a 2-foot-high shining steel model
of Superman in flight, right fist thrust high in a familiar pose.
The organization plans to raise enough money to build a larger
statue and a museum in Cleveland.
   Robb Jackson came to the exposition with Starfleet, a national
organization dedicated to the much-syndicated television show
``Star Trek.'' But don't call him a Trekkie.
   ``Trekkies are more fanatical; we prefer to consider ourselves
Trekkers,'' said Jackson. He works as a police officer for Clinton
Township when he isn't wearing his uniform as Starfleet deputy
commander of the Ohio region's marine division.
   ``It's a little insanity that keeps me sane,'' said Jackson.
   Jeffrey White of Athens, Ohio, a founder of the Southeastern
Ohio Science Fiction Society, said he took time off from his job at
the Kroger Co. to attend the exposition. He said he particularly
likes role-playing games and Dr. Who, the mysterious British time
lord with two hearts, seen in 38 countries on television.
   The exposition ends Sunday with reruns of Superman television
shows.
</TEXT>
