<2ND_LINE>PM-Transplant Campers,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kentucky Woman Gets Liver Transplant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who lived with her family in a pickup
truck camper for five days while awaiting a liver transplant was in
critical condition today after the 12-hour operation.
   Pollie Smolenski, 26, of Hallie, Ky., received the transplant
Thursday, three days after authorities moved her into a donated
apartment.
   ``Doctors are cautiously optimistic,'' said Susan Ruth,
spokeswoman for Presbyterian-University Hospital. ``The family is
ecstatic. They are so relieved she's out of surgery and everything
went well.''
   Mrs. Smolenski suffered from primary biliary cirrhosis, an
irreversible disease caused by an accumulation of bile. She was
admitted to the hospital Wednesday morning.
   Mrs. Smolenski and her parents, Raymond and Ersley Eldrigge,
lived for five days in the camper atop their pickup, parked in a
lot on the University of Pittsburgh campus. Mrs. Smolenski's three
children remained at home with their father, who had to quit his
job in a coal mine to care for them.
   By Sunday the three were down to their last $150 and were living
on handouts from police. Campus police Officer Jesse Long reported
their plight to university officials, who housed the family in a
dormitory Sunday night.
   Sympathetic officials at National Development Corp. moved the
family into a luxury apartment Monday, saying they could stay there
as long as necessary.
</TEXT>
