<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0525 06-17 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0525,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede JERUASALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>One Dead As Army Cracks Down On Firebombers, Demolishes Houses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with more wounded, quotes from
witness, details of clash. PICKS up 15th graf pvs, ``The death
...'' Minor editing throughout to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops killed a
Palestinian and wounded 18 others today when a mob of rock-hurling
Arabs tried stop soldiers from blowing up a house in the occupied
West Bank, a hospital official said.
   The army said only five Palestinians were wounded and that two
Israeli officers also were injured by stones in violence that began
when troops entered the village of Beit Furik to demolish a house.
   A military spokesman said the army was checking on reports of a
fatality and others wounded.
   Throughout the West Bank, Israeli troops destroyed more Arab
homes overnight, bringing to 18 the number demolished or sealed in
the last 24 hours in the army's campaign to stop youths from
throwing firebombs, the army said.
   At least four of the homes belonged to alleged firebombers, the
army said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the army considered
firebombs lethal weapons and that soldiers and civilians could
respond with gunfire when firebombs were thrown.
   ``We define it as a weapon and the action against the throwers
is as if they used weapons,'' he said on Israel radio. ``Those
self-defense orders also include Israeli citizens traveling on the
roads.''
   In Beit Furik, a village five miles southeast of Nablus,
soldiers opened fire when Palestinians attacked with rocks and
bottles, said an official at Ittihad Hospital in Nablus. The
official said the troops later blew up an Arab home.
   The soldiers entered the village before dawn to destroy the home
of Ahmed Hanani, allegedly a member of a gang which killed Nablus
Mayor Zafer al-Masri in March 1986 and carried out attacks against
Israelis, the army said.
   Palestinians saw the approaching soldiers and alerted villagers,
and about 700 Arabs gathered in the streets and began throwing
stones as about 100 soldiers entered, said villager Rafaq Yusef
Masmoud, 25.
   The soldiers opened fire and the street battle lasted for about
four hours, Masmoud told The Associated Press from a bed at Nablus'
Al Ittihad Hospital, where he was being treated for gunshot wound
to his left leg.
   Masmoud said he saw about 20 villagers being detained, but the
army put the arrests at five.
   In addition to the wounded Arabs, two Israeli officers were
injured, the army spokesman said, adding that their condition was
not immediately known.
   The force opened fire ``when it was in a life-threatening
situation,'' the spokesman said.
   The dead man, identified as 24-year-old Tayseer Mlaitat, was
shot in the chest, said the hospital official.
   Of the 18 other Arabs wounded by gunfire, at least two were in
serious condition, the hospital said, adding that three others were
injured by rubber bullets and beatings.
   
   The death brings to 209 the number of Palestinians killed since
the Arab uprising began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Two
Israelis also have died, including a teen-age girl accidentally
shot by a Jewish guard during a clash with Palestinian villagers.
   Rabin, in his radio interview, said the uprising was widespread
and supported by a majority of the 1.5 million Palestinians in the
occupied lands.
   Rabin said the army's actions were now aimed at preventing a
return to the widespread, violent protests that characterized the
early stages of the Arab revolt. Lately, the uprising has consisted
mostly of commercial strikes, fires blamed on Palestinian arsonists
and clashes between soldiers and stone-throwing youths.
   The army said eight homes were destroyed and 10 sealed in the
West Bank in 24 hours ending this morning. Most of the houses
belonged to Arabs suspected of hurling firebombs or planning
attacks against Israelis, but two belonged to alleged members of a
gang suspected of killing al-Masri, a spokesman said.
   ``I have eight children at home and now they want to throw me to
the street ... because my son made a firebomb,'' one homeowner,
identified only as the father of Omad Mahmoud Shalabiye, said on
Israel radio. ``I don't know what he does. He's 18 years old.''
   On Thursday, a 33-year-old woman was severely injured in the eye
by a rock hurled at her train as it passed through Acre, a town
where many Arab Israelis live, Israel radio said.
   Four Bedouins were arrested in the stoning, the radio said. But
it quoted Galilee police chief Yakov Ganot as saying he was
uncertain if the motive was nationalistic or criminal.
   The city of Nablus remained under curfew today, a day after an
Israeli soldier was shot and slightly wounded by an unidentified
assailant.
</TEXT>
