<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0451 06-17 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He'd Provide Police ``Leadership From the Top''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis crime comments, flag ceremony in top 11
grafs, picking up in 5th graf pvs, But Democrats</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, talking tough on crime,
told police recruits today that as president he would ``provide you
with the kind of leadership you must have from the top.''
   Dukakis, on a Southern campaign swing challenging George Bush's
claim to support in the region, also received the backing of a
group of law enforcement officials that included the Democratic
attorneys general of Florida, California, Louisiana and Michigan.
   Meeting with the group, which also included police chiefs,
sheriffs, district attorneys and members of private anti-crime
organizations, Dukakis outlined his plan for a national crime
council patterned after the stte council he formed in Massachusetts.
   He began his day at the flag-raising ceremony at the Southeast
Florida Institute of Criminal Justice.
   It provided a symbolic response to criticism from the Bush
campaign of his veto, a decade ago, of legislation that would have
required the recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance to the flag in
Massachusetts schools.
   Dukakis vetoed the bill after the state supreme court advised
him it was unconstitutional.
   Bush has begun raising the veto and saying he favors recitation
of the pledge ``anywhere and everywhere.''
   Dukakis told the police trainees they would be leading the fight
to ``provide all Americans with the kind of safety and security
they're entitled to have in their homes and in their communities
and in their neighborhoods.''
   He said, ``I'm going to do everything I can to provide you with
the kind of leadership you must have from the top ... to provide
you with the support and the resources and the training you need.
   Dukakis opened a his three-day Southern campaign swing on
Thursday and talked about drugs with high school students in South
Carolina. He planned to continue sounding that theme in an
appearance before Mississippi municipal officials.
   No region of the country backed Republican President Reagan more
solidly than the South, and his vice president hopes to capitalize
on that popularity in the fall presidential campaign.
   But Democrats see it differently.
   ``Anybody who thinks George Bush has the kind of appeal Ronald
Reagan had in the South is going to be sadly mistaken,'' Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said Thursday as he endorsed Dukakis for the
presidency.
   Gore, who dropped his bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination last April after his disappointing finish in the New
York primary, predicted Dukakis would carry five or six Southern
states.
   ``The kind of candidacy Mike Dukakis brings to the South today
is very different from what Republicans were licking their chops
over early in the campaign,'' said Gore. ``They know now they have
their hands full.''
   A new survey by Atlanta pollster Claibourne Darden appeared to
support Gore's assessment.
   Darden's poll of 750 voters in nine Southern states said 45.1
percent favored Dukakis while 42.3 percent backed Bush. With a
margin of error of 3.6 percent, the survey amounted to a dead heat
in the region where Bush virtually clinched the Republican
presidential nomination.
   The vice president swept the Southern primaries on March 8,
Super Tuesday, and broke the back of his competition for the GOP
nomination.
   While Dukakis won the primaries in the two biggest Southern
states on Super Tuesday _ Texas and Florida _ he never campaigned
in several other states in the region.
   The Massachusetts governor was campaigning for the first time in
Mississippi, Alabama, South Carolina and Tennessee.
   ``We aren't going to concede one single state in this country
... and that means the states of the South,'' Dukakis said as he
accepted Gore's endorsement.
   ``They're open, they're ready for new leadership,'' he said of
the Southern states.
   A potential trouble spot for the Democrats in the fall campaign
was raised when Dukakis was asked whether he would support the call
for an independent counsel to investigate allegations against
Democratic House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas.
   Dukakis replied that he understood Wright ``welcomed'' the
independent counsel, adding: ``His attitude about this contrasts
rather sharply with the kind of stonewalling we've had from the
administration in case after case.''
   The Massachusetts governor was asked if he was concerned abput
the possibility Wright would be under investigation when he was
scheduled to be presiding over the Democratic National Convention.
   ``I thought there was a presumption of innocence in this
country,'' replied Dukakis.
   Dukakis was asked about his call for the resignation of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III _ something he has not urged Wright to do.
   His call for Meese to quit, Dukakis said, came ``after repeated
evidence of insensitivity, a lack of awareness of what we mean when
we talk about high standards.''
   ``If you're attorney general of this country and you've stumbled
as often as he has and made as many mistakes as he has and provided
as weak leadership as he has, you ought to leave office,'' he said.
</TEXT>
