<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SingletonReaction     06-17 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singleton Reaction,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singleton Offered $10,000, Ticket To Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freed rapist Larry Singleton is not living in
Tampa, his brother says, but word that Singleton gave authorities
his brother's address here was enough to stir up a campaign to run
him out of town.
   A total of $10,000 and a one-way ticket out of Florida were
offered Thursday by a Bradenton car dealer and St. Petersburg radio
station if the 60-year-old former merchant seaman would pack up and
leave.
   Singleton spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in California
for raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker, chopping off her forearms with
an ax and leaving her for dead in a ditch southeast of San
Francisco in 1978. His parole ended in April.
   There was no response to the offers from Singleton, who earlier
in the week had listed his brother Walter's Tampa address with
state officials. But a neighbor said he was told by Walter
Singleton that his brother is living in seclusion 2{ hours from
Tampa.
   The brother wouldn't disclose the location, according to Phil
Scalera, adding that Walter Singleton invited 10 neighbors in to
his home to look around but they declined.
   ``We talked to Walter Singleton, and he was rather belligerent
about it,'' Scalera said. ``But he said he isn't staying there. ..
. He said: `I can't help it that he used my address. It's my
father's fault that he's my brother.'''
   Singleton, as a felon, had to register an address with the state
to move to Florida, but authorities said the address didn't have to
be his residence.
   Although law enforcement officers say Singleton cannot be barred
from living in Florida, businessman Tom Stimus wants Singleton to
feel unwelcome.
   Stimus, who has three car and truck dealerships in the area,
placed a full-page ad in the Bradenton Herald on Thursday that
read: ``An Open Letter To Larry Singleton, Take this $5,000 and get
out of Florida.''
   He also volunteered to pay rent and utilities for six months for
Singleton at a new address out-of-state.
   Stimus, 49, has previously offered rewards for the assassination
of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi and Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini,
with no takers.
   Meanwhile, WQYK-FM matched Stimus' $5,000 offer after 99 percent
of the listeners responding to an on-air poll said they wanted
Singleton to leave, said station spokeswoman Diana Thomas.
   California officials seeking to place Singleton during his
parole were met by community protests, and local law enforcement
officials said they feared they could not guarantee his safety.
   Singleton finally served his parole time while living in a
mobile home within the gates of San Quentin state prison.
</TEXT>
