<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SymphonyBankrupt 1stLd-Writethru a0408 06-17 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Symphony Bankrupt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0408,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nashville Symphony Files for Bankruptcy Reorganization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS headline, lead to clarify that orchestra is seeking to
reorganize</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nashville Symphony Association has
filed for Chapter 11 reorganization after almost five months of
struggling with its musicians to solve money problems.
   The Music City's 85-member orchestra shut down Feb. 3 because of
financial trouble, and since then a task force of board members and
musicians have wrangled over cost-cutting plans to keep the
symphony alive.
   The board said last week it would file for reorganization under
federal bankruptcy law if it failed to reach a last-minute
agreement with the musicians' union.
   Attorney C. Kinian Cosner Jr., who filed the petition Thursday,
said it will be followed within 15 days by a more detailed
accounting of the orchestra's finances.
   ``The major asset is the endowment of the symphony,
approximately $1 million,'' Cosner said. ``Any reorganization plan
will be funded by the income from that endowment. The purpose of
this filing is to effectuate an orderly liquidation and payment of
the claims under court supervision.''
   The filing of a bankruptcy petition protects the symphony from
its creditors until a reorganization plan can be devised. The
symphony has no plans for future performances, Cosner said.
</TEXT>
