<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS third item, dated NEW YORK, to UPDATE with no comment
from Miller in last graf, `The ad ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fat Boys, the rotund rap trio, have sued
Miller Brewing Co. for $5 million over a TV commercial in which
comedian Joe Piscopo and three heavyweight partners rap a song
touting Miller beer.
   The federal suit filed Monday claims the ad takes advantage of
their platinum-selling record success and infringes on the Fat
Boys' trademark. They also claim the commercial's music ``contains
a melody copied from (and) derived from'' the Fat Boys' music.
   The portly plaintiffs are Mark Morales (better known as ``Prince
Markie Dee''), Damon Wimbley (aka ``Kool Rock Ski'') and Darren
Robinson (``The Human Beat Box''), along with the group's record
company and music publisher. They also seek the withdrawal of the
commercial.
   The ad agency behind the commercial, Backer & Spielvogel Inc. of
Manhattan, declined to comment. Susan Henderson, a spokeswoman for
Miller, said today the Milwaukee-based brewing company had not yet
seen a copy of the suit and so had no immediate comment.
