<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1017EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Trotksy     06-17 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Trotksy,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trotsky's Stock Rises Under Glastnost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leon Trotsky, the revolutionary reviled for more
than a half-century as a Soviet traitor and enemy of socialism,
should be exonerated of criminal charges and his works reprinted, a
historian said today.
   The call for a new look at Trotsky by Yuri N. Afanasyev, rector
of the State Institute on Historical Archives, runs counter to a
central tenet of Soviet orthodoxy that has stood unchallenged for
more than 50 years.
   It was one of the boldest suggestions to date under Communist
Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign for ``glasnost,'' or
openness.
   Under glasnost, the Soviets are taking an increasingly negative
view of the 29-year rule of dictator Josef Stalin. The Soviets also
are exonerating Communists who were branded traitors under Stalin
and killed, imprisoned or exiled.
   By acknowleging that Trotsky was falsely accused of treason, the
Kremlin would further discredit Stalin, who Gorbachev has blamed
for brutal and bloody political terror and choking the development
of socialist democracy.
   ``We have to rehabilitate all those people who were repressed
and who were accused on false evidence, and all those accused must
be rehabilitated,'' Afanasyev told a news conference sponsored by
the government. ``And in line with those people is Trotsky.''
   Afanasyev noted that cleansing Trotsky's judicial record did not
mean an endorsement of his ideas, but even putting Trotsky on an
equal legal footing with other Stalin foes would be a startling
novelty.
   Born Lev D. Bronstein, the son of a prosperous Jewish farmer,
Trotsky was a central figure in the 1917 Russian Revolution and
architect of the Red Army's victory over counterrevolutionaries in
the Russian Civil War
   He served successively as commissar for foreign affairs and for
war, but was bested by Stalin in Kremlin infighting following the
death of Soviet founder Vladimir Lenin in 1924, and was forced out
of the Communist Party in 1927.
   Two years later, Trotsky was expelled from the Soviet Union and
later accused of heading an anti-Soviet plot. He was murdered in
Mexico City in 1940, reportedly by a Soviet agent.
   Under Stalin, Trotsky became an official ``non-person.'' His
role in the Soviet revolution was wiped from the historical record,
and his more radical brand of revolution was branded as heresy and
a betrayal of Lenin's legacy.
   In a major speech Nov. 2, Gorbachev continued the official
condemnation of Trotsky, saying nothing about his role in the
Bolshevik Revolution and attacking his character and ideas.
   Trotsky had advocated using the Soviet revolution as a
springboard to spread working-class revolt to other countries, and
opposed Stalin's program to build ``socialism in one country''
first.
   Afanasyev told reporters today that there may be room soon for a
reassessment of the ideas of Trotsky and other Stalin foes.
   Asked if the works of Trotsky, Stalin and former Soviet leader
Nikita Khrushchev may be republished soon following a long ban,
Afanasyev answered:
   ``I can speak on behalf on myself and think they should be
republished and accessible for all... I think it's very strange
when professors and teachers try to criticize Trotsky while they
haven't read a single word by Trotsky.''
   Afanasyev is a prominent advocate of Gorbachev's reform drive
who was chosen as a delegate to this month's nationwide Communist
Party conference.
   On Monday, the Soviet Supreme Court lifted the convictions
against three prominent Stalin foes, Lev Kamenev, Grigory Zinoviev
and Karl Radek. Kamenev and Zinoviev initially sided with Stalin
against Trotsky, but then backed Trotsky. Both were executed
following a trial for treason in 1936.
   In February, the court exonerated Nikolai A. Bukharin, another
Communist executed under Stalin whose more moderate economic
policies are very similar to what Gorbachev is now pursuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuddenDeath     06-17 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudden Death,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Says Diet Is Chief Cause of Sudden Death Among
Southeast Asian Men</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diet high in vitamin-deficient white rice
is a primary cause of a disease that kills otherwise healthy
Southeast Asian men in their sleep, according to a researcher who
spent three years studying the ailment.
   Ronald Munger, a post-doctoral fellow at the University of
Minnesota's division of epidemiology, said Thursday his studies
show that stress is not the leading cause of Sudden Unexpected
Death Syndrome, as some experts believe. He proposed, instead, that
it results mainly from thiamine deficiency.
   Munger presented his findings to a conference of the Society for
Epidemiologic Research in Vancouver, British Columbia.
   SUDS is the leading cause of death for Southeast Asian refugee
men ages 25 to 44 during their first few years in the United
States. The disease has claimed 117 Southeast Asian refugees since
1977, according to the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
Nearly all died in their sleep.
   Although researchers know the immediate cause of SUDS is an
electrical instability of the heart, they don't know what causes
the instability.
   The most common theory is that the deaths are caused mainly by
stress related to immigration and culture shock. Other possible
explanations are heart abnormalities or genetic predisposition
among Southeast Asians.
   Munger said he believes all those factors may play a part in
SUDS, but he places the main blame on the staple of the Southeast
Asian diet, white rice, which is a poor source of vitamins.
   Brown or unmilled rice is a good source of vitamins,
particularly thiamine, but few Southeast Asians eat it because it's
not considered socially acceptable. Eighty percent of the thiamine
is lost in the milling process that produces white rice. Thiamine,
also known as vitamin B1, is essential to normal nerve function and
metabolism of carbohydrates.
   For his study, Munger gathered electrocardiographs from 80
refugee men in Thailand in 1985 and 40 refugee men in Minnesota
over the last two years. He found ECG abnormalities occurred among
culturally and genetically diverse groups, including Japanese,
Filipinos, Vietnamese, Cambodians, Laotians and Hmong.
   But some researchers doubt Munger's theory.
   ``The thing I wonder a bit about his hypothesis is that it's so
different from what is usually seen in thiamine deficiency,'' said
Dr. Gib Parrish, a medical epidemiologist and pathologist at the
CDC.
   Thiamine deficiency often causes inflammation and degeneration
of the nerves, digestive system and heart. Those also are symptoms
of the disease beriberi, which is caused by a thiamine deficiency.
However, most SUDS victims appear normal before dying.
   Munger said he's suggesting that there are undocumented effects
of thiamine deficiency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
