<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Workers     06-17 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Workers,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers March on Parliament to Protest Reduced Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 4,000 strikers from an
agricultural machinery plant marched on the Yugoslav parliament
today to protest reduced wages.
   The workers of the Zmaj tractor factory in the Belgrade
industrial suburb of Zemun rallied in front of the parliament
building demanding to meet with government officials to air their
grievances. A delegation of the strikers was admitted into the
building for talks.
   ``We want changes!'' the strikers shouted as they crowded the
staircase leading up to the classical domed building. The
protesters carried national and Communist Party flags.
   As they filed through downtown Belgrade, the workers chanted
``Down with bureaucracy. More bread!'' and ``We want better lives!''
   Heavy police reinforements were called in to cordon off
passers-by from joining the strikers.For the first time, activists
of the official trade union joined the marchers, the Tanjug news
agency said.
   Yugoslavia, with a large foreign debt, launched a severe
austerity program that links wages to productivity. Many companies
cut workers pay as a result.
   Wages at the tractor factory were cut 9 percent in April and
another 4 percent in May.
   Yugoslavia owes $21 billion to Western creditors, and living
standards have tumbled by at least a third since 1980. Inflation
hovers at around 170 percent while economic growth has been
negligible during the past eight years.
   The wage-productivity link was one of the requirements made by
the International Monetary Fund before agreeing to reschedule part
of Yugoslavia's debt.
</TEXT>
