<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Bloomsday 2ndLd-Writethru a0458 06-17 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bloomsday, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0458,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joyce, Once Reviled By Dublin, Now a Favorite Son</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf pvs, ``Even today ...'' to CORRECT name of
Joyce's daughter to Lucia sted Nora</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ken Monaghan paused at the top of North
Great George's Street and said: ``Well, this is where it all
happened. Doesn't the whole place just reek of him?''
   He was referring to his uncle, James Joyce, and the Dublin he
immortalized in that colossus of 20th century literature,
``Ulysses.''
   Monaghan, a gentle, snowy-haired man of 62, was taking an
acquaintance around the old neighborhood on Bloomsday eve, hoping
to beat the influx of tourists and Joyce lovers who arrived
Thursday for Bloomsday itself, the most celebrated day of
remembrance ever created by a novel.
   Bloomsday is June 16, 1904, the single day during which
``Ulysses'' unfolds through the wanderings of Joyce's fictional
alter ego Stephen Dedalus, and that quintessential Dubliner,
Leopold Bloom.
   Every Bloomsday, the faithful retrace the action from the
starting point of ``Ulysses'' at the Tower overlooking the sea to
the streets of inner Dublin where the story ends.
   They search for the little that is left of Joyce's meticulous
charting. Some dress up in Edwardian clothes, beige ensembles
favored by Joyce and Bloom-style bowler and black three-piece suit.
   The pilgrims meander from the Forty Foot, the gentlemen-only
bathing cove below the Tower, to No. 7 Eccles Street, where Bloom
lived with his adulterous wife Molly.
   In between, they take in landmarks like the Davy Byrnes pub
where Bloom stopped for refreshment and a cemetery where he
attended Paddy Dignam's funeral. They walk past ``saddened angels,
crosses, broken pillars, family vaults, stone hopes praying with
upcast eyes, old Ireland's hearts and hands.''
   Others are gathered in Venice for the 11th International Joyce
Conference.
   At the Tower, now a Joyce museum, the Dublin literati gather
over wine and canapes to launch yet another guide to Joyce's
Dublin. City Hall, as part of the celebrations of Dublin's 1988
millennium, has funded a series of plaques at ``Ulysses'' landmarks.
   This year's Bloomsday, on Thursday, was especially elaborate
with a recreation of Dignam's cortege complete with horse-drawn
carriages.
   It wasn't always so. It took 30 years for Dublin to start
lionizing its native son. And with good reason. Had he not written
a profane and obscene book that poured scorn on everything from the
Roman Catholic Church to Irish nationalism?
   Had he not lampooned his friends in the guise of fiction?
   Had he not deserted Dublin in 1912, never to live there again?
   Monaghan remembers his Aunts Eva and Florrie, sisters of Joyce,
imploring him never to tell anyone he was related to the writer.
   Even today, Joyce's legacy is not all sweet. His grandson
Stephen, who lives in Paris, recently announced to the horror of
Joyceans that he had burned a series of letters by Joyce's daughter
Lucia, who died in a sanatorium in 1982.
   ``Personal things should remain personal,'' Stephen Joyce was
quoted as saying. ``Being ill in the way my aunt was is very
painful, and it is deplorable to delve into it.''
   Monaghan's walk takes him past the home of John P. Mehaffy, the
late provost of Trinity College, Dublin, who once declared Joyce to
be all the evidence he needed that education was wasted on the
Irish.
   Belvedere School comes into view, and the sidewalk Joyce trod as
a boy, trying not to step on the cracks. Up the road lies Mountjoy
Square, where Monaghan's aunts lived. He remembers them leaning out
of a window with a telescope to read the time on Findlater's Church
clock.
   Meanwhile, back at the Forty Foot, elderly men snort and splash
in the emerald waters with ``warm sunshine merrying over the sea''
just as Stephen Dedalus saw it.
   Suddenly, a gentleman in bowler and black three-piece suit drops
a towel on a rock, strips naked and plunges in.
   It's Gerry Davis, a Dublin painter who faithfully observes each
anniversary with a swim at the Forty Foot.
   Despite his self-exile, Joyce said he never really left Dublin.
All his writing was set there, and he liked to say that if Dublin
was ever destroyed, it could be reconstructed from his works.
   Dublin was slow to reciprocate. Early enthusiasts coined the
name Bloomsday in 1924, but only 30 years later did Dublin writers
stage the first commemoration.
   Today it is everything short of a public holiday. Copies of
``Ulysses,'' which once had to be smuggled into Ireland, now grace
bookshop windows in all their unexpurgated glory.
   Joyce, who also wrote ``Finnegans Wake'' and ``Dubliners,''
published ``Ulysses'' in Paris in 1922, and it was banned in the
United States and Britain that year. Joyce died in 1941 in Zurich
at age 59.
   In 1924, Joyce wrote in his notebook: ``Today, 16th June 20
years after. Will anybody remember this date?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
