<HEAD>Guerrillas Claim Train Attack, 34 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan guerrillas attacked and
destroyed a convoy of five trains on the southern Benguela railway,
killing 34 government soldiers, the rebels claimed today.
   In a note issued in Lisbon, the rebel movement, the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, said the attack
occurred Tuesday between the southern Angolan towns of Kinjenje and
Babaera.
   The note, signed by the rebels' chief of staff, Gen. Demostenes
Amos Chilingutila, said four guerrillas died and 11 were wounded in
the three-hour battle.
   The rebel movement is backed by the United States and South
Africa. It has been fighting the Marxist Movement for the
Liberation of Angola government to share power since the country
achieved independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The government is backed by the Soviets and an estimated 40,000
Cuban troops.
</TEXT>
