<2ND_LINE>PM-Wandering Whale,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whale With Wanderlust Visits Big Apple, But Finds Hudson River
Commute A Pain</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wayward humpback whale who strayed up the
Hudson River cut his Big Apple visit short after Coast Guard
officials gunned their engines, banged pipes and sounded horns to
get him to turn around.
   The 30- to 40-foot whale, described by ocean researchers as
being a juvenile, was last spotted just after 6 a.m. today off the
Earle Naval Weapons Station in New Jersey, said Coast Guard
spokesman Larry Lawrence. The station is approximately 50 miles
from New York City.
   The gray-and-white whale wandered into the Hudson Thursday
afternoon. ``He just made a wrong turn following the contours of
the ocean floor,'' said Judy Rabb of the Long Island-based Okeanos
Ocean Research Foundation.
   The whale went as far as 80th Street before two Coast Guard
boats that were tracking him got the endangered mammal to reverse
direction by sounding horns, banging pipes, gunning their engines
and doing anything else they could think of to annoy the creature.
   Lawrence said the Coast Guard was through babysitting the
wandering whale.
   ``We've contacted someone from the National Marine Fisheries
Service and they're taking the case over now,'' he said.
</TEXT>
