<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CorruptionIndictments     06-17 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corruption Indictments,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney Charges 69 with Theft of Treasury Checks from Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Complaints of missing checks and other valuables
at post offices in Illinois have led to charges against 69 people
of stealing money from the mail, forging signatures and fencing
property, a U.S. attorney says.
   Twenty-nine of those named in indictments announced Thursday are
Postal Service employees, many of whom worked together in small
rings, said U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas.
   Most of the stolen securities were U.S. Treasury checks, Valukas
said. But he could not say how much the thefts totaled or how many
people may have been affected.
   He also said many of the stolen securities were welfare checks,
``placing an immense burden on those least able to afford it.''
   He said one ring of three men fenced 45 checks worth almost
$42,700 and another of four men conspired to steal and sell 57
checks worth $45,000.
   In addition to theft of treasury checks, Valukas said packages
containing jewelry, credit cards and other valuables were stolen
from Chicago's main post office as well as postal stations as far
away as Rockford and Aurora.
   Mark Grey, head of the U.S. Postal Inspection Service for the
Chicago district, said inspectors from his office worked undercover
for 18 months after noticing unusually high loss figures for the
district and receiving an inordinant amount of complaints from the
public.
   In an unrelated case, Valukas also disclosed a kickback scheme
that centers on Central Truck Parts Co., which is charged with
paying bribes to purchasing agents for the city of Chicago, the
suburb of Wilmette and the state to secure contracts illegally.
   Charges against 24 people, including three Chicago employees and
one state employee, range from racketeering to failure to provide
information to the Internal Revenue Service.
</TEXT>
