<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hungary 3rdLd-Writethru   06-17 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0587,a0579,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BUDAPEST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Police Beat Demonstrators, Arrest 25</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12 graf pvs, ``About a ...'' to ADD detail of location</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club-swinging riot police in Hungary beat
demonstrators and arrested 25 people who gathered to memorialize
activists executed for leading the 1956 anti-communist revolt, a
dissident said today.
   The government media reported only five arrests.
   Police arrested the demonstrators after Thursday's unofficial
gatherings in Budapest, dissident Miklos Haraszti said in a
telephone conversation from the city. He said they were all later
released.
   He told The Associated Press that two well-known dissidents,
Gabor Demszky and Roza Hodosan, were taken to a district police
precinct, handcuffed, thrown to the floor and beaten in front of 15
other people arrested with them.
   ``They yelled to police to stop beating the two, but the police
didn't stop,'' Haraszti said.
   The activists were part of an officially estimated crowd of 400
who gathered in downtown Budapest on Thursday after a peaceful
morning vigil at the unmarked graves where former premier Imre Nagy
and fellow leaders of the 1956 revolt are believed buried.
   The revolt began Oct. 23, 1956, with mass demonstrations for a
new government and demands that Soviet troops leave Hungary. On
Nov. 4, the Soviets mobilized 200,000 Soviet troops and 2,500 tanks
to quell the uprising in Budapest.
   The only official report on Thursday's events came in a brief
report carried by the MTI news agency, which said that five alleged
ringleaders were detained for ``trying to bring under their
influence the crowd ... whom they had mobilized.''
   The report accused the crowd of disregarding a ``preliminary
warning by the police'' against attending the gatherings marking
the 30th anniversary of the executions.
   The protesters, chanting ``Democracy, Democracy'' and ``Nagy,
Nagy,'' demanded rehabilitation of Nagy and some of his associates
who were also executed or sentenced to prison and sang the
Hungarian national anthem.
   About 150 police guarded the square and conducted frequent
identity checks.
   About a half hour later, the crowd moved toward the Danube
river, which divides the historic city of Buda and Pest, and then
to the nearby Hungarian television center.
   After dissident Janos Kiss addressed the crowd from the steps of
the television station building, riot police moved in to disperse
the rally, witnesses said.
   ``They came with rubber truncheons and even drove motorcycles at
a clip into the crowd to frighten and disperse it,'' said a witness
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Police were a little crazy.
I saw people knocked to the ground by the cops and beaten up.''
   The source said one of those injured was Ottilia Solt, an
activist who was taken to her home ``in pretty bad shape.''
   Haraszti said police ``attacked deliberately and brutally'' and
did not spare women or children.
   Witnesses said police did not interfere during an evening
requiem mass, however.
   Thursday's ceremonies in honor of Nagy and three close
associates marked 30 years since official media published a
Ministry of Justice decree on June 17, 1958, announcing the four
were sentenced to death. The statement said they ``played a leading
role in the preparation and starting of the counter-revolutionary
uprising in October 1956.''
</TEXT>
