<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CorpseRing     06-17 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corpse Ring,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eighteen Arrested Arrests For Stealing and Selling Dead Bodies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested 18 people for
allegedly stealing and selling ancient corpses believed to possess
magical powers, a newspaper said today.
   The Kompas daily reported the arrests were made over the past
two months in the Mamasa district in Sulawesi island, 1,125 miles
northeast of Jakarta. The newspaper, quoting police, said buyers
were willing to pay up to $3,100 for ``corpses belonging to people
buried tens even hundreds of years ago.''
   The district police chief, Lt. Col. Ryanto Amrin was quoted as
saying the thieves ``acted on orders from some mysterious buyers''
and did not know what the buyers wanted to do with the corpses.
   Many people in the district still hold a long belief that
ancient corpses possessed magical powers, the paper said.
   The paper did not say how many graves had been broken by the
alleged corpse traders or identify the buyers. It did not detail
the investigation. It said they were arrested for stealing and
selling corpses, but did not give formal charges.
   Cadavers in the district are traditionally treated with
substances that prevent them from decomposing for many years, the
paper said.
</TEXT>
