<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos     06-17 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Philippine President Worried About Possible Indictments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
says proposed federal charges against him and his wife would be
harassment and could not be proved, but he acknowledges he is
concerned.
   ``Of course I'm worried. I am worried. I could not sleep for one
whole night when I learned about it,'' Marcos said Thursday during
a news conference at his home overlooking Honolulu.
   Justice Department officials have been reviewing proposed
charges, including racketeering conspiracy to loot the Philippine
government over 20 years and fraud in the way money was concealed
behind false ownerships, Washington-based law enforcement
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Wednesday.
   ``What is racketeering? Where is the proof of the transfer of
funds?'' Marcos said.
   He said there is nothing new about the allegations and dismissed
them as ``the same old charges.''
   ``All along I thought this was over.'' he said.
   ``This has been going on for two years,'' said Marcos, 70,
forced to leave office in 1986 and go into exile. ``It is
harassment, pure and simple. They should be dismissed because it is
only hearsay.''
   Marcos said there is no proof that he stole money while he was
president.
   On another topic, Marcos said he still held out hope that the
government of President Corazon Aquino would allow him to return to
the Philippines for the funeral of his mother, Josefa Edralin
Marcos, who died May 4 at the age of 95.
   After the news conference in Marcos' living room, his wife,
Imelda, pulled two reporters into the dining room to see a
videotape showing thousands of Marcos supporters marching with a
motorcade that set out Wednesday from Manila carrying his mother's
body to her home province of Ilocos Norte, 250 miles away.
   The two-hour tape was shot by an amateur photographer, she said.
   Meanwhile, Marcos said he will go to a hospital in the next few
days to have a knee examined.
   ``My left knee is in pain, the muscle is weakened and I can
hardly walk,'' he said. ``The pains are very unbearable.''
   Marcos was hospitalized for two days last month for chest pains
his doctor said were caused by arthritis or inflammation in the
area of the left sixth rib.
</TEXT>
