<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     06-17 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trustee Predicts PTL Deal, Bakker Submits Rental Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PTL ministry should strike a deal by
the end of the month with one of at least four prospective buyers
for its 2,300-acre Heritage USA complex, its bankruptcy trustee
predicted.
   M.C. ``Red'' Benton told U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds on
Thursday that all of the potential buyers want to maintain it as a
Christian retreat while allowing the church and cable television
network to operate as a separate, non-profit corporation.
   Benton said he foresees no future for founder Jim Bakker at PTL,
either as a legitimate buyer or as a guest on the ministry's cable
television program.
   Bakker ``has shown no positive evidence he has resources to come
up with a plan'' to buy PTL and his presence on the show would be
harmful to the ministry, Benton said. ``He's still floundering out
in left field.''
   Benton's comments came as a Bakker attorney submitted a formal
proposal for Bakker to regain control of the ministry, a newspaper
reported today.
   Bakker proposes to rent the Heritage Grand Hotel and Heritage
Island water park in Fort Mill, S.C., while buying broadcast time
on the PTL satellite network, The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer
reported.
   The newspaper said Bakker attorney Ryan Hovis gave the proposal
to PTL attorney Joe Allman after Thursday's court hearing.
   The newspaper cited unidentified sources as saying the proposal
is unacceptable to Benton and Reynolds because Bakker's return
would seriously damage the ministry's credibility.
   Benton said after the hearing that sports entrepreneur George
Shinn will submit a plan before the week ends to buy PTL's
property, where he would build a sports complex while allowing the
ministry functions to continue.
   Bakker has criticized Shinn's proposal because it would allow
alcohol to be sold at the Heritage Grand Hotel.
   Bakker said Wednesday that he still intends to regain control of
the ministry he began building in 1974 and believes he will be
accepted back by PTL's followers despite the sex and money scandal
that surfaced when he resigned in March 1987.
   Benton said the only way PTL can survive is if it sells its
property and forms a non-profit ministry that is debt free. PTL,
with current debts of up to $130 million and assets of $160
million, filed for reorganization in June 1987.
   Also Thursday, Bakker and his wife, Tammy, began moving into a
house in Lake Wylie, near PTL's Fort Mill headquarters, said Bakker
attorney James Toms.
   Inez Brown, president of the Bring Bakkers Back Club, said in a
news release that members of the group leased the $1,000-a-month
house for nine months for the Bakkers.
</TEXT>
