<DOCNO> AP880617-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonEscape 2ndLd-Writethru a0591 06-17 0909</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0591,0928</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials: Prisoners May Have Plotted Escape For Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 3-4 with prison spokesman saying piece of
hacksaw blade found. SUBS 6th graf pvs, `The eight...' to UPDATE
with no sightings by midmorning and DELETE redundant first
reference to Waller; SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Two state...' to UPDATE
with boat used in search; DELETES outdated 20th graf, `Prison
officials...' that said no tools had been found.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDDYVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four convicted killers and four other
inmates who fled Kentucky's maximum-security prison may have spent
months plotting their elaborate escape plan from the 105-year-old
fortress, officials say.
   ``They had no hope of leaving legally anytime soon. They had
nothing else to do but spend their time thinking of a way to get
out,'' Jack Wood, a spokesman for the Kentucky State Penitentiary,
said after Thursday's escape.
   Bobby Waller, another prison spokesman, said today that a 2 to
3-inch piece of hacksaw blade was found in one of the escapee's
cells, the first tool of escape officials had found.
   He said investigators had recovered other information but he was
unable to release any details.
   In Fayetteville, N.C., meanwhile, authorities today recaptured
the third of six men who escaped from a Cumberland County jail on
Sunday.
   Prison officials are usually able to prevent escape attempts
because they ``hear the rumblings that something's going on'' and
then conduct searches that turn up contraband or homemade equipment
that could be used in an escape, said Kentucky State Penitentiary
Warden William Seabold.
   ``But the number (of escapees) and the avenue they took would
indicate it was well-planned and not a spur-of-the-moment escape
attempt,'' Seabold said.
   The eight are believed to have split up after what authorities
say was the largest prison escape in state history. The search for
the inmates was focused within two miles of the prison, and there
were no confirmed sightings of the escapees by midmorning, said
Waller.
   At least nine other inmates also attempted to flee the prison,
authorities said.
   The penitentiary, about 200 miles southwest of Louisville on
Lake Barkley, was built in 1883 and has undergone several additions
and renovations over the years. It is surrounded on three sides by
water and on the fourth by woods, but no wall or fence enclosed the
cellblock from which the eight fled.
   Waller said a boat was being used in the search, as well as two
state police small airplanes, 20 troopers, a dog team, local
authorities and 60 prison officers. In addition, pictures of the
escapees were distributed in area stores and gas stations.
   Dogs tracked the scent of at least one escapee to the site where
a pickup truck was stolen, about a half-mile from the prison.
   Authorities warned residents to lock their doors and watch their
children closely.
   Collaborators set several small fires in another section of the
building early Thursday to divert guards, giving the eight about 15
minutes to make their escape, Waller said.
   ``Fire in an institution like this is an extreme emergency,''
Wood said, explaining why guards at the time were not paying
attention to the cellhouse from which the prisoners escaped.
``You've got people locked up in cells and they can't get away.
You've got an enclosed area and smoke can reach dangerous levels
very quickly.''
   The escapees were housed in a cellblock known as ``the jail
within the jail,'' which is used to separate certain inmates from
the general population, Wood said.
   ``There's more security in the sense that there's more staff in
the cellhouse,'' Wood said.
   Wood said six of the escapees, who included four convicted
killers, were being housed in the cellhouse because they had been
charged with or found guilty of assault on other inmates. The other
two were being investigated for an escape attempt last week.
   The escapees apparently sawed open their cell doors and then cut
through a prison window that was enclosed by a screen on one side
and criss-crossed bars on the other, he said. They climbed down an
extension cord tied to a window about 30 feet above the ground.
   Once outside, the escapees traveled across a small parking lot
toward Lake Barkley, where they walked along the shore to the other
side of the prison and up into a wooded area, Wood said.
   One prisoner who failed to escape was found hanging from the
window and three others were outside their cells. Five additional
cells had been tampered with, Waller said.
   The prison, which houses 780 inmates, remained under lockdown
status, during which time prisoners are confined to their cells, he
said.
   ``We're going to make absolutely sure there is nothing else in
progress,'' Seabold said.
   In North Carolina, three prison escapees were still at large
from a Sunday jailbreak, including a former soldier convicted in
two Ninja-style slayings.
   Gregory Maurice Lee, 30, of Fayetteville, was arrested early
today at an apartment after Fayetteville police received a
telephone tip. Lee, who had been serving time for burglary, larceny
and assault, offered no resistance, said police Lt. William
Barefoot.
   Six men escaped from the Law Enforcement Center Sunday night
after using hacksaw blades to cut through a floor-level piece of
steel and kick out a portion of a bar, authorities said. They used
knotted bedsheets to climb four stories down the building's side.
One escapee fell and was soon recaptured; a second prisoner was
arrested Wednesday.
</TEXT>
