<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Frigate     06-17 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Frigate,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cargo Ship Arrives to Carry Damaged US Frigate Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A specially-built Dutch cargo ship is in
the Persian Gulf to carry the mine-damaged U.S. Navy frigate Samuel
B. Roberts back to the United States this month, U.S. military
officials disclosed today.
   The Mighty Servant 2, a 25,743-ton ``semi-submersible'' cargo
ship, was escorted into the gulf Tuesday and went to Dubai, where
the Samuel B. Roberts is in drydock.
   The 3,600-ton frigate has been undergoing preliminary repairs in
Dubai since it struck a mine in the central gulf on April 14. Ten
members of its crew were injured in the blast.
   U.S. officers have credited other crewmen with saving them and
the ship itself after the mine, laid by Iran, blew a 22-foot gash
in the hull.
   The Navy contracted the Mighty Servant 2 from its owners,
Wijsmuller Beheer B.V., of Ijmuiden, Netherlands, to carry the
frigate back to the United States rather than attempt to sail it
home.
   Maj. Charles Boyd, a spokesman for the U.S. Central Command,
said no firm date had been set for the Samuel B. Roberts'
departure. But military sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the ship would leave the gulf this month.
   He said it would be taken to its home port at Newport, R.I. Navy
officials said earlier that the 2-year-old ship would be returned
to the Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine, where it was built, for
final repairs.
   The Samuel B. Roberts had just completed escorting a
U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker to Kuwait and was saiing back down the
Gulf when it lumbered over what U.S. offiers say was a freshly-laid
minefield 50 miles northeast of Qatar.
   The United States retaliated for the mining four days later with
attacks on two Iranian oil platforms in the south central gulf.
That action began a day of fighting during which six Iranian naval
craft were sunk or disabled.
   The Navy escorts followed the U.S. reflagging of Kuwaiti tankers
to protect neutral shipping in the gulf, which has been the scene
of spillover violence in the 7-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
</TEXT>
