<2ND_LINE>PM-Missed Deadline,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Agency Rejects Appeal of Student Seeking Scholarship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state scholarship board has rejected an
appeal from a top student that it accept her application for a
$5,000 grant since it was submitted late through no fault of her
own.
   The State Student Assistance Commission of Indiana voted 4-3
Thursday not to consider Nicole L. Lovett's scholarship
application, despite pleas by the 18-year-old graduate and her
guidance counselor, who missed the board's deadline.
   Miss Lovett, who graduated this month in the top 3 percent of
her class at Indianapolis North Central High School, gave her
application to counselor Donna March on Feb. 22.
   Mrs. Marsh told the commission at a hearing Thursday that she
neglected to notice the March 1 deadline for submitting the
application and asked that Miss Lovett not be penalized for her
mistake.
   Miss Lovett, who had nearly straight A's during her four years
of high school, was seeking the scholarship from the federally
funded Paul Douglas Teacher Scholarship.
   The scholarships are based on the student's academic record in
competition with other applicants.
   The hearing followed an April decision to reject the application
because of the missed deadline.
