<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Rebels,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Say They Killed 63 Troops in 2 Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in southern Sudan say they killed
63 government troops and wounded 218 in two attacks near an army
garrison near the southeastern border with Ethiopia.
   The clandestine radio of the Sudanese People's Liberation Army
said Thursday that guerrillas ambushed the troops June 9 in the
first attack at Piyang forest, about 40 miles west of the town of
Akobo.
   Rebels one day later attacked troops at Riang, about 20 miles
south of the town, said the report, monitored in Nairobi, Kenya.
   The radio said rebel units also attacked Akobo's government
garrison, killing an unspecified number of troops. ``Four captains
and two lieutenants were among the dead,'' it said. The radio did
not say whether the officers were counted among the 63 soldiers
slain in the other attacks.
   No rebel casualties were given.
   ``The enemy soldiers also suffered widespread damage in military
equipment including five trucks loaded with foodstuffs,'' the
report added.
   Independent verification of the report was not immediately
possible. No telephone communications were available to Akobo.
   The rebels, mainly Christians and animists, have fought since
1983 against the Moslem-dominated central government for greater
autonomy and economic reforms in three southern provinces.
</TEXT>
