<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HeatWave     06-17 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heat Wave,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Chilled By Cold Front</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front accompanied by rain and storms that knocked out
power has ended a heat wave across the Northeast after three days
of record highs in the 90s, with today's highs forecast 15 to 20
degrees lower.
   In Massachusetts, medical officials said 20 deaths in Suffolk
County since Sunday, 14 of them Thursday, may have been caused in
part by the heat.
   The front slid across the upper East Coast during the night and
the clash of cool, dry air with the humid blanket of hot air
touched off storms, some violent.
   The Baltimore area was hit by hail and heavy rain that knocked
out power to about 22,000 customers. Power was restored to all but
300 customers by today.
   In northern Massachusetts, the heat wave was broken by strong
thunderstorms which brought half-inch hail and wind gusts up to 50
mph to Methuen. Three people were reported struck by lightning in
the Merrimack Valley and one was listed in critical condition today.
   As of 10 a.m. today, the temperature in Boston had reached only
70 degrees, according to the National Weather Service, compared to
Thursday's high of 92 degrees at Logan International Airport.
   About 10,000 Massachusetts Electric Co. customers in Methuen,
Lawrence and Dracut were without power for up to five hours
Thursday night, utility spokesman Ken Larson said
   The cold front gave the Chicago area relief from 90-degree heat
on Wednesday, dropping Thursday's high to 82, but temperatures were
expected to rise back into the 90s on Sunday, said Jim Vermoch, a
weather service meteorologist.
   The cooling trend brought Chicago no relief from the drought.
The area is in its 24th day without rain, added to an already
abnormally dry spring, and is about 6 inches short of the normal
14{ inches of rain it usually gets by this time of year, he said.
   And farther west, a new round of heat was building on the
Plains, with thermometers expected to go as high as 103 today in
western South Dakota.
</TEXT>
