<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EspositoIndicted     06-17 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Esposito Indicted,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Dem Party Boss Indicted On Tax Evasion Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Brooklyn Democratic boss Meade Esposito,
his daughter and a business partner handed out bribes and kickbacks
to ensure business for their printing company, according to an
indictment that also charges them with tax fraud.
   In an 18-count indictment, they also were accused of laundering
more than $250,000 through a phony invoice scam to obtain cash for
the bribes and personal use, U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney said
Thursday.
   The indictment issued by a federal grand jury in Brooklyn
outlined a scheme that alleged the three paid $200,000 in bribes
and kickbacks.
   Esposito, 81, was described as a silent partner of the printing
company, Beaumont Offset Corp. of Farmingdale, N.Y. The other
defendants are Harry Dickran, president of Beaumont; and Phyllis
Zito, Esposito's daughter and secretary-treasurer of the company.
   The charges are an offshoot of the investigation that led to
Esposito's conviction last September for giving an illegal gratuity
to U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., Maloney said. Esposito is
appealing the conviction.
   ``He is an intimate part of a long continuing fraud on the
government,'' Maloney said of Esposito.
   Esposito's lawyer, Edward Brodsky, said his client was innocent
of the charges. Esposito was a powerful party boss from 1969 until
1984.
   ``Although he is now 81 years old and not in good health, he
will go to trial and prove to the entire world that he is not
guilty,'' Brodsky said.
   A woman who answered the phone at Beaumont said the company's
attorney was not available for comment.
   The three are charged with violating interstate travel laws to
commit bribery, making false statements on Beaumont's tax returns
and conspiracy to make false statements on tax returns.
   Dickran and Mrs. Zito were also charged with making false
statements on their personal income tax returns.
</TEXT>
