<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReverseBias     06-17 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reverse Bias,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules White Minority In Birmingham Has Voting Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a twist on a tactic generally used to
increase black representation, Birmingham's white minority has won
a ruling allowing it to challenge at-large local elections for
allegedly diluting white votes.
   Similar suits filed by blacks have thrown out at-large election
systems in many other cities as violations of the 1965 Voting
Rights Act.
   U.S. District Judge Robert B. Propst signed a ruling Thursday
rejecting the city's request to throw out the suit, which seeks to
impose single-member district elections for the nine-member City
Council.
   Propst's ruling sets the stage for trial of the lawsuit,
possibly this fall, and holds that voting rights law applies to
white minorities in the same way it has protected blacks who once
were a minority in a segregated Birmingham.
   ``The court finds no substantial indication in the act or in its
legislative history which suggests that some minority races are not
protected by it,'' said Propst.
   ``If it were so, it would be contrary to other civil rights
legislation which may have been spawned by virtue of well-known and
blatant discrimination against blacks, but the reach of which
extends to both black and white,'' he said.
   The suit was filed by a biracial group that claims the Jefferson
County Citizens Coalition, led by black Mayor Richard Arrington,
has turned Birmingham's white voters into an oppressed minority.
   Donald Watkins, the city's attorney in the case, said he was not
surprised by the ruling.
   ``Ever since the first hearing before Judge Propst (in
December), my clients have realized and been prepared to go the
long haul on this case,'' Watkins said. ``We are prepared to go the
distance.''
   The city claims that the election of three white council members
proves that whites are not shut out of the at-large system.
   Jack Harrison, an attorney for the plaintiffs, said the city has
not been willing to negotiate. He declined comment on the judge's
ruling.
   Propst rejected the plaintiffs' claim that the lawsuit is not a
racial issue and gave the biracial group's attorneys 10 days to
show why its three black members should not be dismissed from the
action.
   That would leave only the white voters' claim that their voting
strength is being diluted by black bloc voting.
</TEXT>
