<2ND_LINE>PM-Cincinnati Opera-Swaggart,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Opera Edits Swaggart Speech Out of Radio Spot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cincinnati Opera said it has responded to
public criticism by revamping a radio commercial to remove an
excerpt of the Rev. Jimmy Swaggart's public admission that he had
sinned.
   The original commercial, in which Swaggart was heard to say, ``I
do not plan in any way to whitewash my sin. I have no one but
myself to blame,'' was never aired.
   It was supposed to start being broadcast Thursday, but the
company pulled it, edited Swaggart out and will begin airing the
new version Saturday, Kathy Neus, the opera company's public
relations manager, said today.
   Ms. Neus said the opera company and advertising agency who
created the radio spot received about two dozen calls criticizing
it, based on advance publicity.
   The opera had no intention of offending anyone, she stressed.
   The advertisement promotes the company's June 30 and July 2
performances of Carlisle Floyd's 1956 opera ``Susannah,'' in which
an isolated young women is seduced by a hypocritical backwoods
Tennessee preacher.
   ``It's basically the same kind of commercial,'' Ms. Neus said
Thursday of the edited spot. ``It just doesn't have Swaggart.''
   The promotional campaign also included a television
advertisement that did not mention Swaggart, Ms. Neus said.
   Swaggart, a Louisiana-based television preacher, made the public
admission of sin in a February speech to his congregation. He never
specified the sin, but he was reported to have met several times
with a prostitute at a New Orleans motel to watch her perform
sexual acts. He has not denied those reports.
   William Treeby, a New Orleans lawyer who is a board member of
Jimmy Swaggart Ministries, said his organization did not plan to
take any legal action against the company.
   ``They have withdrawn all their advertisement and they've
apologized,'' Treeby said Thursday.
   Ms. Neus said the opera had not apologized. ``It was just in
fun. We were hoping to attract people to the opera.''
</TEXT>
