<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LostArt     06-17 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Art,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Government-Owned Artworks Said To Be Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of works of art that
decorated the walls of Dutch offices around the world are missing,
the government says, and some of the paintings may even have ended
up in the trash.
   Koos de Jong, who oversees the government's collection of
360,000 works of art, said he discovered the pieces were missing
when he took an inventory recently. He was quoted Friday by the
Amsterdam daily De Volkskrant.
   About 165,000 pieces had been lent to government offices and
embassies around the world and many never came back, he said.
   The government began collecting the works under a post-World War
II program to support Dutch artists. The collection also includes
antiques and paintings by masters of the 17th, 18th and 19th
centuries.
   ``There may be several thousand _ I can't predict for sure _
that are certainly gone,'' de Jong told De Volkskrant. ``Artworks
got lost or were irreparably damaged because of ill-treatment.''
   De Jong is head of collections for the Dutch National Pictorial
Arts Service. He did not disclose a damage figure, and the article
did not provide details on the missing art.
   ``In the old days, it was possible (for government officials) to
come and collect paintings or bits of furniture from the national
depot just as they pleased,'' De Jong said.
   ``Even now, it can still happen that a work given on loan years
ago becomes part of somebody's inventory and ends up among the
garbage when the office is being moved or redecorated,'' he said.
   De Jong's service itself recently moved to new quarters in The
Hague from an old Amsterdam warehouse where much of the collection
lay gathering dust.
   Today, the art is carefully stored on specially designed racks
in air-conditioned rooms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
