<HEAD>Navy Names Bushey as New Chief of Enlisted Men</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year Navy veteran who is the command
master chief of enlisted men on the aircraft carrier Theodore
Roosevelt has been tapped to become the next master chief petty
officer of the Navy, Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost announced Friday.
   Trost, the chief of naval operations, said he had selected
Master Chief Avionics Technician Duane R. Bushey to become his top
adviser on all issues involving enlisted personnel.
   The new top enlisted man for the Navy will assume his duties in
September. He will replace Master Chief William H. Plackett, who
has held the post for the past two years and who is retiring after
32 years of active service.
   Bushey, 44, is a native of Lebanon, N.H., but graduated from
Wicomico Senior High School in Salisbury, Md. He enlisted in the
Navy in June 1962 and moved immediately into the field of air
warfare avionics, graduating from the Aviation Electrician's School
in Jacksonville, Fla.
   Since then, he has held a variety of posts both at sea on
aircraft carriers and at naval air stations. He has been in charge
of enlisted personnel on the Theodore Roosevelt since October 1985.
   Bushey is married to the former Susan W. Prause of Oakland,
Calif., and the couple has two sons.
