<HEAD>Evacuations Follow Chlorine Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out today at a plant where
chlorine was stored, spreading fumes through the area and forcing
the evacuation of 1,800 people, including children at three
schools, officials said.
   There were no reports of serious injuries, but Fire Department
spokesman Giorgio Placanico said nine firefighters were overcome by
fumes in the hot, humid weather. One worker at the plant may have
been affected also, he said.
   Fire Chief Raymond J. Sullivan said rain from an early morning
thunderstorm apparently blew into a chlorine hopper at the Advanced
Laboratories plant, sparking a chemical reaction and small fire
that sent chlorine fumes through the neighborhood shortly after 10
a.m.
   Firefighters, using soda ash, quickly quenched the blaze and an
area within a quarter of a mile of the three-story brick plant was
evacuated as a precaution, he said.
   More than 1,200 children at three elementary schools were taken
by bus to junior high schools, said Durham Caldwell, a spokesman
for the city school system. Caldwell said the evacuation was
orderly and none of the children were reported to have been
affected by the fumes.
