<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Indictment,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mail Handlers Union President Charged With Embezzlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has charged the
president of the Mail Handlers union with embezzling nearly
$100,000 of union money, authorities said.
   Herbert Walker, 45, president of the Post Office Mail Handlers,
Watchmen, Messengers and Group Leaders, also is accused of making
false reports in union records.
   The indictment, announced Thursday, alleges that Walker, of
Cincinnati, embezzled $99,077 for his own use from 1983 to 1985
while he was president of the union's Local 304, which represents
3,200 workers in Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky.
   Walker could not be reached for comment; his telephone number is
not published. A receptionist at the postal union's national office
in Washington, D.C., said no one in there could comment.
   Prosecutors allege Walker deposited Local 304 checks in his bank
account, rather than in the union's account. They also contend he
wrote checks to himself from the local's account and altered
records to make it appear as though the checks were written for
union expenses.
   Prosecutors said Walker would face a maximum 198 years in
prison, fines of $500,000 and $2,500 in other assessments, if
convicted. Walker also would be prohibited from serving as an
officer, director, trustee or member of the executive board of any
union for 13 years, prosecutors said.
   In 1987, Walker was elected president of the 50,000-member
national union and moved to Washington. Meanwhile, the national
union was put into trusteeship for alleged mismanagement of funds.
</TEXT>
