<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MultipleKillings     06-17 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Multiple Killings,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judges Denies Petition to Delay Simmons Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today denied a petition to delay the
execution of a man convicted of two murders and accused of 14
others while appeals on his behalf are considered.
   The ruling by Circuit Judge John F. Patterson came despite
testimony at a hearing this morning from a psychiatrist who said he
was having second thoughts about his earlier judgment that R. Gene
Simmons was competent and responsible for his actions when the
slayings occurred last December.
   ``Mr. Simmons seems more competent than most of the testimony
that I've heard here today,'' Patterson said in denying the
petition filed on behalf of the Rev. Louis Franz of Star City,
representing a group called Arkansas Churches for Life.
   The judge also denied a motion to appeal Simmons' conviction and
sentence.
   Franz and his attorney, Mark Cambiano of Morrilton, filed the
petition to stop the execution in an effort to assure an appeal of
Simmons' May 12 conviction for killing two people in a Dec. 28
shooting rampage at Russellville.
   After he was sentenced, Simmons read a statement asking that he
be executed quickly and that no appeals be filed on his behalf.
   Simmons is scheduled to die by injection June 27. He also is
charged with two counts of capital murder in the deaths of 14
family members whose bodies were found t the Simmons home in a
rural area near Dover, north of Russellville. Trial on those
charges is scheduled for July 18.
   Dr. Irving Kuo, a psychiatrist at the State Hospital in Little
Rock, testified today that he began to have doubts about Simmons'
competence after receiving a letter Simmons wrote in response to a
letter Kuo sent him after the trial last month.
   ``Officials are starting to play their little games,'' Simmons
said in the letter to Kuo. The psychiatrist said that suggests
Simmons has some characteristics of paranoia.
   Simmons' lawyers, John C. Harris and Robert E. ``Doc'' Irwin,
and prosecutor John Bynum attacked Kuo's new opinion.
   ``If this letter demonstrates anything at all, all it
demonstrates is that he may be getting a little bit paranoid, a
little bit tired,'' Bynum said.
   Kuo said Bynum's opinion represented one possibility, but that
others were that ``he has been paranoid and is becoming more
paranoid'' and ``he has been paranoid and it's coming out more in
the open.''
   Kuo's letter to Simmons had asked for information about what
motivated Simmons in his crimes, saying the request was for
personal and professional curiosity and to obtain information that
might be published in a scientific journal.
   Simmons has said in letters to newspapers that he doesn't want
Franz to be allowed to intervene, and he accused Cambiano of trying
to make a name for himself in Arkansas legal history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
