<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   06-17 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-South Africa, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0611,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Council Schedules Emergency Meeting On `Sharpeville Six'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with Security Council
resolution; picks up 4th pvs: In March...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Friday unanimously
adopted a resolution appealing to the South African government to
stay the executions of six black prisoners.
   The United States, which sometimes vetoes measures to shield
South Africa, declined to exercise its veto and allowed the mercy
plea to pass. It was a clear signal to the Pretoria government of
Washington's displeasure with plans to execute the so-called
``Sharpeville Six.''
   On Thursday, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar appealed
for clemency.
   The council said it was convinced that the executions, if
carried out, would ``further inflame an already grave situation in
South Africa.''
   It called ``once again upon the South African authorities to
stay execution and commute the death sentences imposed on the
Sharpeville Six.''
   In March the 15-member Security Council appealed to the South
African government to grant clemency to the six. The council
frequently condemns South Africa for its system of apartheid but
South Africa says the U.N. group has no right to interfere in
domestic affairs.
   The six were convicted of participating in a 1984 riot in which
a black Sharpeville town councilor was killed. But they were not
found to have joined in the physical assault.
   The members of the council are the United States, Britain,
China, France and the Soviet Union _ the permanent five nuclear
powers _ and Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Italy, Japan, Nepal,
Senegal, West Germany, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
   The United States frequently vetoes Security Council
denunciations of South Africa and its calls for sanctions against
the government. But the United States sometimes declines to
exercise its veto and allows certain critical resolutions to pass.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million black majority has no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
