<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WelfareOverhaul     06-17 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Welfare Overhaul,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Says Welfare Veto Still Possible Unless Congress Toes
the Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Friday refused to
endorse a landmark Senate welfare bill and said a veto still was
possible due to potential welfare demands in the House ``far out of
line with our judgment.''
   The Senate bill, passed 93-3 on Thursday, carries a five-year
price tag of about $2.8 billion, while the House plan, passed
narrowly in December, is much more generous and would cost $7
billion.
   ``It is a case of Sisyphus having to push the rock up the
mountain at this point,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
told reporters Friday. ``We will try to get changes in the
conference (between House and Senate negotiators), but it's going
to be very tough to reconcile with the House bill that is so far
out of line with our judgment.''
   Both the Senate and House bills are designed to turn the
country's Depression-era welfare system into a jobs program with a
rigorous child support collections component. Government assistance
would be a last and temporary resort.
   Negotiators from each chamber will start meeting in two to three
weeks to try to reconcile the two bills. They expect to have a
compromise measure on the president's desk by Labor Day.
   Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., sponsor of the House plan, which gives
more money to the jobs program, said he would try to retain a
higher spending level than called for by the Senate.
   ``If you're going to have a meaningful work program, you have to
be prepared to help finance it,'' Downey said.
   Downey also said a House plan to offer financial incentives to
states that raise cash benefits, which are very low in some places,
would be ``hotly fought and contested'' in the House-Senate
conference.
   Despite those difficulties, Downey said he was optimistic that
an acceptable compromise could be struck ``if the administration
will sign a welfare bill that is something similar to the Senate
bill. Then maybe we can work out a deal.''
   Fitzwater indicated, however, that the administration had not
yet decided whether the Senate bill, even with revisions sought by
the White House, was acceptable.
   ``We still have some problems with the bill,'' he said, but
added that White House officials would examine the changes that
were made Thursday in response to their demands.
   Senators agreed to compromises on two major concerns raised by
Reagan. One provision says that by 1994, state jobs, education and
training programs must be serving 22 percent of eligible
participants.
   The other, more controversial provision requires that states
create workfare programs, or community work projects, and require
part-time participation for one adult in each two-parent family on
welfare.
   ``It's the first time a welfare bill has ever been passed that
includes a federal requirement for work in association with
welfare, and in that sense we believe it is a very important
concept to be established in law,'' Fitzwater said.
   But governors generally oppose the provision, as do Downey and
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., author of the Senate bill.
Moynihan said governors consider it costly and counterproductive,
especially in states with strong labor markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
