<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Debt     06-17 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Debt,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General Consulting On Debt Crisis To Keep UN Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
met Friday with U.N. delegates about the nearly $700 million that
member countries owe the United Nations, a debt that U.N. officials
said could close the organization.
   The secretary-general consulted with Eastern European delegates
on Friday. Earlier in the week, he met with Western European, Asian
and Latin American delegates and is expected to meet with African
delegates next week.
   Perez de Cuellar and U.N. staff officials have said the United
Nations could become insolvent by late October if members don't pay
what they owe.
   The United States is responsible for most of the debt. It owes
$467 million of the $691 million outstanding.
   Most of the U.S. money has been withheld in the past few years
due to congressional disagreements with U.N. policies and
operations and in an attempt to influence Soviet personnel policy
at the world body.
   The Soviet Union has launched a campaign over the past year to
increase its influence and standing at the United Nations. It has
paid off about $60 million in arrears to the regular budget and is
beginning to repay about $200 million it owed for peacekeeping
operations, which come under a separate budget.
   The United States has traditionally been assessed one-fourth of
the annual U.N. budget of nearly $1 billion. The U.N. money comes
from assessments of member nations, which are based on the nations'
wealth.
   Congress in 1985 passed an amendment to the budget bill,
sponsored by Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., and Rep. Gerald Solomon,
R-N.Y., that allows the withholding of part of the U.S. dues to the
United Nations.
   Part of the dues are paid when assessed, but the majority are
withheld until the president informs Congress that adequate
progress is being made on cutting the U.N. staff by 15 percent and
other budgetary reforms and that more Soviet U.N. employees are
shifted from short-term contracts to long-term international civil
servant status.
   The goal of the U.S. demand for the Soviet personnel policy
change is to make Soviet staff loyal to the international civil
service and independent of Moscow's goals.
   Until recently, nearly all Soviets were rotated through the
United Nations on contracts of fewer than five years. In May,
however, the Soviet deputy foreign minister, Vladimir Petrovsky,
announced that more Soviets would be allowed to sign ``permanent
contracts'' with the U.N. Secretariat.
   That statement would appear to meet the last serious objection
that U.S. officials had to paying the full U.N. dues assessment.
   Satisfactory progress has been made on the personnel cuts and
budgetary reforms, said a U.S. official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   One U.N. staff official suggested that if the United States
continued to withhold funds, perhaps the Soviets would allow the
early payment of the second half of their annual dues, which they
usually pay in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
