<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson-Bush     06-17 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson-Bush,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Urges Supporters To Work For Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson on Friday urged
conservative Minnesota Republicans who supported his presidential
candidacy to back Vice President George Bush in the November
election.
   ``It matters whether the man in the White House is a mediocre
liberal who returns us to the policies of Jimmy Carter, or a
distinguished conservative who builds upon the foundation of a
great Republican, Ronald Reagan,'' he said.
   Robertson, who has returned to religious broadcasting since
dropping out of the Republican presidential race, received an
enthusiastic welcome from the approximately 2,000 delegates at the
state convention. He placed second to Sen. Bob Dole in Minnesota's
Feb. 23 caucuses.
   Robertson received a standing ovation when he attacked
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who has sewn up the Democratic
presidential nomination, as a member of the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   ``I don't want a president in the White House putting in ACLU
lawyers as federal judges and Supreme Court judges,'' Robertson
said. ``We absolutely must oppose him on that ground.''
   Robertson told a news conference before his speech that he's
``delighted with the sense of harmony'' among Republicans he sees
within every state he visits.
   ``I'm looking forward to George Bush's election,'' he said. ``I
know it will be close, but I believe the gap between George Bush
and Michael Dukakis will be closing.''
   Robertson said he prefers Dole for Bush's running mate.
   ``A Bush-Dole ticket would be virtually unbeatable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
