<DOCNO> AP880617-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Sharpeville     06-17 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Sharpeville,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Urges Clemency For Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Friday appealed to
the South African government to grant mercy to the Sharpeville Six,
who have been sentenced to hang for the death of a town councilor.
   The United States, which sometimes vetoes measures against South
Africa, joined in the plea. It was a clear signal to the Pretoria
government of Washington's displeasure with plans to carry out the
death sentences.
   The resolution was adopted unanimously without debate. The
15-member council said it was convinced the executions would
``further inflame an already grave situation in South Africa.''
   It called ``once again upon the South African authorities to
stay execution and commute the death sentences imposed on the
Sharpeville Six.'' It was the second time in three months the
council has passed such a resolution.
   South African Ambassador A. Leslie Manley criticized the action.
``This is blatant interference in the internal affairs of a member
state of the United Nations,'' Manley said.
   South Africa has ignored worldwide appeals for clemency for the
six blacks, who were convicted in the 1984 death of a Sharpeville
town councilor killed during a riot. They were not found guilty of
physical involvement in the slaying but were convicted on the basis
of their involvement with the rioters.
   ``This council decision was taken in contravention of the
charter of the U.N. This is entirely an internal matter which is
the subject of due process of law in South Africa,'' Manley said in
a telephone interview.
   The Dutch government Friday also urged South Africa to commute
the death sentences. South African Ambassador Frank Quint was
summoned to the Dutch Foreign Ministry, where top official Henri
Wijnaendts asked for clemency for the five men and one woman.
   A stay of execution was granted March 17, the day before the six
were to hang, and last week a judge extended the stay until July 19
but rejected a request to reopen their trial.
   On March 16, the Security Council adopted a resolution identical
to that approved Friday.
   The council expressed ``grave concern'' at the deteriorating
situation in South Africa, saying the human suffering resulted from
the apartheid system of racial segregation and the state of
emergency.
   The members of the council are the United States, Britain,
China, France, the Soviet Union, Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Italy,
Japan, Nepal, Senegal, West Germany, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RevolvingDoor     06-17 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Revolving Door,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1987 `Revolving Door' Law Was Aimed at Military-Contractor Job
Shifts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress tried to slow down the movement of
Defense Department procurement officials to civilian defense
contractors with a 1987 law.
   But a growing investigation of possible Pentagon and contractor
bribery raises questions about how the revolving door law is
working.
   The law says Pentagon procurement officials must wait two years
after leaving the government before the may work for defense
contractors with whom they had major contact in the last two years
of federal service.
   Since the statute did not take effect until April 15, 1987, it
is not clear how many of those involved in the budding Pentagon
investigation were covered by the law's restrictions. There were
reports that some Pentagon officials quit before the effective date
to avoid its provisions.
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., a sponsor of the legislation, has
asked the Pentagon's deputy inspector general, Derek Vander Schaaf,
to determine ``whether there is cause to believe'' that anyone
named by the FBI as under investigation in the case may have
violated the revolving door law.
   One provision of the law applies to mid-level civilian or
military defense procurement officials. They fall under the
two-year ban if they spent the majority of their work during their
last two years at a defense contractor's plant, or working on a
major weapons system the contractor was selling.
   Another section forces the two-year waiting period on high-level
officials who acted as government representatives in the
negotiation or settlement of a contract of more than $10 million.
   This applies to anyone who was a decisionmaker, even if he did
not have official responsibility for the negotiations.
   Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla., a prime sponsor, said this
provision applied to cases such as the high-ranking Navy Department
officials who negotiated multimillion-dollar deals with General
Dynamics, and then went to work for that corporation.
   The law requires that companies submit to the secretary of
defense the names of former Pentagon officials now working for the
defense contractors.
   Penalty provisions include a civil fine of up to $500,000 for
companies offering compensation to an official it knows is covered
by the restrictions.
   The official can receive a civil fine of up to $250,000.
   When the 1987 law was passed, the strongest advocates of closing
the ``revolving door'' blamed the procurement system for the
problem _ not the integrity of individuals.
   Even that has changed, now that a search warrant has revealed
that the government is investigating the ``bribery of public
officials'' as part of a scheme in which defense contractors got
inside information from former government officials whom they had
hired as consultants.
   Taking note of the change, Boxer said in a floor speech this
week, ``Now, it is bad enough that such a situation undermines
public confidence in the procurement system.
   ``It is far worse to learn that former and current public
officials may have broken the law in a rush to cash in on the
contracts that they gained at taxpayers' expense. Nothing could be
lower than that.''
   An illustration of the revolving door is the case of Melvyn R.
Paisley, a major target in the current investigation.
   He left his Navy job in April 1987 to become a Washington
consultant, and some of the largest defense contractors lined up to
hire him.
   Paisley, 63, had played a key role in President Reagan's naval
build-up. As a private executive, he was selling information, a
commodity much in demand among the various companies seeking any
edge they could get in the competition to sell weapons to the
government.
   A General Accounting Office study in 1986 said more than 20
percent of the people who left jobs at the Pentagon in 1983 and
1984 to join defense contractors were spending at least some time
working on the same projects they had overseen for the government.
   The study said 45 percent of the former Pentagon employees said
their new jobs in industry required them to communicate with former
colleagues at the Pentagon, and 26 percent acknowledged they were
in positions to affect the work of their future employer during
their last two years at the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
