<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Libya-Terrorism     06-17 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Terrorism,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United States Protests Release of Suspected Terrorists by Senegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States protested to Senegal on
Friday for dropping charges against two Libyans arrested for
allegedly carrying explosives.
   ``The government of Senegal released, without trial, two known
Libyan terrorists caught red-handed in Dakar Airport last February
attempting to smuggle arms and explosives into Senegal,'' State
Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   The two men were sent back to Libya on Thursday, according to
official spokesmen in Dakar.
   ``We're extremely disappointed by Senegal's action,'' Redman
said. ``It raises questions about that country's commitment to the
struggle against international terrorism.''
   He said U.S. ``dissatisfaction'' was communicated through
diplomatic channels.
   The Libyans, Mohamed Abdou Salam and Mansour Oumrane, were
arrested on arrival in the West African country on Feb. 19 after
customs inspectors allegedly found the weapons in baggage.
   In past years, Senegal has criticized Libya for its involvement
in fighting in Chad, but Senegalese President Abdou Diouf, elected
to a second term recently, has said relations between his country
and Libya have ``considerably improved.''
   State Department officials have said the arrests in Senegal were
evidence of a possible renewal of terrorism sponsored by the Libyan
government of Moammar Gadhafi.
   The officials said Libyan involvement was suspected in attacks
in Europe and Asia earlier this spring, around the time of the
anniversary of the April 1985 U.S. bombing raid against Gadhafi
strongholds in Tripoli and Benghazi.
</TEXT>
