<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   06-17 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill One, Wound 18, In Pre-Dawn West Bank Raid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fired on
stone-throwing Palestinians who tried to stop them from blowing up
an Arab's home Friday, killing one and wounding 18, hospital
officials and witnesses said.
   Army officials confirmed the death but said only four Arabs were
wounded. They said two soldiers were injured by stones in the
confrontation before dawn at Beit Furik, five miles southeast of
Nablus in the occupied West Bank.
   At least 209 Palestinians have been killed in the rebellion that
began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war. An Israeli soldier and a
Jewish settler also have been slain.
   Troops demolished seven other homes in the West Bank and sealed
10 during a 24-hour period ending Friday. Most belonged to
Palestinians suspected of throwing firebombs.
   Increased use of firebombs in recent weeks prompted army
officials to order harsher punishments, including house demolitions
and sealings. Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said this week the
army considers firebombs lethal weapons to which soldiers and
Israeli civilians could respond with gunfire.
   Israeli soldiers entered Beit Furik at about 4 a.m. to destroy
the home of Ahmed Hanani, an alleged member of a gang that
assassinated Nablus Mayor Zafer Masri in March 1986 and carried out
attacks on Israelis, the army said.
   Rafaq Yusef Masmoud, a 25-year-old villager, said young men
guarding the village alerted residents with portable loudspeakers
and about 700 armed with rocks and bottles rushed into the streets
to face about 100 soldiers.
   He said the troopers opened fire and the ensuing street battle
continued for about four hours. Masmoud, who was shot in the right
leg, spoke to The Associated Press from his bed at Al Ittihad
Hospital in Nablus.
   The house was blown up about two hours after the Israelis
arrived and ``I saw a big cloud go up into the sky,'' Masmoud said.
``After the house exploded, the fighting really picked up.''
   Bahar Khareb, 15, said he and four friends rushed outside when
the soldiers came.
   ``We threw stones at a passing jeep,'' said Khareb, a slight
youngster who was wounded in the right shoulder and spoke
haltingly. ``The jeep stopped. An officer stood up and fired
directly at us from about 15 meters. He hit all five of us.''
   An army official said soldiers entering Beit Furik encountered
roadblocks and ``masses of villagers who attacked the force with
bottles, cement blocks and stones.''
   Five Arabs were detained, the army reported. Masmoud said he saw
soldiers taking 20 villagers away.
   Two army jeeps were parked at a roadblock outside Beit Furik
later Friday and soldiers barred reporters from the village.
   A doctor at Al Ittihad said five of the 18 people wounded by
gunfire were in serious condition. They said the victims a
22-year-old woman who was shot in the throat and paralyzed from the
chest down.
   Casualties were brought to the hospital throughout the morning.
About five hours after the battle, an 18-year-old arrived in the
emergency room with a bullet wound in the right leg.
   The young man, his face contorted with pain, said he walked
miles on back roads to avoid soldiers.
   Rabin said Thursday that the emphasis in the rebellion has
shifted from mass demonstrations to commercial strikes, civil
disobedience and individual acts of firebombing and stoning.
   ``The firebombs are the most disturbing problem,'' Maj. Gen.
Amram Mitzna, army commander in the West Bank, told Israel radio.
``We shall do everything possible to stop this phenomenon.''
   Mahmoud Shalabiye of Jericho in the West Bank said soldiers
knocked on his door at midnight Thursday and told him to remove his
belongings so they could seal the house.
   ``I have eight children at home and now they want to throw me to
the street ... because my son made a firebomb,'' he said on the
radio. ``I don't know what he does. He is 18 years old.''
   Jewish settlers said the army should be tougher. ``We are asking
to deport people who throw firebombs,'' Uri Ariel, head of the West
Bank settlement council, told the radio.
   Israel has deported 21 Arabs during the rebellion, most on
charges of inciting anti-Israeli violence.
</TEXT>
