<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Apartheid-Cher     06-17 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apartheid-Cher,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cher Taken Off List after Promising Not to Perform in South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher, the actress and entertainer, once
performed in South Africa but has been taken off a list kept by the
U.N. anti-apartheid agency because she promised not to do so again.
   The list contains the names of more than 200 performers and
members of related professions who have worked in South Africa
since 1981. A person can be taken off by promising in writing not
to perform there while the government practices the apartheid
policy of race segregation.
   The sixth annual list will be published next month. Frank
Sinatra, Tina Turner, Eartha Kitt and others were removed earlier
this year.
   Sotirios G. Mousouris, assistant secretary-general of the U.N.
Center Against Apartheid, said Friday the letter from Cher
responded to one he wrote to the actress.
   In an interview, he said he congratulated her on the Academy
Award she won for her performance in ``Moonstruck.''
   After telling Cher ``her career had been marked by sensitivity
and talent and her roles in `Silkwood,' `Mask' and `Suspect' show
her concern about injustice and oppression,'' he expressed surprise
that her name was on the list.
   Mousouris said he suggested that she might be unaware of it,
since the listing dated from a performance in August 1981.
   In a letter dated May 25, Cher wrote: ``This is to state that I
shall not be performing in South Africa as long as apartheid lasts
in that country.''
   The list's purpose is to persuade performers to join the boycott
and inform countries, groups and individuals about those who work
in South Africa.
   ``Most artists are sensitive to the issue of racial justice and
would want to be removed,'' Mousouris said, adding that Linda
Ronstadt, Goldie Hawn and Telly Savalas were among those to whom he
would write letters similar to the one he sent Cher.
   Fighting apartheid has been a major cause in the U.N. General
Assembly and Security Council, which have condemned the race laws
that preserve power for South Africa's 5 million whites and deny a
voice in national affairs to the 26 million blacks.
   On Sept. 2-4, the U.N. Special Committee Against Apartheid will
sponsor a meeting in Athens at which prominent artists, performers,
theater and movie directors and writers will discuss the cultural
boycott.
   Among about 30 people expected to attend are Harry Belafonte,
Jules Dassin, Yves Montand and Joseph Papp.
</TEXT>
