<HEAD>Thirsty Marijuana Plants Wilting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVONIA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought in Michigan is leaving
marijuana growers dry but not high.
   The state is entering the prime growing season for the illegal
but profitable weed and the thirsty plants need a lot of water,
said State Police Lt. Roy Vernier.
   ``They're either going to have to irrigate or their crop will be
very low,'' said Vernier, director of a program called Help
Eliminate Marijuana Planting. ``They won't have the harvest if the
drought continues.''
   Last year, police seized 82,000 plants through anonymous tips to
the HEMP program. Vernier said 90 people were arrested and 20
weapons were confiscated.
