<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-17 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAOLI, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His favorite color is green and he likes
basketball, but Larry Joe Bird the monkey is a pet, not an NBA
player.
   The guenon, a long-tailed monkey native to Africa, is named for
Larry Bird, a forward with the Boston Celtics and a native of
nearby French Lick.
   Linda Tuell said her husband, Brad, came up with the name.
   ``They were good friends in high school, both playing ball at
the same time,'' she said. ``Larry played for Springs Valley and
Brad played at Paoli.''
   Good behavior isn't the 2-year-old monkey's strong suit. Even
when tethered to a leash he manages to jump on furniture, whack
visitors on the face and steal things from their hands.
   Larry Joe stays in a cage in his own bedroom, which is decorated
with Celtics memorabilia, while Mrs. Tuell works at her family's
restaurant.
   ``He's such a character, we really have a lot of fun with him,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIOLA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnesota may be known as the Gopher State
but this small township celebrates a bounty hunt to get rid of the
pesky rodents.
   Township officials collected more than 1,300 pairs of gopher
feet Thursday and doled out $1,377 to kick off the 114th annual
Viola Gopher Count.
   The township pays $1 each for a pair of feet from a pocket
gopher, and 25 cents for two pairs from striped gophers.
   Townspeople say it's worth it.
   ``Pockets are a problem in a hayfield,'' said township board
member Richard Brennan. ``They build mounds that high,'' he said,
raising his hands 8 inches off the table, ``and it's rough. You
can't mow it, and it's tough on the machines.''
   Hunters of all ages carried their bounty to the township
Thursday in freezer bags, socks, cigar boxes and buckets. One had
his nailed to a board in pairs for easy counting.
   This year's champion bounty hunter was Lyle Splittstoesser, 71.
He turned in 374 sets of feet worth $335.75. But because
Splittstoesser always turns in several hundred sets, he is
considered a ``professional'' and doesn't qualify for the
championship prize of $10.
   The township, near Rochester in the southeastern corner of the
state, has celebrated the hunt ever since a group of residents
gathered for a lemonade picnic in a pasture in 1874 and agreed to a
competition to see who could collect the most gopher tails by the
next year.
</TEXT>
