<HEAD>Red Army Member Indicted In 1970 Hijacking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors indicted an alleged terrorist of the
Japanese Red Army on Friday in the hijacking of a Japanese jetliner
to North Korea 18 years ago, an official said.
   Yashuhiro Shibata was indicted by the Tokyo District
Prosecutor's office, said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. He said a convicted hijacker not charged with murder
faces a maximum term of life in prison.
   Shibata was arrested in Tokyo on May 6 with a false passport.
Police believe he returned to Japan in April 1985 from North Korea.
   Shibata, then 16 years old, was one of nine alleged Red Army
members who hijacked a Japan Air Lines Boeing 727 to the North
Korean capital of Pyongyang in 1970. The hijackers released all 138
aboard in exchange for a Japanese vice transport minister.
   The official would not discuss whether Shibata or members of the
group were planning terrorist action before or during the Olympic
Games scheduled for Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in Seoul, South Korea.
   Shibata's arrest and the recent arrests of several other
self-confessed or alleged members of Japan's Red Army have raised
concerns the radical leftist terrorist group may be planning
attacks at the Olympics.
   Seiroku Kajiyama, chairman of the National Public Safety
Commission, said Wednesday that the Red Army, which had been
dormant, is ``stepping up their activities and it is quite natural
that we think they have Seoul as a target.''
