<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParchutistMemorial     06-17 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parchutist Memorial,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parachutist Who Gave Life To Save Student's Honored at Memorial
Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHELBURNE, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parachuting instructor and aerial
acrobat who died while saving a student making her first jump was
honored Friday at the airport where he was killed.
   Walter ``Hawk'' Leno, 45, of Bolton, was an ultralight
enthusiast, stuntman and instructor who held records for his
airborne acrobatics. His dramatic rescue and death Saturday was
captured on videotape by the student's husband.
   ``Hawk did a lot for the sport (parachuting) in Vermont, said
Ray Beresford, Leno's jumping partner for the past five years.
   ``He exposed a lot of people to it who wouldn't have learned
about it otherwise. It's unfortunate he had to die this way. It's
just what he didn't want,'' Beresford told the friends and admirers
at Shelburne Airport, the base for most of Leno's flying and
jumping.
   Authorities have refused to release the name of the student,
whose parachute jump was a gift from her husband.
   The footage taken by the husband shows Leno and the woman
falling end over end as they left the plane at 4,000 feet, said
state police investigator Leo Blais.
   Blais, who reviewed the videotape with a U.S. Parachutists
Association official, said the student's primary chute became
caught between her legs. She and Leno tried to loosen it, and Leno
finally pulled her emergency chute at about 600 feet, he said.
   Leno, however, could not pull his chute at the same time because
the two might have become entangled and neither would have worked,
Blais said.
   ``But by the time he cleared her he was at just 200 feet and by
the time he pulled his chute open he had hit,'' he said.
   It was just 23 seconds from the time Leno and his student jumped
until he hit the ground. He was traveling 130 mph at impact, Blais
said.
   He said the student suffered injury to her tailbone.
   ``It's very clear from the video that he gave up his life to
save hers,'' said Blais.
   Leno launched his own business, Barnstormers Aviation, last
year. He assembled and sold ultralight planes and did jumps for
parties, county fairs and weddings.
</TEXT>
