<HEAD>Family of Irish Hostage Appeals To Kidnappers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother and sisters of Irish hostage
Brian Keenan appealed in a Beirut newspaper Friday to the
kidnappers to declare their demands for his release.
   ``More than two years have lapsed since the disappearance of our
son and brother in Beirut,'' said the appeal, published in the
An-Nahar newspaper.
   The letter was signed by Maria Keenan, the hostage's mother, and
her two daughters, Brenda Geilham and Eliane Spinneys.
   ``Despite the fears we have suffered during this period, we
still hope that Brian will be freed and return to his family in
Ireland soon,'' they said.
   ``We have addressed previous appeals through the media in
Lebanon for information about the fate of Brian Keenan. But no one
has come forth with any information about him,'' they said. ``If
you are not prepared to free him, we ask you to declare what should
be done so that he regains his freedom.
   ``We are poor people, but are willing to do everything we can to
help Brian.''
   Keenan, 36, of Belfast, worked as an English-language teacher at
the American University of Beirut. He was kidnapped on April 11,
1986. No group has claimed reponsibility for his abduction.
   Seventeen other foreigners are held hostage in Lebanon. They are
nine Americans, three Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Indian
and two unidentified men.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was abducted March 16,
1985.
