<1ST_LINE>u a AM-KellnerProfile Bjt   06-17 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kellner Profile, Bjt,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Attorney Who Indicted Noriega Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During his tenure as U.S. attorney, Leon Kellner
saw an indictment against Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and
drug charges against officials in Haiti, Nicaragua, Bolivia, the
Bahamas, Turks and Caicos, Suriname and Cuba.
   ``I had no inkling I would be at the eye of the hurricane, and I
still have trouble understanding it,'' Kellner said before his last
day in office, Friday. ``I'm not doing anything profound _ I just
take a case where the evidence leads.''
   Kellner spent three years as an assistant and three years as
chief prosecutor in the Southern District of Florida, among the
busiest federal districts in the nation.
   Kellner's office indicted leaders of the Colombia-based Medellin
Cartel, responsible for up to 80 percent of U.S. cocaine imports.
And he successfully prosecuted scores of Miami police who ran a
drug-ripoff ring.
   Kellner, 42, who usually is very serious and low-key but flashes
an occasional ironic smile, is proud he aimed for the leaders of
drug rings, but says only drying up the demand can really stem
trafficking.
   ``When I became U.S. attorney, one of the things I wanted do was
go as high up in the narcotics trafficking business as I could,''
said Kellner. ``And I think that's what I did.''
   But not without personal danger.
   His most chilling moments came after the extradition of Medellin
Cartel leader Carlos Lehder Rivas, when SWAT teams and federal
agents responding to death threats were sent to guard him and his
family against possible reprisals from the violent drug ring. His
family fled their Coral Gables home and, for a time, had to be
escorted on routine errands.
   ``What is interesting about that episode is that ... the
government was prepared to do anything, no matter what the cost, to
ensure the safety'' of people working on the case, says Kellner,
whose Jewish parents fled Nazi Germany before World War II.
   He contrasts that with the violence the cartel has wreaked on
Colombia, where a justice minister, an attorney general and
hundreds of other law enforcement officials have been gunned down.
   That experience made him even more militant on winning
extradition rights from countries which have been traditional
havens for traffickers.
   ``The reason extradition is so important in my mind is that
there is a recognition that foreign countries ... do not enforce
their own laws because of the power of the cartel, the threats of
the cartel,'' he says.
   The Noriega indictment and the subequent political firestorm
over negotations to drop the charges forced Kellner to take a
strong public stand against politicizing law enforcement. But he is
understanding of the administration's problems.
   ``What that flap indicates is the extraordinary problems that we
have in dealing with narcotics in the international sphere,'' he
says. ``This is the most unique problem that law enforcement has
ever dealt with.''
   Kellner differs strongly with those who say legalization of
drugs could solve problems stemming from the drug trade.
   While drugs have been the focus of most of his attention, one of
the most professionally painful moments of his tenure came over
another high-profile investigation, into arms smuggling to the
Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   Critics accused him of buckling under to the Reagan
administration and stalling an investigation of a 1985 weapons
shipment to the Contras out of Fort Lauderdale. But Kellner notes
he has been cleared by every investigation into that case. And an
indictment in the case is expected later this month.
   Those criticisms, his wife's bout with thyroid cancer from which
she is recovering, the Noriega drama and his inability to stem drug
trafficking eventually took their toll on Kellner, however.
   After taking the summer off with his family, Kellner will return
to Washington to rejoin the firm he helped found, Anderson, Baker,
Kill & Olick. ``There comes a point when I get frustrated,'' says
Kellner. ``I did the job for six years ... sometimes you just have
to recharge your batteries.''
</TEXT>
