<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Shipwreck,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunken Dutch Ship With Chemical Agent Righted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IJMUIDEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch salvage workers using a huge
floating crane Friday righted the wreck of a sunken tanker loaded
with a dangerous chemical, the Traffic Ministry said.
   Operations were continuing to float the Dutch-flagged Anna
Broere and empty its cargo of highly inflammable and toxic arcylon
nitryl, said ministry spokesman Bruno Voskuyl.
   None of the chemical, which is used by the plastics industry,
had leaked so far, Voskuyl said.
   Workers of the Smit-Tak salvage company attached reinforced
steel cables around its hull and righted the wreck with the crane,
Voskuyl said.
   The ship, carrying 1,600 tons of the chemical agent, sank about
55 miles off the North Sea port after it and the Swedish-flagged
freighter Atlantic Compass collided.
   There were no injuries in the accident.
</TEXT>
