<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     06-17 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Release Children Unharmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter and two sons of a wealthy
Lebanese jeweler who were kidnapped three days ago by gunmen
demanding $3 million in ransom were freed Friday and returned home
safely.
   It was not known whether their father, Zuheir Ariss, paid the
ransom the kidnappers demanded in a telephone call.
   Interior Minister Abdullah Rassi said the kidnappers had not
been arrested but that the investigation was continuing.
   The children, who were snatched Tuesday from their
chauffeur-driven Mercedes in west Beirut, said they were not hurt
during their captivity.
   ``We had chicken for breakfast, lunch and dinner for the past
three days. I don't want to see chicken for the rest of my life,''
9-year-old Samer Ariss said at his home on west Beirut's Hamra
Street.
   Ramzi, 5, said he missed his parents and was very frightened
``because we were locked in a room filled with cockroaches and
ants.''
   ``They (the kidnappers) did not hurt us,'' said his sister,
Dana, 14.
   A police spokesman said mediators from the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, handed the children to Brig. Gen. Ali
Hammoud, the Syrian army's intelligence chief in Beirut, and
Lebanese police chief Col. Issam Abu Ziki at the Syrian army
command in Beirut on Friday morning.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing
regulations, said Hammoud and Ziki delivered the children to their
home about 40 minutes later.
   Ariss owns a plush jewelry shop and a money exchange company.
   In a statement broadcast by the Moslem Voice of the Nation
radio, Ariss expressed ``gratitude to all those who helped achieve
the release of my children.''
   ``We thank God because this ordeal was brought to an end. We
thank God for the safe return of our three children,'' he said.
   Ziki refused to say if the ransom demand was met or to elaborate
on how the children were freed from the kidnappers.
   In a separate development Friday, police said seven people were
wounded overnight in sporadic machine gun fire between followers of
Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization and members of
the Syrian-backed anti-Arafat faction called Fatah-Uprising.
   The new casualties brought the overall toll to 31 killed and 137
wounded in the latest round of fighting for control of Chatilla and
Bourj el-Barajneh camps.
   A police spokesman said two Libyan military observers entered
Chatilla on Friday to try to enforce a cease-fire and disengage the
combatants. Two other Libyans were to enter Bourj el-Barajneh later.
   Libya is an ally of both Arafat and Syrian President Hafez
Assad. Its leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, played a key role in
bringing Assad and Arafat to meet in a reconciliation effort in
April.
   Palestinian sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Arafat had sent a letter to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
discussing ways of ending fighting in the camps between his
fighters and those of the Syrian-backed breakaway faction led by
Col. Saeed Moussa.
   Assad, a Soviet friend, and Arafat have been bitter enemies
since Syria backed the May 1983 uprising against Arafat.
</TEXT>
