<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BiotechnologyResearch     06-17 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biotechnology Research,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Biotechnology Bill 88-1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill that some believe is the first step of
a $3 billion project to map the human genetic pattern passed the
Senate Friday by a vote of 88 to 1.
   The legislation, called the Biotechnology Competitiveness Act,
does not authorize the start of any laboratory research, but
experts in the biotechnology field said the bill creates a
framework that would enable the start of a major genetic project in
about two years.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., cast the single dissenting vote.
   The bill has four major provisions. These are:
   _Establish a 20-member national biotechnology policy board to
review federal research support efforts and to make recommendations
on biotechnology issues. The first report to the president and to
Congress is due by Jan. 31, 1990.
   _Establish an advisory panel on the human genome that will
develop a strategy needed for a project to map and sequence the
human genome, or genetic pattern. Experts say that a crash program
of research on the genome would take seven to 10 years and cost
about $3 billion.
   _Establish a $10 million biotechnology information center at the
National Library of Medicine.
   _And, finally, the bill would reauthorize a biomedical ethics
board that would analyze the reports of the biotechnology policy
board and the human genome advisory panel.
   Provisions in the bill are estimated to cost $10.4 million in
fiscal year 1989, which begins in October. The cost would rise to
$14.2 million in 1990, $15.4 million in 1991, and $13 million
annually for the following two yeasrs.
   Richard D. Godown, president of the Industrial Biotechnology
Association, said the 88 to 1 vote ``shows the overwhelming support
of the United States for the biotechnology industry.''
   Godown said that establishing the boards and panels described in
the bill are essential for organizing the genome research, a
project that may involve hundreds of laboratories and thousands of
scientists.
   ``This clears the way for the money to be appropriated later,''
he said. Godown said it may be two years before the project is
organized, but that the organizational structure established by the
bill is the first step.
   Godown said that private industry and some federal laboratories
already are studying the human genome and this work will continue
while the committees conduct their studies.
   The human genome is the genetic pattern contained in the human
chromosones. The pattern, which is unique to each individual,
determines fundamental physical characteristics. Many diseases are
related to genetic patterns and scientists hope that by
understanding the genome that these diseases can be treated or
prevented.
   Godown said understanding the genome is fundamental to the
revolution occurring in biotechnology.
   ``Mapping the sequence of the human genome will determine the
degree of success we realize from the biotechnology revolution,''
he said. By understanding the genetic pattern, Godown said,
scientists will significantly advance an understanding of how the
human body works.
   The bill was drawn up after studies by scientists at the
National Research Council strongly supported a federally funded
effort to map and sequence the human genome.
   One major consideration supporting the genome research is
international competition.
   The Department of Commerce has estimated that the market for
biotechnology products _ which would include pharmaceuticals and
agricultural products _ will exceed $40 billion a year by 2000.
France, Germany and Japan already have national biotechnology
programs which includes human genome research.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1705EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uganda     06-17 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 1,600 POWs Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER WASSWA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,600 rebels were freed from
Ugandan prisons on Friday on the orders of President Yoweri
Museveni, the government said.
   The release is expected to improve Museveni's efforts to
organize peace talks with several rebel armies fighting his
government in the north and east of Uganda, Western analysts told
The Associated Press.
   The Internal Affairs Ministry said the guerrillas were freed
following a directive by Museveni earlier this week that 1,671
prisoners of war be freed.
   Most of the prisoners were fighting for the Uganda People's
Democratic Movement, a northern-based guerrilla force. They were
held without charge after being captured in clashes with government
troops.
   Museveni evidently ordered their release as a concession to
guerrilla leaders with whom government envoys have made contact in
a bid for peace in Uganda. The country has been convulsed by civil
conflicts almost constantly since its independence from Britain on
Oct. 9, 1962.
   Museveni seized power in January 1986, ending a five-year war
against civilian president Milton Obote and the military junta that
ousted Obote in July 1985. Museveni formed a government of national
unity, inviting four other rival parties to join his Cabinet.
   In September and October 1986, soldiers arrested several men on
treason charges of plotting a coup. Courts have released most of
the men for lack of evidence.
   Soldiers loyal to Obote and other toppled Ugandan leaders,
including former military dictator Idi Amin, have mounted guerrilla
operations against Museveni's government since August 1986.
   Amin lives in exile in Saudi Arabia and Obote in Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1722EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Congress     06-17 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Congress,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Battle Plan To Combat Drought Urged by Capitol Hill Task Force</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought that is curling corn leaves and
darkening wheat fields across the nation's heartland calls for a
blueprint for aiding farmers and guarding against stepped up food
prices, lawmakers said Friday.
   ``We have to have a battle plan before too long,'' Sen. David
Pryor, D-Ark., said as a congressional task force met with
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng to discuss possible means of
responding to the drought.
   The bipartisan House-Senate task force was formed this week to
monitor the drought and its effect on crops and to prepare
recommendations for congressional action if that should prove
necessary.
   Lyng has been saying lawmakers should wait to learn more about
the full extent of the damage before they begin to formulate aid
legislation.
   USDA officials reiterated that much of the wheat crop in Montana
and the Dakotas already is severely damaged, but an inch or so of
rain once a week for the rest of the growing season could save the
Midwest's corn and soybean crops.
   ``We need teamwork, Repoublican and Democrat, House and Senate
and the administration to make sure that the federal government
responds to the catastrophe that many American farmers today
face,'' House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la
Garza, D-Texas, said.
   He said the goals of the task force should be to assess the
impact on trade and food prices and to formulate recommendations
for farm aid.
   De la Garza applauded Lyng for a decision Thursday to loosen
USDA rules to allow farmers to cut hay on Conservation Reserve
Program acreage. He had earlier resisted such a step, saying
growers already had been paid by the government to keep the highly
erodible lands out of production for a decade.
   De la Garza called Lyng's decision a ``first step.'' A number of
lawmakers have been calling for livestock grazing on the acreage.
   A Senate Agriculture Committee contingent planned to visit wheat
country over the weekend for first-hand inspections of drought
damage.
   Pryor said the task force should not overlook the health effect
``that the long-protracted heat wave has on the rural elderly.''
   Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., said the task force should look into
the possibility of cooperation between federal and local
governments as well as the private sector on providing irrigation
to farmers who are without it.
   Sens. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and Thad Cochran, R-Miss., called on
Lyng to look into some way of utilizing the Federal Crop Insurance
Program to aid farmers caught in a complex financial bind by the
drought.
   Because the drought threatens to make agricultural commodities
scarce, it already is driving up their prices. But higher prices,
in turn, are likely to shrink federal income-support payments that
growers receive.
   The payments are the difference between market prices and
higher, target prices set by Congress and adjusted by the secretary
of agriculture. As the difference narrows, the farmer's payment
shrinks. Meanwhile, the drought may leave the grower without a crop
to sell at the higher market levels.
   The problem is even worse for many farmers who have received
part of their income-support payments in advance and now are faced
with the prospect of having to repay part of them.
   Harkin said it might be possible to reopen the sign-up period
for obtaining federal crop insurance.
   Officials said it would be worthwhile to explore ways that the
crop insurance system might be useful. But they added that there
could be problems.
   ``If we move into some kind of a relief package, we need to
recognize those who did have the willingness to buy crop
insurance,'' Lyng said. ``But at the same time we cannot ignore
those who did not.''
</TEXT>
