<HEAD>Fire Endurance Test Canceled After 1 Candidate Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to CORRECT that seven were sickened on
several occasions, and update that two remain hospitalized,
symptoms.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health experts are trying to determine why a
firefighter candidate died and six others became ill after
completing recent grueling physical endurance tests, officials said
Friday.
   ``We have no idea at this point what caused it. That's why we
have medical people and others looking into it. They're looking at
everything,'' said Fire Department personnel spokeswoman Magda
Gandasegui.
   As a result of the incidents, the department has suspended
further tests of prospective firefighters. ``We're going on a
day-to-day basis,'' Ms. Gandasegui said. ``We don't know when we'll
resume.''
   She said the firefighter candidates became ill after tests
conducted on different occasions this month.
   The physican endurance test ``a very demanding test,'' Ms.
Gandasegui said. ``It simulates the job of a firefighter, so we
expect our candidates are physically fit.''
   During the test, would-be firefighters wear 40 pounds of gear
while scaling walls, carring a 145-pound dummy, breaking down a
door and dragging 57 pounds of hose.
   She said the seven candidates were taken to St. Luke's-Roosevelt
Medical Center at different times. One candidate died June 11
shortly after arriving at the hospital.
   Autopsy results were inconclusive, and the cause of death was
not ascertained pending the results of further tests, said Ellen
Borakove, a spokeswoman for the medical examiner's office.
   The others were not seriously ill; two remained hospitalized in
good condition, said hospital spokeswoman Judy Murphy. She said the
patients were treated for mild-to-moderate kidney disease, caused
by physical exertion. She said the effects are reversible.
   Experts from the city Health Department and fire officials were
examining the room where the test was conducted to see if there was
any connection.
   Ms. Gandasegui said more than 5,000 candidates have completed
the test that was to run May 31 through July.
</TEXT>
