<HEAD>TV Academy Honors Cartoon Animators Hanna and Barbera</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Hanna and Joseph Barbera,
television's premiere cartoon animators and creators of the movie's
``Tom and Jerry,'' have been voted the Governors Award by the
Academy of Television Arts & Sciences.
   They will receive the award during the 40th Annual Primetime
Emmy Awards presentation Aug. 28, Doug Duitsman, academy president,
announced Friday.
   Hanna and Barbera are the founders and chief executives of
Hanna-Barbera Productions, a leading producer of animated
entertainment. Their company, founded in 1957, has produced
``Huckleberry Hound,'' ``Quick Draw McGraw,'' ``The Flintstones,''
``The Jetsons,'' ``Johnny Quest'' and ``The Smurfs.''
   Hanna had worked on the original ``Looney Tunes'' and ``Merrie
Melodies'' and joined MGM in 1937. There he teamed up with Barbera
to create ``Tom and Jerry,'' winner of seven Academy Awards and one
of the most popular movie cartoon series.
