<DOCNO> AP880617-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1759EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ScienceFoundation     06-17 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Science Foundation,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Authorizes $2 Billion for National Science Foundation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Friday approved a bill
authorizing $2 billion for the National Science Foundation in the
1989 fiscal year.
   The bill, passed 88-1, would direct the foundation to establish
programs to stimulate research at colleges and universities, and in
states that historically receive little federal research funding.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., cast the only dissenting vote.
   The bill increases the federally funded research into
superconductivity by 30 percent, adding $5 million to the $16.5
million already planned by the Reagan administration.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said the commercial opportunities
in superconductivity _ the study of chemistry that allows
electricity to flow without resistence _ ``are mindboggling for
transportation, computers, medicine and energy.''
   ``I want us to lead in this field, to gain a competitive
advantage over other nations, and I believe we can if we provide
the resources to our best scientists so that they cand do the
research they are eager and able to do,'' Bentsen said.
   The bill authorizes $2.05 billion for the NSF in fiscal 1989,
which begins Oct. 1. It boosts the authorization to $2.15 in 1990;
$2.47 billion in 1991; $2.83 billion in 1992, and $3.24 billion in
1993.
   Several new programs benefiting universities and certain states
were established in the bill.
   The provisions call for the NSF to help colleges renovate
obsolete laboratories, start a program to encourage undergraduate
research, and to assist both colleges and states that have received
relatively few of the federal research dollars in the past.
   Also included in the bill is a provision directing the National
Academy of Sciences for earthquake engineering research efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
