<DOCNO> AP880617-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-CorporateTakeovers     06-17 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Corporate Takeovers,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Begins Debate On Corporate Takeover Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate began considering legislation
Friday that would make it tougher for corporate raiders to succeed
in hostile takeovers and increase criminal penalties for people
convicted of insider trading.
   Several days of debate loom over the bill, pitting lawmakers who
argue that takeovers cost jobs and cut productivity against others
who insist that shareholders need the power to readily remove
inefficient managers.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee and sponsor of the bill, described corporate raiders as
``agents of greed'' and said, ``Americans are rightly fed up with
this takeover game.''
   Proxmire and his supporters argue that corporate takeovers have
become a primary goal of American business activity, causing
executives to spend much of their time on mergers and acquisitions
instead of enhancing their companies' competitiveness.
   In addition, they say, successful bidders often sink so deeply
into debt that to repay their lenders, they must sell productive
parts of the companies they have acquired, often costing jobs.
   But opponents say co-called hostile takeovers actually consist
of willing sellers surrendering their stock to willing buyers.
Instead, they say, it is abuses by managers who fear being fired by
new owners that must be controlled.
   ``Hostile acquisition of companies is a traditional technique
used to ... change corporate policy or displace incompetent
management,'' said Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, ranking Republican on
the banking panel.
   The legislation would give investors buying 5 percent of a
company's stock five days to report the transaction to the
Securities and Exchange Commission, and bar them from acquiring
more shares until the report is filed.
   Currently, there is a 10-day reporting deadline, and purchases
can continue before the report is filed, permitting takeovers to
proceed before the activity is publicly known.
   Share buyers would be required to report whether their goal is
to make an investment or acquire the entire company.
   Share holders would be given 35 business days _ nearly doubling
the current 20 days _ to consider public tender offers, in which a
buyer offers to buy stock at a specified price. Buyers who acquire
25 percent of a company would be required to make future purchases
through tender offers.
   In addition, the SEC would be given the power to sue investors
who disobey disclosure requirements for up to 50 percent of the
value of the stocks they acquired. Currently, violators are often
ordered simply to stop their violations or correct the inaccurate
information they have provided.
   Maximum penalties for insider trading would be increased from
five years to 10 years in jail, and $100,000 to $1 million.
   Some lawmakers say they believe the legislation puts roadblocks
in front of raiders without halting abuses by corporate management.
   One amendment will be offered to bar the issuance of non-voting
shares of stock, which some companies use to limit the number of
people who control corporations.
   Others will be considered that are designed to limit golden
parachutes, or expensive severance benefits for executives; poison
pills, or moves by companies aimed at discouraging raiders, such as
increasing debt; and greenmail, or payments by target companies of
high prices for stocks to raiders who agree to halt their takeover
efforts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2046EST</FILEID>
