<HEAD>GOP Charges Against Citizen Action Ridiculous, Group Spokesman
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegations by the National Republican
Senatorial Committee that a Chicago-based group has made illegal
campaign contributions is ``a ridiculous charge'' designed to
stifle concerns of average citizens, a spokesman said Friday.
   Robert Brandon, vice president of Citizen Action, said the GOP
committee's recent charges against the 1.75 million-member group
were misleading and false.
   The committee said Thursday that Citizen Action and its
affiliates in 24 states have gone beyond the legal bounds of
pushing issues solely among members. Instead, the committee said,
they used donations to make a pitch for political candidates to
members and the general public.
   Brandon said the committee's allegations contained ``a great
deal of misstatement, falsehood and inaccuracy about the nature of
our organization.''
   Committee members, Brandon said, ``have decided to embrace this
ridiculous charge that's really designed to stifle the legitimate
concerns of average citizens.'' He added that many members of
Citizen Action were in fact Republicans.
   The GOP committee has said it will ask the Internal Revenue
Service and the Federal Election Commission to investigate its
charges against Citizen Action.
