<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1617EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DroughtRdp Bjt   06-17 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp, Bjt,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nice Showers, but Drought's Vice Grip Tightens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ST2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Parched farmland soaked up moderate rain in parts of Iowa on
Friday, Ohio officials warned of the possibility of mandatory water
conservation, and barges sat idle near shallow sections of the busy
Mississippi and Ohio rivers.
   ``I don't think the public understands the gravity of this
problem,'' Ohio Lt. Gov. Paul Leonard said Friday. ``They think
this is a great summer. From the beach point of view, this may be a
great summer. But from a water availability point of view, this
could be a dangerous summer.''
   In the South, reservoirs on the Savannah River in South Carolina
are at low levels comparable to their status during the severe
droughts of the 1930s and 1950s, the Army Corps of Engineers says.
   Several points in northwestern and north-central Iowa received
half an inch of rain or more Friday, but other areas got nothing
more than clouds when a warm front made its way southeast through
the region.
   ``This is probably our last chance for rain for a week,'' said
Chuck Myers, forecaster for the National Weather Service in Iowa.
He said weather patterns would shut off any moisture from the Gulf
of Mexico; Friday's rain came from a weak weather system that came
all the way from the Pacific.
   Iowa State extension climatologist Elwynn Taylor said Friday's
rain barely made a dent in the amount of moisture needed. He said
dry counties in northeastern Iowa need five inches of rain to get
back to normal growing conditions. The rest of the state needs
between two and four inches.
   In other developments, Iowa ordered irrigators and other heavy
water users along the Winnebago, English and Little Cedar rivers
and a section of the Cedar River to stop pumping, with officials
saying similar action is being considered to protect other
low-flowing streams.
   The weather service has predicted a continuation of the
unusually dry Midwestern weather through at least July 15, raising
the possibility of a 20-25 percent loss in corn yields as opposed
to the 10 percent loss suffered to date.
   Futures traders on Chicago, Kansas City and Minneapolis
commodities exchanges have been bidding up prices for future
delivery of grains and soybeans. On the Chicago Board of Trade,
corn futures have risen about 40 percent since May 1 and soybeans
have advanced about 35 percent, and cash prices have followed suit.
   In Ohio, the lieutenant governor was named by Gov. Richard
Celeste to head a special state agency task force being created to
draft recommendations for gubernatorial and legislative action in
response to the drought.
   Leonard said that while dry farms have gotten most of the
public's attention, ``In my opinion, an equally serious risk is
facing Ohio communities in terms of potential water shortages or
eventual contamination of water supplies in Ohio communities.''
   Leonard would not rule out the possibility of mandatory
restrictions. ``That would certainly be a last resort, but at this
point in time you can't rule anything in, or rule anything out,
until you get a good assessment of the problem,'' he said.
   About 1,000 barges were halted on the Mississippi near
Greenville, Miss., while nearly 700 barges were stranded on the
Ohio near Mound City, Ill., authorities said, with water down to 7
feet deep in spots, 2 feet too shallow for loaded barges.
   The Coast Guard shut down a 7-mile stretch of the Ohio near
Mound City on Tuesday to begin dredging a 2,100-foot channel, 11
feet deep by 250 feet wide. The Guard planned to reopen the Ohio to
traffic Thursday night, shifted that to Friday, then delayed the
opening again until Sunday because of dredging problems.
   The Mississippi is at its lowest levels since authorities began
keeping records in 1872. Eight dredges from Greenville to Cairo,
Ill., were working round-the-clock and only a few barges were
passing at a time.
   Water theft has become a new problem in Georgia's Henry County,
just south of Atlanta. Eight people have been cited for tapping
onto county water lines in the past four weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
