<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmOutlook     06-17 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Outlook,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Based on Pre-Drought Figures Predicts Higher Farm Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought is having a major impact on farm
income this year, but an analysis issued Friday by the Agriculture
Department showed that economists have not caught up the rapidly
developing situation.
   The report by the department's Economic Research Service showed
that net cash income in 1988 will be even higher than predicted a
month ago _ in a range of $53 billion to $59 billion, compared with
a record $56 billion in 1987.
   Last month, as it had for some time, the agency forecast net
cash income _ the difference between gross cash income and cash
expenses _ at $50 billion to $55 billion, and the 1987 net at $57
billion.
   ``The forecast range for farmers' 1988 net cash income was
raised to reflect early June data, but it does not yet reflect
potential impacts of the drought,'' the report said.
   Prospects of higher feed costs and lower livestock prices have
reduced the outlook for cattle and hog producers.
   ``Lack of rainfall this spring raised concerns about pasture and
range conditions as cattle movements off spring pastures
increased,'' the report said. ``Conditions were the worst since
1934.''
   The report added: ``If marketings of (grain) fed cattle rise and
their prices drop enough to cause financial losses, feeder cattle
prices will also be pushed down.''
   A rise in hog slaughter could reduce hog prices in late summer
from the level of around $50 per 100 pounds in May, the report said.
   ``Despite lower income prospects for hog and cattle producers,
cash receipts for the livestock sector as a whole will about equal
last year, thanks to strength in poultry receipts,'' it said.
</TEXT>
