<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultipleKillings     06-17 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Delay Simmons' Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge refused Friday to delay the execution
of a man convicted of two murders and accused of 14 others and who
has asked to be executed as soon as possible.
   R. Gene Simmons 47, has been sentenced to die June 27. He was
convicted in May for the Russelville slayings of a woman who
reportedly had spurned his advances a year earlier and a man police
described as a chance victim.
   Simmons is scheduled to stand trial July 18 for the
Christmastime deaths of 14 relatives whose bodies were found at his
home in a rural area near Dover.
   Five of the bodies were found in the Simmons house by police who
came there after the Russellville shootings. The other nine bodies
were found the next day outside, in shallow graves and in the
trunks of two abandoned cars.
   In keeping with their instructions, Simmons' attorneys fought
the attempt to delay his death during a nearly two-hour hearing
before Franklin County Circuit Judge John S. Patterson.
   An attorney for the Rev. Louis J. Franz, chairman of Arkansas
Churches for Life, a group opposed to the death penalty, asked the
judge to delay the execution and to order an appeal. Arkansas law
doesn't provide for an automatic appeal of cases in which a
defendant is sentenced to death.
   The attorney, Mark S. Cambiano, also asked that Franz be allowed
to represent Simmons' interests even against Simmons' wishes.
   Simmons testified that he did not want Franz to represent him.
   ``It would not be in my best interest,'' he said, reiterating
his desire to be executed ``as ordered, when ordered.''
   The judge denied Cambiano's requests.
</TEXT>
