<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Graham     06-17 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Graham,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graham: ``Quiet Religious Revival'' Taking Place in USSR</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Billy Graham said Friday he sensed
stirrings of a ``quiet religious revival'' in the Soviet Union due
in part to Kremlin reforms, but he called the reforms no substitute
for religious faith.
   Graham, who ended his fourth visit to the Soviet Union on
Friday, also said he was assured that some members of the
government are ``true believers,'' but he would not elaborate. His
10-day trip to the Soviet Union included meetings with church and
government officials.
   ``Perestroika means restructuring, but we must have spiritual
restructuring,'' the 69-year-old Southern Baptist evangelist said
in an interview.
   Perestroika, Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's reform program,
has included promises to loosen regulations on religious
denominations and their members in the officially atheist land.
   Soviet religious activists, however, say organized religious
groups remain under the tight control of the government and ruling
Communist Party.
   ``I think perestroika has generated a tremendous hope among the
people,'' Graham said. ``Some people say it's a false hope. I think
that if all Mr. Gorbachev is saying is going to come to pass, it is
going to be a very historic turn in this country.''
   Graham, who first visited the country in 1958, was an honored
guest at government-sanctioned ceremonies celebrating the 1,000th
anniversary of Christianity in what is now the Soviet Union.
   Graham, who also preached in the Soviet Union in 1982 and 1984,
said the crowds that formed to hear him preach in Moscow and Kiev
were the largest he had addressed in the country.
   ``For the first time, they put up amplification outside, and no
police held people back,'' he said. ``When I was here before, they
wouldn't shake hands. They were nervous or afraid.''
   Graham said Gorbachev's more liberal policies on self-expression
and ``incurably religious'' human nature had combined to rekindle
interest in religion.
   ``There is a quiet religious revival going on in Russia, in the
hearts of its people,'' Graham said. ``I think that under Stalin
and Khrushchev, and to a certain extent under Brezhnev, the people
were held back. Now it's been opened up some and will probably be
opened up more.''
   Graham said he thought Soviet authorities were stunned by the
``hunger for faith''shown by many citizens during the millennium
celebrations, which began June 5 and ended Friday.
   Graham was asked if the church could be sure of its future in a
land where atheism is official doctrine.
   ``Christianity has always grown under rulers who didn't believe
in Christ or in God. Yes, the (Soviet) government is atheistic. But
I believe that in this government there are true believers,'' added
Graham, who said he had been assured of this by Soviets.
   Graham's 1982 visit to the Soviet Union sparked controversy when
he told a news conference in Moscow that the church in the country
was free.
   Graham maintained Friday that he had said churches have ``a
measure of religious freedom'' but were not ``free in the sense
that we call freedom.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
