<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PeaceWalk     06-17 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Walk,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Begin March for Peace Across United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 220 Soviet citizens waving banners
reading ``We Are One Family'' and ``Our Goal Is Nuclear-Free
World'' began a month-long walking tour of the United States on
Friday with the aim of building friendship and lobbying for
disarmament.
   The Soviets, joined by as many as 100 Americans, planned to walk
to Philadelphia and then travel by bus to Moline, Ill., for a walk
across the Mississippi River to Des Moines, Iowa, where they will
celebrate the Fourth of July holiday.
   The group will fly from Des Moines to Los Angeles for a final
walk to San Francisco, ending with a mid-July rock concert in
Golden Gate Park.
   The group plans to walk as much as 15 miles a day and spend
nights in a mobile tent city.
   The tour is sponsored by International Peace Walk Inc., a
private, non-profit U.S. organization which is planning a
reciprocal walk from Odessa to Kiev in August involving between 200
and 250 Americans. The exchange began a year ago with a three-week
trek by 230 Americans from Leningrad to Moscow.
   Soviets taking part in the current peace walk represent each of
the 15 Soviet republics and include Vladimir Fedosov, a deputy of
the Supreme Soviet or parliament.
   Others include farmers, students, a firefighter from Chernobyl _
site of a Soviet nuclear power plant disaster in 1986 _ and Janis
Kipurs, winner of the bobsledding gold medal at the 1988 Winter
Olympic Games.
   The Soviet participants were selected by the Soviet Peace
Committee.
   ``We should put a red light in front of the arms race,'' Fedosov
told a rally at the West Front of the Capitol before the walk
began. He said the walk was ``one more attempt at diplomacy between
the peoples of our nations to make the world safe.''
   ``Our goal is a non-nuclear and non-violent world,'' said
Fedosov, a member of the Soviet commission that supervised
ratification of the recent U.S.-Soviet medium-range nuclear missile
treaty.
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who will join the walk on July 3 in his
home state, called for an immediate halt in superpower production
of advanced long-range nuclear weapons, a nuclear test ban treaty,
a ban on missile test flights and rejection of Reagan's Star Wars
missile defense system.
   ``Now, before it's too late, let's stop the arms race from going
right into outer space,'' Harkin said. He urged that the two
countries cooperate instead to conduct joint space missions,
eliminate hunger, illiteracy and poverty, protect the environment
and improve education.
   ``We must recognize that the fate of the two superpowers is
inseparable,'' Harkin said. ``There is no U.S. security without
Soviet security. In the nuclear age, there is only common
security.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
