<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1809EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Rivers     06-17 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Rivers,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Barges Still Stranded In Midwest Rivers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of barges sat idle Friday on the Mississippi and Ohio
rivers as a lingering drought kept water levels low, and officials
said Sunday would be the earliest that safe travel could resume.
   Drought has lowered channels in the rivers to about 7 feet in
spots _ 2 feet less than needed for loaded barges _ and officials
warned that aquatic life could suffer if the dry weather continues.
   Flow rates in the two rivers are so slow that more sediment than
normal is settling to the bottom, forming new sandbars that become
navigational hazards.
   ``It's not good,'' Ron Blake of the U.S. Coast Guard in Paducah,
Ky., said of conditions on the Ohio. ``Pretty much of the river is
bank now _ it's that shallow.''
   About 1,000 barges were halted on the Mississippi near
Greenville, Miss., waiting a turn through a narrow channel, while
nearly 700 barges were stuck on the Ohio awaiting completing of
dredging near Mound City, Ill., authorities said. Tow boat owners
were losing about $10,000 a day, officials said.
   Ed Green of the Army Corps of Engineers in Washington said the
Ohio is the nation's only inland waterway shut down because of
shallow water, and it is at its lowest levels since January 1969.
   Water levels stood at 7 feet to 8 feet on the Mississippi near
Greenville, said Robert Anderson of the Corps' Memphis, Tenn.
office. The river is at its lowest level there since authorities
began keeping records in 1872.
   Eight dredges were working round-the-clock from Greenville to
Cairo, Ill., to dig channels of at least 9 feet, Green said. ``It's
be pretty much clogged up until Sunday,'' he said.
   ``Right now the only things passing are the small tows, just a
few barges at a time.''
   The Coast Guard on Tuesday shut down a 7-mile stretch of the
Ohio near Mound City to begin dredging a 2,100-foot channel, 11
feet deep by 250 feet wide.
   Water depths of 8 feet in the troubled section have caused
numerous barge groundings in the past two weeks. The Guard planned
to reopen the Ohio to traffic Thursday night, shifted that to
Friday, then delayed the opening again until Sunday because of
dredging problems.
   Underwater cables, rocks and debris forced the Corps of
Engineers to delay the reopening, said Corps spokesman Chuck
Shumann in Louisville, Ky.
   Blake said 42 towboats were waiting to go downriver, while 26
needed to go upstream.
   The drought also is threatening aquatic life in the Ohio because
of low oxygen, and prompting algae growth that can taint drinking
water, a river monitoring official said.
   Peter Tennant, water quality programs manager of the Ohio River
Valley Sanitation Commission, said local water treatment operations
can make the algae-contaminated water safe, but can't eliminate the
bad taste.
   Tennant also said that if the drought continues for two weeks
more, the oxygen level could drop to the point where it would
affect the reproductive quality of fish.
</TEXT>
