<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Uranus-Moons     06-17 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uranus-Moons,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>List Of Names For New And Old Moons Of Uranus</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Uranus-Challenger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the proposed names for the
10 moons of Uranus discovered by the Voyager 2 spacecraft and the
existing names of the five previously known moons.
   Listed in order of increasing distance from Uranus, the first 10
names are for the new moons. The source of each name and estimated
diameter of each moon also are listed.
   All names are from William Shakespeare's plays, except for those
taken from Alexander Pope's poem ``The Rape of the Lock.''
   _Cordelia, disinherited and executed daughter of ``King Lear,''
25 miles.
   _Ophelia, who goes insane and drowns herself after her father,
Polonius, is murdered by ``Hamlet,'' 30 miles.
   _Bianca, sister of the shrew, in ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' 30
miles.
   _Cressida, unfaithful lover in ``Troilus and Cressida,'' 37
miles.
   _Desdemona, falsely accused wife murdered by her husband,
``Othello,'' 37 miles.
   _Juliet, doomed lover in ``Romeo and Juliet,'' 50 miles.
   _Portia, wife of the assassin Brutus in ``Julius Caesar,'' 50
miles.
   _Rosalind, main character and daughter of the wrongfully
banished duke in ``As You Like It,'' 37 miles.
   _Belinda, whose lock of hair was stolen in ``The Rape of the
Lock,'' 37 miles.
   _Puck, mischievous elf in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' 106
miles.
   _Miranda, daughter of wrongfully exiled Duke of Milan and lover
of Ferdinand in ``The Tempest,'' 300 miles.
   _Ariel, mischievous spirit in ``The Tempest;'' also the sylph,
or imaginary being, in ``The Rape of the Lock,'' 720 miles.
   _Umbriel, a sprite in ``The Rape of the Lock,'' 740 miles.
   _Titania, queen of the fairies in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,''
1,000 miles.
   _Oberon, king of the fairies in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,''
963 miles.
</TEXT>
