<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2314EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Dien     06-17 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Dien,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Who Defied Vietnam Over Church Control Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Philippe Nguyen Kim Dien of
Hue, Vietnam, has died after spending his last years under house
arrest for defying communist attempts to control the country's
Roman Catholic Church. He was 67.
   The official Vietnam News Agency, in a report monitored in
Bangkok on Friday, said Dien died of an unspecified illness on June
8 at Cho Ray Hospital in Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon.
   A Vatican spokesman in Rome reported that the Vatican sent a
telegram to Cardinal Trinh Van Can, archbishop of Hanoi, saying
Pope John Paul II praised Dien for his courage.
   ``The Holy Father joins in the sorrow of the bishops and of all
the Catholic community in Vietnam,'' the telegram read. ``He
commends to the Lord the courageous pastor who faithfully testified
the Gospel in a life of untiring service for the people of God.''
   It was signed by Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, Vatican secretary
of state.
   Dien was barred from priestly work and put under house arrest in
1984 for urging priests not to join the Committee for Solidarity of
Patriotic Vietnamese Catholics. The communist government of Vietnam
formed the committee in 1983 and critics said it was designed to
control the church.
   Authorities apparently made no serious attempt to replace Dien,
however.
   The Vietnamese news report, dated Thursday, said a memorial
service was held on Monday in Hue. The Ho Chi Minh City archbishop,
Nguyen Van Binh, held a funeral service in Hue on Wednesday which
was attended by Communist Party and government officials concerned
with religious affairs, it said.
   The Vatican said Kim was born in March 1921 in Vinh Long, a
traditional center of the Catholic Church in the Mekong River Delta
in southern Vietnam; was ordained in July 1947 and became a bishop
in 1961.
   There are 4 million to 5 million Catholics among Vietnam's
largely Buddhist population of about 63 million.
   The Vatican, Vietnamese refugees and other sources charge that
after the communists came to power in 1975, they closed seminaries,
jailed priests and took other steps to repress the Catholic Church.
   Authorities have moved toward reconciliation since Nguyen Van
Linh became Communist Party chief in December 1986. A seminary was
reopened and many priests were freed from political
``re-education'' camps where they were confined since 1975.
   Relations with the Vatican also improved somewhat, although
Hanoi has condemned the Vatican's scheduled canonization this
Sunday of 117 people who were martyred in Vietnam in the 18th and
19th centuries.
   Vietnamese officials say the Vatican has allowed anti-communist
Vietnamese exiles to use the occasion to criticize Hanoi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
