<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuelSpill     06-17 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Says Modern Steel Could Have Resisted Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fuel tank collapse that fouled water in
three states would have only been a leak if Ashland Oil Inc. had
used modern steel instead of weaker 1940s steel to build the tank
in 1987, a federal agency said Friday.
   A National Bureau of Standards study agreed with earlier
findings of the Battelle Memorial Institute that a dime-sized flaw
caused the 48-foot tank wall to split in a fraction of a second,
said Richard N. Wright, director of the agency's center for
building technology.
   Modern steel could have resisted total collapse, he said.
   ``Virtually every older tank may be susceptible to this type of
accident,'' said U.S. Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., who requested the
NBS probe and introduced a bill that would raise construction
standards on large fuel tanks.
   The flaw was in the steel before the 4 million-gallon tank was
built in Cleveland around 1940, said Battelle, a private Columbus,
Ohio-based institute hired by Ashland to investigate the cause of
the spill. Ashland dismantled it and reconstructed the tank at its
Floreffe Terminal south of Pittsburgh in 1987.
   It burst while being filled Jan. 2 during freezing weather.
   Even without the flaw, the steel did not meet current industry
standards, becoming brittle below 80 degrees, said Wright. No
standards existed when Ashland first erected the tank.
   Modern steel retains its strength at zero degrees, he said.
   The accident sent about 700,000 gallons of oil into the
Monongahela and Ohio rivers, the source of drinking water for
communities in Pennsylvania, West Virginia and Ohio.
   Ashland has admitted failing to obtain the necessary local
permits before erecting the tank. The company has assumed
responsibility for the accident and has already paid $6 million of
the $7 million clean-up costs, plus $1.2 million in damage claims
to government agencies, businesses and individuals.
   The NBS and the American Petroleum Institute say they do not
know the age of the nation's several thousand large fuel tanks.
Wright said he believed a substantial number are made of old steel.
   ``A hunter's stray bullet, a pick-up truck whose brakes fail,
even a sledge hammer blow could explode some tanks,'' Walgren said.
   The difficulty of preventing and detecting flaws underscores the
importance of using strong steel, said Wright.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
