<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Expulsions 1stLd-Writethru a0725 06-17 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Expulsions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO, Israeli Official Ordered Out of Britain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, Prosecutors said ... RESTORING dropped
word ``for.'' Picks up 7th graf pvs, At the ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office on Friday announced the
expulsions of an Israeli diplomat and a PLO official following a
British court's conviction on weapons charges of a Palestinian who
was accused of spying for Israel.
   The Foreign Office said that Israeli attache Arie Regev and the
PLO's London press officer, Zaki al Hawa, were no longer welcome
because of activities incompatible with their diplomatic duties. It
said they must leave the country by the end of June.
   The department also made clear that Britain had expressed
irritation that the Israeli intelligence agency Mossad had not kept
Britain informed of its operations in Britain.
   In Jerusalem, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said, ``We regret
that her majesty's government has seen fit to take measures of the
kind adopted. Israel did not act against any British interests.''
   The decision follows a London trial of 28-year-old Palestinian
Ishmael Sowan, convicted Wednesday at the Old Bailey court of
possessing explosives, grenades and rifles. He was sentenced
Thursday to 11 years in jail.
   Prosecutors said Sowan kept the arms for Abder Mustapha, a
Palestine Liberation Organization member. Mustapha was suspected of
arranging the murder in London of an Arab cartoonist, Ali Naji Awad
Al-Adhami.
   At the same time, Sowan was spying on Mustapha for Mossad, the
prosecution alleged.
   The Foreign Office said it understood that the PLO official, al
Hawa, was a member of Force 17, whose function is to provide
personal security for PLO leader Yasser Arafat and senior officials
overseas.
   In its coverage of the trial, The Times of London said the
Mossad failed to tell British authorities of the presence in
Britain of Mustapha. Britain had made an exclusion order against
Mustapha and was unaware he had returned to Britain.
   Press Association, the domestic news agency, quoted unidentified
government officials as saying the exclusion order against Mustapha
was because of suspicion about his activities but that there was no
evidence he had committed an offense.
   Sowan was arrested in August when police were investigating the
shooting of Al-Adhami.
   He testified that the weapons found in his house in the eastern
port of Hull belonged to Mustapha. Sowan was not a suspect in the
shooting of the cartoonist. Police said Mustapha fled to the Middle
East after Al-Adhami was shot.
   The London Times said Mustapha was linked to the murder of three
Israeli vacationers on a yacht at Larnaca, Cyprus, in June 1986. He
was also wanted for an attack on an Israeli El Al bus in West
Germany in 1970, the newspaper said.
   On Friday the Foreign Office summoned Israeli Ambassador Yehuda
Avner and told him Arie Regev should leave. It later summoned
Faycal Aouidha, head of the PLO in London, and told him the Home
Secretary had ordered the departure of Zaki Al Hawa.
   The Foreign Office also confirmed that the Israeli Embassy was
told last year that an attache at the embassy, Jacob Barrad, who
was out of the country, would not be welcome to return.
   Regev, who has been in London since 1984, and Barrad were
thought to be the officials at the embassy who coordinated the work
of Mossad, Press Association said.
</TEXT>
