<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     06-17 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers Reject `Settlement Offer' From Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The East and West Coast leaders of the
striking Writers Guild of America voted Friday to reject a $71
million contract offer that movie and television producers had
hoped would settle the 15-week-old walkout.
   The unanimous vote was held during a telephone conference call
between the union's two governing boards, said West Coast executive
director Brian Walton.
   He said that only ``a very small part of the meeting'' was
devoted to considering whether to accept the contract, with most of
it spent reviewing details of the offer, which was rejected
Thursday by the guild's negotiating committee.
   Members of the 9,500-member union will meet Wednesday in New
York and Los Angeles to vote on the contract. Union officials said
they expected a rejection despite pressure from a union splinter
group to sign a contract.
   Walton said he believed producers intended to divide the union
Thursday by making an offer they knew would be rejected.
``Presumably they wanted to see if the membership would follow the
leadership ... that's the only explanation I can give for the
offer.''
   Walton characterized the offer by the Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers as ``quite better than the previous
offer,'' but still not acceptable in the area of domestic
television and foreign residuals for reruns.
   ``We are very disappointed. We have nothing more to give,'' said
producers' spokesman Herb Steinberg.
   While no new talks were scheduled, Walton said the guild has
offered to resume negotiations.
   The rejected offer represented an across-the-board increase of
14.7 percent over a four-year contract and a value of $71 million,
Steinberg said. The producers' previous offer was valued by the
alliance at $52 million.

</TEXT>
