<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AtheistAnniversary     06-17 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atheist Anniversary,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Madalyn Murray O'Hair Celebrates Anniversary of School Prayer Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Granddaughter's last name in 9th graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair said a
celebration Friday was the first time she has commemorated the
landmark U.S. Supreme Court decision outlawing organized prayer in
public schools.
   ``There wasn't anything to celebrate before. We were still
struggling,'' said Mrs. O'Hair, 70, before festivities celebrating
the 25th anniversary of a related court decision that resulted from
a suit she filed.
   Now, she said, ``We've made it. We're here. There is no way that
we can be pushed out of society any more. There are too many
atheists now.''
   The Supreme Court in 1963 outlawed daily Bible reading in public
schools, based on a landmark ruling the previous year that
organized school prayer violated the Constitution's First Amendment
prohibition against any state establishment of religion.
   Mrs. O'Hair _ then Madalyn Murray _ in 1959 had complained that
her son, Bill, was being required to pray in his public schools in
Baltimore.
   ``There has been a long struggle,'' said Mrs. O'Hair, referring
to continuing hostility and challenges to the court victories
against organized prayer.
   American Atheists, the organization Mrs. O'Hair founded, began
the anniversary celebration Friday with a ribbon-cutting planned
primarily for reporters to see its new headquarters. The building
cost $1.75 million before renovations, and was paid for in cash, as
is the group's custom, Mrs. O'Hair said.
   Over the weekend, the atheists planned tours of the headquarters
and a celebration of the summer solstice. About 200 people were
expected, said Rob Sherman, the group's national spokesman.
   Mrs. O'Hair's son Jon and granddaughter Robin Murray-O'Hair,
Bill's daughter, work with her. Mrs. O'Hair says she does not
discuss Bill, who has become a Christian. The headquarters has a
staff of 16 and four volunteers.
   The organization has a budget of about $750,000 this year, Mrs.
O'Hair said, and it has 38,000 families as members and chapters in
35 states.
</TEXT>
