<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Murdoch     06-17 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murdoch,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murdoch Asks FCC Permission To Put Boston TV Station in
Independent Trust</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Rupert Murdoch on Friday proposed to
put his Boston UHF television station in an independent trust to
comply with government rules barring common ownership of a
newspaper and TV station in the same city.
   A waiver allowing Murdoch to own WFXT-TV and the Boston Herald
expires June 30, and although he won the right in court to request
an extension of the waiver, Murdoch had said he would sell the TV
station.
   But the media magnate said Friday he had decided to avail
himself of the trust option, which is allowed by the Federal
Communications Commission as a method of complying with the
cross-ownership rule.
   Murdoch proposed to the FCC that the trust be managed by former
Sen. Edward Brooke of Massachusetts and former New York Gov. Hugh
Carey.
   Lawrence Kessler, general counsel of Murdoch's company, News
America Publishing Inc., said the trust was chosen because ``it
seemed a more appropriate thing to do right now. It lets us remain
the beneficiary of what we believe will be a valuable property.''
   Under terms of the trust agreement, Murdoch would relinquish
control of the station but would still receive profits. The station
could not be sold for less than $35 million. It could be sold for
more than that amount if Murdoch agrees, but he would be able to
consider only the ``financial terms and conditions'' of the
proposal.
   The station has been valued at between $30 million and $50
million.
   The agreement also provides that the trust would be terminated
if the station were sold or ceased operation or if Murdoch sells
the Boston Herald.
   Andrew Schwartzman, executive director of the Media Access
Project, a public interest law firm, said he was concerned that the
agreement would allow the station to be held by the trust
indefinitely.
   ``That's very troubling,'' Schwartzman said in an interview.
``These guys (Brooke and Carey) aren't broadcasters. We want to
license people who are going to be broadcasters on a permanent
basis.''
   Murdoch in March sold the New York Post for $37 million to real
estate developer Peter Kalikow to comply with the cross-ownership
rule.
   Murdoch had engaged in a bitter battle with Congress over
temporary waivers allowing him to own the two Boston properties and
the New York Post and WNYW-TV in New York.
   Sens. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., late
last year pushed through the Congress a little noticed measure
prohibiting the FCC from eliminating or modifying the
cross-ownership rule and barring it from extending any waivers of
the rule.
   In March, Murdoch successfully challenged the legislation in the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and won the right to request an
extension of his waiver from the FCC.
   However, he decided against a further extension, saying the
station had ``suffered as the result of a regulatory cloud.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
