<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FondaFlap     06-17 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fonda Flap,0359</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Fonda's apology for her
controversial trip to Hanoi during the Vietnam War apparently won't
appease all her critics, but others say they are ready to forgive
and forget.
   Veteran groups in Waterbury and Holyoke, Mass., have been
protesting Fonda's plans to film a movie in their communities in
August because of her 1972 trip to North Vietnan.
   In a television interview, Fonda apologizes for her actions
during the trip but not for her anti-war message.
   ``I am proud of most of what I did, and I am very sorry for some
of what I did,'' Fonda said in an interview for Friday night's
ABC's ``20-20''.
   ``I was trying to help end the killing, end the war. But there
were times when I was thoughtless and careless about it, and ... I
am very sorry that I hurt them,'' she said.
   Joseph Griggs, a spokesman for the Veterans Coalition Against
Hanoi Jane, said Fonda must back up her words with action, such as
returning to Vietnam to seek the return of prisoners of war still
unaccounted for.
   ``I would have to say that's a very nice beginning,'' he said of
her apology. But ``it's been our position for some time now that
efforts have to go along with the words,'' Griggs said.
   Gaetano Russo, head of the coalition, called the apology
``typical Fonda hogwash.''
   But Korean War veteran John Sarlo of Waterbury said of the
apology, ``I guesd that's something we can be grateful for and
appreciate.''
   The Rev. John A. McColley, rector of St. Michael's Episcopal
Church in Naugatuck and a Vietnam veteran, said: ``I'm just about
absolutely certain (the apology) is genuine and well done. She made
her apology.''
   In the interview, Fonda said she was sorry for being
photographed aboard a North Vietnamese anti-aircraft gun, saying
``that was a ... thoughtless and careless thing to have done.''
   She also apologized for saying that POWs were not tortured.
   ``They suffered enough. They didn't need to hear from me,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
