<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Howard     06-17 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Howard,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Television Broadcasts Interview with CIA Defector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television aired an interview with CIA
defector Edward Lee Howard Friday and showed him at a country
dacha, walking down Moscow's Arbat shopping street and discussing
his life since he arrived here in 1985.
   The broadcast included a home movie Howard made for his family
during travels around the Soviet Union. He said he was happy, but
he also said he had few friends.
   Howard's wife and son did not accompany him to the Soviet Union.
His defection to Moscow was the first by someone known to have
worked for the CIA.
   He shed little light during the interview on how he managed to
slip through FBI surveillance of his home in Santa Fe, N.M. and
reach Soviet soil.
   Howard did say he traveled to Hungary since defecting and that
his disagreements with the Central Intelligence Agency were
``mostly political. I am opposed to secret methods.''
   In a previous interview on Soviet TV, Howard said he was granted
political asylum in the Soviet Union and had never ``done anything
that would damage or threaten my country's security.''
   The Soviets reportedly paid Howard $6,000 for information which
compromised many CIA operations in the Soviet Union and is believed
to have led to the arrest and execution of at least one Soviet
working for the CIA.
   Howard spoke mostly in English during the Friday interview and
his remarks were translated into Russian. While strolling down the
Arbat, he chatted in Russian with his interviewer.
   The home movie included footage of churches, which he said were
one of his favorite sights in the Soviet Union. He said he has
always been a Roman Catholic, but it was not clear where he
worshiped.
   He was shown inside his dacha, which appeared plush by Soviet
standards. He said he also had an apartment in Moscow, but this was
not shown, perhaps for security reasons.
   Howard said he met in Moscow at length with David Wise, an
American based in Washington who has written several books critical
of the CIA. The defector said he might write a book on his
experiences after a time.
   Howard, 36, went to work for the CIA in 1981 and was fired by
the agency in June 1983. Some sources said he quit because he was
angry at being assigned to Moscow, and others because his superiors
became concerned about his personal life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
