<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-German     06-17 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-German,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohl Calls on Scientists To Combat World Ills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on Friday
urged scientists to work with politicians to combat global economic
problems in the same way they spurred attempts to protect the
Earth's ozone layer.
   Kohl, accepting an honorary doctorate of laws from Toronto
University, said he and the six other leaders eeting in Toronto
next week need help from scientists if they are to meet their
challenges.
   ``We will use all means at our disposal to promote stable,
non-inflationary world economic growth,'' Kohl said. ``We will
resolutely combat global protectionism of any kind.''
   He said they also would have to find ways of keeping developed
countries from overproducing food while the poorest countries,
especially in Africa, have increasingly less food.
   They likewise will have to improve the economy of the Third
World, including finding a way to ease the developing nations'
indebtedness, Kohl said.
   ``All these crucial problems pertaining to the world economy and
the international debt situation cannot be solved by any one
country alone, regardless of its economic strength,'' he said.
   ``These problems ... present challenges that require cooperation
between politicians and scientists,'' Kohl said. ``We need
scientific and technological innovation.''
   He said politicians need scientists as an ``early warning
system'' to sound the alarm about threats in nature, technology and
society as they warned about the dangers that chlorofluorocarbons
from refrigerants, foam and aerosols pose to the Earth's protective
ozone layer.
   ``Those warnings have prompted global efforts to restrict
further still the production and use of such substances,'' Kohl
said.
   The West German chancellor, who addressed the Canadian
Parliament on Thursday, also paid a visit to David Peterson,
premier of Ontario. Toronto, which is hosting the economic summit
conference starting Sunday, is capital of Ontario, Canada's
wealthiest and most populous province.
   Kohl then went to Kitchener, Ontario, one hour to the southwest
of Toronto, for a speech to the German-Canadian community. The
ethnic group, consisting of more than 2 million people, is the
third largest in Canada after the British and French Canadians.
</TEXT>
