<DOCNO> AP880617-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1850EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Pinero     06-17 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Pinero,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miguel Pinero, Author of `Short Eyes,' Dead in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO PEREZ RIVERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miguel Pinero, the former prisoner who turned
his jail experiences into the prize-winning play ``Short Eyes,''
has died in a Manhattan hospital, the New York Public Theater
announced Friday. He was 41.
   Pinero died Thursday of cirrhosis of the liver, said Reva
Cooper, a theater spokeswoman.
   ``Short Eyes,'' Pinero's most famous play, was based partly on
his own jail experiences and its first draft was written while the
author was still in prison, Cooper said. It is set in the day room
of a cell block and deals with how other prisoners deal with a new
inmate charged with the rape of a young girl.
   The play opened in 1974 at the off-off-Broadway Riverside
Theater as a part of the Third World Project, moved to the Public
Theater and then to the Vivian Beaumont Theater in Lincoln Center
and won the coveted New York Drama Critics Award for best American
play of the season. It was made into a movie in 1976.
   At the time of his death, Pinero was writing another play for
the Public, titled ``Every Form of Refuge Has Its Price,'' Cooper
said. The play takes place in the intensive care unit of a
Manhattan hospital, very similar to the one where he died, said
Joseph Papp, head of the New York Public Theater.
   ``Pinero was the first major writer to come out of the large
numbers of Puerto Ricans that came to New York in the '50s,'' said
Papp. ``He was a mentor for Reinaldo Povod _ another successful
Puerto Rican dramatist _ who will pave the way for other young
Latino writers.''
   In a reference to the violent, striking play that cemented
Pinero's reputation, Papp said that Pinero ``brought a hard-hitting
realism to the stage that shook it up.''
   Pinero's other plays include ``The Sun Always Shines for the
Cool,'' set in a hustlers' bar, and ``Eulogy for a Small Time
Thief.''
   Miguel Antonio Gomez Pinero was born in Gurabo, Puerto Rico,
Dec. 19, 1946.
   His family moved to New York when he was 4. A few years later
his father abandoned the family and ``we were thrown out to the
street when I was 9 or 10,'' the author said in an interview.
   As a young man, Pinero was in and out of jail several times,
convicted of robbery and other charges, and was sent finally to
Sing Sing, where he started writing ``Short Eyes.''
   He was also an actor, and had a small role in the film version
of that play.
   Pinero was married to Juanita Rameize in 1977, and they were
divorced two years later.
   Papp said the Public will hold a memorial on June 24 for Pinero.
According to Pinero's wishes, his body will be cremated, Papp said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1900EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Space     06-17 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Space,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet and Bulgarian Cosmonauts Land After 10-Day Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spacecraft carrying two Soviets and a Bulgarian
cosmonaut landed softly Friday on the sweltering, dusty plains of
Soviet Central Asia at the end of a 10-day mission, state-run media
reported.
   ``Ain't it hot down here on earth!'' mission commander Anatoly
Solovov said as he clambered out of the Soyuz-TM capsule, the Tass
news agency reported.
   The capsule landed by parachute 124 miles southeast of
Dzhezkazgan, a city in Kazakhstan about 1,300 miles southeast of
Moscow.
   A chase helicopter and special trucks with huge wheels raced
across the plains to the landing spot, reaching it minutes after
touchdown, Tass said.
   Although the launch had been broadcast live on Soviet
television, the moment of landing was not televised. The three
cosmonauts were shown sitting in chairs beside the capsule.
   Solovyov sipped hot tea to quench his thirst in temperatures
that reached 108 degrees.
   Other crewmembers were Alexander Alexandrov of Omurtag,
Bulgaria, and Viktor P. Savinkyh of the Soviet Union. They blasted
off June 7 from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan and two days
later linked their capsule with the Soviet Union's orbiting space
station Mir, Russian for peace.
   Soviet television broadcast live footage Friday morning of the
three cosmonauts saying goodbye to Mir's crew. The three were shown
kissing and embracing the Mir crewmembers _ Vladimir Titov and Musa
Manarov _ and then entering an airlock en route to the capsule.
   During their 10-day mission aboard Mir, the cosmonauts performed
more than 40 experiments involving astronomy, medicine, metallurgy
and geology. Alexandrov, 36, brought several Bulgarian-made
scientific devices.
   It was the first time a Bulgarian had boarded a Soviet space
station. An April 1979 attempt by a Soviet-Bulgarian crew to dock
their Soyuz-33 capsule with the orbiting Soviet station Salyut-6
failed, and was aborted.
   Tass said the 40-year-old Solovyov, an air force lieutenant
colonel, has been awarded the title Hero of the Soviet Union for
the space mission ``and for heroism and courage displayed.'' He is
also to receive the government's highest award, the Order of Lenin.
</TEXT>
