<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Bologna     06-17 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Bologna,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Hold Bologna Buffet In Bush's Houston Residence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Texas Democrats, in town for their party's
state convention, held a ``bologna buffet'' Friday in the hotel
suite that is Vice President George Bush's official state residence.
   ``It's pretty well known that George Bush moved out of Texas
some years ago and moved to Maine,'' said Ty Fain, an Austin
businessman and Democratic Party activist who rented Suite 271 at
the Houstonian Hotel and Conference Center.
   ``You can't begrudge anyone that, but sometimes politicians get
carried away with their own baloney and we can poke holes in them.
And anyone who walked through here can see this is not a home,''
Fain added.
   Fain, munching a bologna sandwich on white bread, led visitors
around the three-room suite, which rents for $515 a night, showing
off two bedrooms, each with king-size beds, and each with a small
bathroom. The suite, with floor-to-ceiling one-way glass windows,
overlooks the hotel pool, just a few feet away outside.
   ``Every man lines up in this room at the windows,'' said Elisa
Lyles, who works for Fain, as she watched men in the room gaze at
dozens of bikini-clad women tanning themselves on the pool deck.
   Fain said he called the hotel, said he was going to be in town
for a couple of days and thought it would be fun to rent the suite.
   ``I'm absolutely delighted,'' Fain said. ``This is one of the
finest hotels I've ever been in. We're just trying to have a little
fun.
   ``But the question of George Bush being a hometown boy is a
little out of date. When he comes to Texas and parades around as a
hometown boy, I think this is a little bit of baloney.''
   Bush's residency was subject of a court challenge a few years
ago but a Houston judge ruled the vice president could vote in the
city as a Texas resident.
   Bush, who has wrapped up the Republican presidential nomination,
lived in Texas for years and served as a congressman for a Houston
district. However, he has not owned a home in Texas since becoming
vice president in 1981. He was born in Massachusetts, grew up in
Connecticut and has a vacation home in Maine.
</TEXT>
