<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Oath 1stld-writethru a0761 06-17 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Oath, 1st ld-writethru, a0761,0681</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 12th graf, ``These changes'' with comment
from peace group leader. Picks up 13th graf previous ``The
government''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parliament on Friday adopted a new
military oath that deletes a pledge to serve in alliance with the
Soviet army, a clause long criticized as an affront to Polish
sovereignty.
   A brief statement by the official news agency PAP said the new
oath, which was recommended by the government and the defense
ministry, was passed unanimously.
   The government has called the change merely a matter of updating
antiquated language and has said it would not affect relations with
the Soviets.
   Previously, military inductees pledged to guard peace in
``brotherly alliance with the Soviet army and other allied
armies.'' An outlawed opposition group, Freedom and Peace, had long
charged the oath affronted Polish sovereignty.
   The new oath contains no reference to the Soviet Union, and the
pledge is only to ``guard peace in the brotherhood of arms with the
allied armies.''
   It also drops a reference to defending Poland against ``the
threats of imperialism.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban has stressed that the revised
wording does not reflect any lessening of Poland's alliance with
the Soviet Union.
   ``The alliance with the Soviet Union provides the foundation for
the Polish armed forces,'' Urban said last March. ``No matter how
this truth is expressed in words, the essence of the matter will
not change.''
   Urban said the oath was changed because ``it came into existence
some time ago, so it requires some adjustments.''
   ``All periods in time have their specific styles,'' he added.
   Freedom and Peace leader Jacek Czaputowicz said many people has
been imprisoned simply for opposing the old oath. He said his group
deserved credit for the proposed change.
   ``These changes are because of the activity of Freedom and
Peace,'' he said. He called the change ``a very big success, I
think the biggest success of Freedom and Peace in its short
history.''
   He said his group hoped the new oath would be more than ``a
symbol, a one-time action, but the start of a process of changing
the role and function of the army in Polish society.''
   
   The government has denied that Freedom and Peace affected the
decision to change the oath.
   Freedom and Peace says 16 of its supporters are in prison,
either for refusing to take the oath or to comply with Poland's
mandatory two-year military draft.
   The group also demands the right to alternative national service
for conscientious objectors. The government has announced it is
considering some form of such service, but said inductees would
have to serve up to four years.
   The old oath also contained the promise to ``guard unyieldingly
the rights of the working people guaranteed in the constitution,
unyieldingly stand guard of the people's rule and remain faithful
to the government of the Polish People's Republic.''
   The new oath says simply: ``I swear to serve the homeland and
the nation,'' with no specific reference to the government or
working people.
   Czaputowicz said it was significant that the references to
socialism and the government were dropped.
   ``Some people from Freedom and Peace who refused to take the
oath said they cannot swear to the government because this
government is not our government,'' he said. ``It is not the
government of the whole nation.''
   Five Freedom and Peace supporters from Gdansk were detained
outside Parliament on Thursday, 15 minutes after they sat down on
the pavement to demand passage of the new oath, Czaputowicz said.
   The protesters were also calling for release of Freedom and
Peace member Slawomir Dutkiewicz, 24, of Szczecin, who was
imprisoned for resisting the draft.
   Dutkiewicz has been force-fed since he began a hunger strike in
November. He has lost 44 pounds and his health has deteriorated
significantly, according to Dr. Zofia Kuratowska, a physician who
examined him in prison earlier this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Election     06-17 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Election,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed Verdict Emerging in Special Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Partial results were announced Friday in
special elections to fill seven vacancies in Parliament and 11 in
state assemblies, and political commentators on state-run
television called it a mixed verdict.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress Party won five state
assembly seats and one in the federal Parliament in Thursday's
balloting. Various opposition parties claimed two seats in
Parliament and four assembly seats.
   In the key contest, still outstanding, former Defense Minister
V.P. Singh was reported leading by more than 9,000 votes over
Congress Party candidate Sunil Shastri for Parliament, with about
35,000 votes counted.
   The Allahabad district involved has 850,000 registered voters.
Final results there were not expected before Saturday following
allegations by Singh supporters o ballot-stuffing and intimidation
of voters by the Congress Party.
   A Congress Party spokesman denied the allegations.
   Singh, a onetime Gandhi ally now turned foe, is being trumpeted
by the opposition as an alternative to Gandhi for prime minister.
Full elections for Parliament must be held by January 1990.
   The six states in which elections were held were Allahabad, West
Bengal, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Haryana and Gujarat. Among the
opposition parties contesting the Congress Party were the Lok Dal,
Janata and Indian People's parties, as well as alliances.
   The Congress Party won five assembly seats in four different
states, the United News of India reported.
   It ran strongly in the desert state of Rajasthan, which has been
gripped by a severe drought this year, but lost its parliamentary
seat in Pali, in the Hindi heartland of Haryana.
   In Gujarat state, the Janata Party claimed the Godhra seat.
   Counting was postponed in two contests in opposition-ruled
Haryana state after Congress Party workers were attacked and
injured, the TV reported.
   But national attention remained focused on Allahabad, the
prestigious constituency of former prime ministers and the hometown
of the Gandhi family.
   The contest there has become a new test for Gandhi's popularity,
currently on the decline with charges of corruption against his
government.
   Singh resigned from Gandhi's Cabinet last year, saying the
government was not moving fast enough to investigate alleged
kickbacks in defense contracts.
   Singh campaigned on an anti-corruption platform, promising to
provide a ``clean'' alternative to the present government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
