<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     06-17 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Reports Fighting in North; Iran Condemns US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Friday its forces shot down an
Iranian helicopter during battles on the mountainous northern
border. An Iranian leader criticized a proposed U.S. arms sale to
Kuwait.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, speaker of the Iranian parliament and new
appointed commander of the armed forces, said the proposed $1.9
billion sale of U.S. aircraft and missiles to Kuwait was
``arrogant.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Thursday it would be
``a political breakthrough'' for Kuwait to tie itself to U.S.
technology and handle its own defense.
   U.S. warships now protect 11 Kuwaiti tankers in the Persian
Gulf, where Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
The tankers, half the Kuwaiti fleet, have been given American flags
and registration.
   Rafsanjani said Iran had achieved its goal in the drive launched
Monday toward Basra, Iraq's southern provincial capital, which he
said was to ``destroy the Iraqi forces in the Salamcheh area'' near
the border city.
   Iran gave no reports on fighting Friday but Iraq said its
helicopter gunships flew 295 combat sorties, the largest number
this week and an indication of heavy ground fighting.
   Dispatches from the official Iraqi News Agency said ground
forces in the northern sector shot down an Iranian helicopter and
fighting has heavy on the peaks surrounding the Ahmed Romi mountain
recaptured a day earlier.
   Iraqi reports said the town of Mawet was captured in a battle
that began Wednesday. Iranian forces took both town and mountain
last summer.
   Ahmed Romi, more than 6,500 feet high, overlooks an entire
valley and is about 25 miles northeast of Sulimaniyah, Iraq's
largest northern city and provincial capital of the Kurdish region.
The mountain is just over four miles from the border.
   In other developments Friday:
   _Richard Murphy, special U.S. envoy to the region, was in Saudi
Arabia at the start of an eight-nation tour to discuss both the
Iran-Iraq war and the Arab-Israeli conflict, diplomatic sources
reported.
   _Javier Perez de Cuellar, U.N. secretary-general, said he was in
weekly contact with officials of Iraq and Iran and had not
abandoned the attempt to end the war. He spoke to reporters after
briefing the Security Council on his latest efforts.
   _Saudi Arabia said it has not barred Iranian pilgrims from the
annual pilgrimage to Mecca and Medina next month, and warned Iran
against trying to foment trouble by proxy. Iran's supervisor of
pilgrims, Mehdi Karrubi, said Wednesday no Iranians would make the
pilgrimage because the Saudis had ``created obstacles.''
</TEXT>
