<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     06-17 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Police Get Death Sentence; Few Casualties Reported on Soweto
Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black policemen on Friday
were sentenced to hang for hiring an assassin to kill a woman who
charged them with torturing her during interrogation.
   Naftan Mchunu, the gunman who committed the murder, also was
sentenced to die by the Supreme Court in Pietermaritzburg, capital
of Natal Province.
   Police earlier reported that Thursday's anniversary of the 1976
Soweto black uprising passed with five injuries but no deaths in
township unrest. Black newspapers called for the day to be declared
an official holiday.
   The two black officers, Jabulani Zondi and Mphikwa Ndela, were
convicted of hiring the assassin to shoot Minah Ngcobo, a woman
they assaulted during an investigation in Natal.
   According to testimony at the trial, Miss Ngcobo filed charges
of attempted murder against the policemen after they put rubber
tubing over her face and ducked her head in a river during
interrogation.
   After the charges were filed, the officers hired Mchunu to
commit what Judge P.M. Nienaber called a ``cold-blooded, brutal and
self-serving execution.''
   Four other policemen, all white, have received the death penalty
in the past three months in two separate murder cases.
   Police in Pretoria reported about two dozen disturbances and 52
arrests in townships across the country Thursday as blacks marked
Soweto Day.
   The day, which has become an unofficial black holiday,
commemorates a 1976 protest during which police fired at students,
setting off months of nationwide rioting that left hundreds of
blacks dead.
   Most of the incidents Thursday involved firebombings or stonings
of vehicles. In several cases, police used tear gas or fired
gunshots to disperse crowds. Hundreds of thousands of blacks stayed
home from work.
   A suspected guerrilla from the outlawed African National
Congress was killed in Cape Town when explosives he was carrying
accidentally went off, police said.
   Two leading black newspapers, The Sowetan and City Press, noted
Soweto Day was observed with dignity by most blacks and called on
the government to declare June 16 an official holiday.
   At present, there are no official holidays of special
significance to the 26 million black majority in South Africa.
   The government intensified its monitoring of foreign journalists
by asking officials to report all interview requests from foreign
reporters and to rebuff those not accredited by the government.
   The Bureau of Information outlined the new policy in a letter
circulated to government departments, The Weekly Mail reported
Friday.
   The bureau confirmed existence of the letter, which also asked
officials to report all interview requests from accredited foreign
journalists ``so that you can be informed of the attitude of the
particular journalist and the media he represents, and the
activities of foreign journalists can be monitored more
efficiently.''
   Bureau director Dave Steward said the new procedure was aimed at
protecting unsuspecting officials from journalists who enter South
Africa ``under false pretenses with a view to produce one-sided and
vitriolic propaganda against South Africa.''
   A week ago, the government imposed new state-of-emergency press
restrictions on reporting anti-government activity.
   Regulations already in effect restrict reporting on security
force activity, unrest, various types of peaceful protest and a
range of ``subversive statements.''
   Also on Friday, the black metalworkers union called off a strike
at the Mercedes-Benz plant in East London and agreed to arbitration
following management's threat to fire the strikers.
   From 300 to 400 black workers had been on strike since June 9,
mainly over dismissals. The factory employs nearly 4,000 workers.
</TEXT>
