<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Economy     06-17 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Economy,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Rise After Government Lifts Most Wage, Price Controls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of dollars and food soared,
taxi drivers quadrupled fares and two unions demanded pay raises of
600 percent Friday, two days after the leftist Sandinista
government introduced free-market measures.
   Among actions taken were a huge devaluation of the cordoba,
Nicaragua's currency, a near-doubling of gasoline prices and a
general pay increase of 30 percent.
   The government retained subsidies on some basic foods. But in
markets where goods sell outside the rationing system at
free-market rates, the price of a liter of milk, just over a quart,
had gone from 6.6 to 21 cordobas; meat from 50 to 100 cordobas a
pound, and a dozen eggs from 50 to 80 cordobas.
   A dollar was worth 80 cordobas instead of the former 13 at the
official rate. On the black market Friday, a dollar bought 250
cordobas, 90 more than the market offered before devaluation.
   The transporation system was in disarray because of the new
gasoline prices. Cab drivers ignored the official tariff of 5
cordobas for a short trip, demanding 20, and many who own their
taxis simply stayed home.
   Two major unions controlled by the Socialist Party demanded
raises of 600 percent. The government called the positions of the
Workers' Federation of Nicaragua and General Federation of
Independent Workers ``unreal'' and inflationary.
   Primary school teachers earn about 2,500 cordobas a month and
their guild says that is not enough to live on. President Daniel
Ortega said he would meet with the teachers Sunday.
   So far, no public protests of the economic measures have been
held.
   Ortega told domestic critics Thursday they were ``playing with
fire'' by opposing the program and the political opposition might
``disappear if they don't respond with the patriotism our country
demands.''
</TEXT>
