<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Swindall     06-17 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swindall,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some in GOP Knew of Contents of Swindall Tapes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKSTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall apologized Friday for
considering a proposal to finance a $1 million home with laundered
drug and gambling money, saying he was wrong and ashamed but will
still run for re-election.
   The Republican congressman said his political future should be
left up to the voters of Georgia's 4th District, in Atlanta's
eastern suburbs.
   ``I was wrong to have ever considered such a proposal, to have
discussed, it,'' Swindall said. ``I was wrong not to have gone to
the authorities before I did.''
   He said, however, that he ``made the right decision'' in walking
away from the deal before he got in too deep.
   ``I do know the difference between right and wrong,'' Swindall
said at a news conference. ``I did not break the law nor do
anything unethical.''
   Swindall, who appeared to choke back tears while making his
opening statement, apologized to his supporters and family for
making them ``bear this burden.''
   Swindall said he would continue his campaign for re-election
because ``there is not another candidate who will reflect the
majority view of this district in Congress.''
   He said he had no ill will for the federal investigators
``because I think what they were doing is exactly what they should
be doing.''
   ``I think the drug situation in this country is such that we
need sting operations,'' he said.
   The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution reported
Thursday that transcripts of tapes made secretly by federal
authorities show Swindall was told money he was seeking to borrow
for a home in Stone Mountain might be illegal drug or gambling
profits.
   The tapes were made by Internal Revenue Service agent Michael
Mullaney. Mullaney, posing as a money broker for underworld
figures, was investigating Charles LeChasney when the Atlanta
businessman brought in Swindall to negotiate an $850,000 loan.
   LeChasney was indicted in February on federal money laundering
charges.
   Swindall said he did receive a $150,000 check at one point, but
he returned it uncashed. He said he terminated all dealings with
LeChasney when he began to suspect the money was tainted.
   ``A U.S. congressman ought to be totally above reproach,'' he
said. ``I wasn't above reproach. I will say that I have never been
as ashamed about anything as I am ashamed about what I have done.''
   Georgia Democratic Party Chairman John Henry Anderson sent Rep.
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., a letter of complaint against Swindall,
asking Gingrich to sign it and forward it to the House ethics
committee.
   Gingrich, who filed a complaint that has led to an ethics probe
of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said Thursday he would look
into a possible investigation.
   Swindall, at his news conference, said he would welcome such an
investigation as well as any other probe.
   ``I think I am subject to every investigation that can be
conceived by the human mind. When I make mistakes, I will confess
them and say this was a mistake,'' he said.
   Earlier Friday, Guy Davis, an Atlanta lawyer who was the Georgia
Republican gubernatorial nominee in 1986, said he met with
LeChasney in jail early this year and was warned Swindall would be
politically damaged by the laundering investigation.
   State party leaders heard the warning and rejected suggestions
that they get another candidate into the race for Swindall's seat,
said two participants in the discussions, Davis and Rich
Richardson, an Atlanta businessman and past financial contributor
to Swindall.
   ``Some believed that Pat was such a Mr. Clean guy that he'd come
out of it,'' Richardson recalled.
   Because the qualifying period has ended, no name other than
Swindall's can appear on the Republican primary ballot.
   Write-in votes are not allowed in the Aug. 9 primary, so any
Republican other than Swindall wishing to run would have to wage a
write-in campaign in November against the winner of the three-way
Democratic primary, said Lee Raudonis, executive director of the
Georgia Republican Party.
</TEXT>
