<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-ParliamentRebels     06-17 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Parliament Rebels,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Rejects Party Recommendation on Appointee</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Oath, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parliament on Friday have staged an
unprecedented rebellion against the ruling Communist Party
leadership, refusing to unseat an officeholder to create a vacancy
for a former Politburo member.
   Also Friday, Deputy Foreign Minister Tadeusz Olechowski was
appointed foreign minister to succeed Marian Orzechowski, who
assumed new Communist Party responsibilities earlier in the week.
   As foreign minister since 1985, Orzechowski saw Poland through a
period of improved relations with Western countries. Such relations
deteriorated following the 1981 military crackdown on the
independent Solidarity trade union movement.
   On the legislators' action, one deputy said it was the first
time the Sejm, or parliament, had turned down such a motion from
the party.
   ``I think it was a kind of warning addressed to the state
leadership that the old methods are not going to be effective and
not going to be tolerated,'' said Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, a Sejm
deputy and member of the Communist-allied United Peasant Party.
   The vote came the same day parliament passed unanimously a new
military oath that deleted a pledge to serve alongside the Soviet
army. The old pledge had been seen by some as an affront to Polish
sovereignty.
   Polish government officials have said the change was only an
updating of antiquated language and did not reflect a lessening of
the alliance with the Soviet Union.
   The parliament revolt came on a motion to remove Gen. Tadeusz
Hupalowski as head of the Supreme Chamber of Control, a post
similar to auditor general, to make room for Wlodzimierz
Mokryszczak, who left the Politburo of the Polish United Workers
(Communist) Party on Tuesday in a leadership reshuffle.
   Only 154 deputies, less than a majority of the 460-member Sejm,
voted in favor of removing Hupalowski, with 140 voting against and
40 abstaining. The motion was defeated.
   State radio initially announced Hupalowski had been removed and
Mokryszczak would replace him, but later corrected the report.
   A spokesman for the government press office said Friday night
there would be no immediate comment on the matter.
   Deputy Kozakiewicz said Hupalowski had been doing a good job and
most deputies felt his removal would harm parliament. He said the
proposed replacement ``didn't arouse such enthusiasm.''
   Increasing the power and independence of the Sejm has been one
of Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's aims in his program of
political reforms. But because the Communist Party dominates the
Sejm and the government, party dictates in the past have been
treated as law.
   Some deputies complained openly when they were instructed to
approve ministerial appointments with only a few hours to review
nominees during a government shake-up last year.
   Kozakiewicz said the parliament action Friday was ``important
proof that something is going on in the Sejm, that something is
changing, that some kind of mechanisms are at work.''
   Of the 460 deputies in the Sejm, 245 are Communists, 106 are
members of the United Peasant Party, 35 are members of the
Democratic Party and 74 are non-party members.
   The constitution says the Communist Party has the ``leading
role,'' and its leadership is recognized by the other two parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
