<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SoccerViolence 2ndLd-Writethru a0804 06-17 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soccer Violence, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0804,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roving Bands of English Fans Tear up Parts of Frankfurt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to delete redundant word `violent' in lede
and UPDATE with police charging demonstrators, arresting three.
PICKS up 7th pvs: In Munich...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   English and German soccer fans
went on rampages in Frankfurt and Munich Friday, and police said
the body of an Irishman was recovered from the River Main.
   They said the man apparently fell into the river while drunk and
he was not the victim of violence.
   English fans, on a self-proclaimed ``Invasion of Germany 1988,''
descended on Frankfurt from Duesseldorf for Saturday's match
between Britain and the Soviet Union in the European Soccer
Championship.
   Groups of rowdies smashed windows, overturned cars and hurled
beer bottles in a rampage through the streets early Friday.
   Small bands of English, West German and Italian hoodlums
scuffled Friday night near Frankfurt's main railroad station where
about 200 beer-drinking English fans had been milling about since
the afternoon, police reported.
   At one point police dispersed a group of dozens of Britons and
arrested three people, according to police.
   ``They (the English) came out of the bar looking for trouble and
they got it,'' said Peter Staskiewecz, a Frankfurt police spokesman.
   He said the English fans were marching down a street shouting
and singing when the police charged.
   In Munich, where West Germany defeated Spain 2-0 in a match,
police reported 59 arrests and said most of those jailed were
Germans but at least one was an Englishman. They also said 61
``skinheads,'' young men who shave their heads as part of a gang
cult, were rounded up to prevent violence but were not charged.
   Munich police said some of those arrested were accused of
damaging several cars in the train that took them to the Bavarian
capital.
   Several people, including three police officers, were slightly
injured in the violence early Friday in Frankrurt.
   This year's two-week soccer championships, which began June 10,
have led to some of the most elaborate police and security
preparations in several years in West Germany.
   The English fans already have left behind a string of arrests in
Stuttgart, Cologne and Duesseldorf. In Duesseldorf, police say West
German thugs sparked the violence by attacking the English.
   The violence already has prompted England to withdraw its
application for readmission to European club soccer tournaments
next season.
   English clubs were banned after the 1985 Heysel stadium tragedy
in which 39 people, most of them Italians, were killed in violence
sparked by English soccer fans.
   In preparation for Saturday's match, Frankfurt police put 1,400
officers on alert in Frankfurt, and special squads patrolled the
city.
   The expected troubles already have led many tavern owners to
announce they will close early over the weekend.
   ``This is a soccer-free area,'' said a sign taped up in one bar
window by an owner trying to keep drunken fans away.
   Early Friday, fans smashed up bars and brawled with German
tavern patrons in Frankfurt's Sachsenhausen district and near the
main railroad station.
   ``There were at least 60 English fans involved, and they had
split up into groups,'' Frankfurt police spokesman Karl-Heinz
Wagner told The Associated Press.
   The rowdies also overturned cars, hurled beer bottles at
passers-by and smashed store windows, Wagner said. Ten English
soccer fans and a West German were arrested, he said.
   Later Friday, police said the body of a 29-year-old Irish soccer
fan was found floating in the Main River running through Frankfurt.
   Police said there was no immediate indication of foul play and
that the victim apparently drowned while intoxicated. Wagner said
the body was discovered Thursday night.
   In Duesseldorf, police spokesman Wolfgang Rodax said that two
days of violence among soccer fans there led to 371 arrests. Of
those, 18 were English and most of the others West German.
   ``Neither before nor after the game were the English the ones
who started the street battles, fights and brawls,'' said Rodax.
   Rodax accused West German thugs of starting the disturbances
Tuesday and Wednesday as the Dutch beat the English 3-1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
