<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Italy-Terrorists     06-17 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Terrorists,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Arrested In Discovery of Red Brigades Hideout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities discovered a Red Brigades
terrorist hideout, arrested nine people and seized a submachine gun
possibly used to kill a former U.S. diplomat, police said Friday.
   Warrants issued by a prosecutor in Milan accused the nine people
of participating in an armed band and of illegally possessing
weapons, said Col. Luigi Nobili, commander of Milan's carabinieri
police.
   A police anti-terrorist squad discovered the hideout Thursday in
a Milan apartment after a two-year investigation of a group
suspected of trying to rebuild Italy's left-wing terrorism network,
Nobili told a news conference Friday.
   The Red Brigades terrorized Italy in the 1970s with kidnappings
and assassinations, including the murder of former Prime Minister
Aldo Moro in 1978.
   Nobili said officers found two machine guns and a submachine
gun, ammunition, 60 million lire ($46,000) and documents related to
killings claimed by the Red Brigades and a related group, the
Fighting Communists.
   He said investigators believed the submachine gun may have been
used to kill American Leaman R. Hunt, director-general of the
Multinational Force and Observers. The Rome-based group monitored
the Egypt-Israel peace treaty in the Sinai Peninsula.
   Hunt, a career diplomat, was assassinated in Rome in February
1984.
   The submachine gun may also have been used in the murders of
Sen. Roberto Ruffilli, economist Ezio Tarantelli and former
Florence Mayor Lando Conti, Nobili said.
   The Red Brigades claimed responsibility for killing the three
Italians, while the Fighting Communists said they killed Hunt.
   Ballistics experts were checking the submachine gun, police said.
   Ruffilli, a Christian Democrat and close friend and adviser of
Premier Ciriaco De Mita, was killed last April at his apartment in
Forli, a small town near Bologna.
   Tarantelli, who was shot and killed in Rome in March 1985, was a
leading official of the Christian Democrat-dominated labor union
CISL and had been a member of the government commission that
drafted a plan to reduce Italian workers' automatic wage increases.
   Conti, who was killed in February 1986 in Florence, was a
consultant for a company that produced radar and other military
electronic equipment. He had been accused in left-wing pamphlets of
``exporting war.''
</TEXT>
