<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PrisonEscape 2ndLd-Writethru a0727 06-17 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Escape, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0727,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Escapees From Kentucky Penitentiary Still At Large</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with two grafs to UPDATE with one Kentucky escapee
caught, another sighted, picking up 2nd graf: `A lockdown; SUBS
11th graf, ``Until they've ... with 2 grafs of details about
escapee.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDDYVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities captured one prison escapee
and searched for seven others by plane, boat, car and foot Friday,
and a prosecutor who sent one of the men to prison for murder was
given extra protection.
   Robert G. Sherman, was caught 15 minutes after he was sighted on
Interstate 24, about a mile from the maximum-security prison, said
corrections Capt. Billy Adams. Authorities said they spotted
another escapee in the same vicinity, but lost him after a short
chase.
   A lockdown at the century-old Kentucky State Penitiary entered a
second day, with the prison's approximately 770 inmates kept in
their cells except for meals.
   Authorites in North Carolina, meanwhile, on Friday captured the
third of six detainees who escaped a county jail.
   In the Kentucky prison break early Thursday, the escapees sawed
open their cell doors and cut through a prison window, then climbed
down an extension cord 30 feet to the ground. Guards had been
diverted by fires set elsewhere in the prison.
   Authorities found a 2- to 3-inch piece of a hacksaw in one of
the escapee's cells, prison spokesman Bobby Waller said Friday.
   In Louisville, 200 miles northeast of the prison, extra security
was put into effect for Jefferson County Commonwealth's Attorney
Ernest Jasmin, said an assistant, John W. Stewart. Jasmin
prosecuted Leo C. Spurling, 30, for murder and sent him to prison
for life.
   Jasmin first declined the offer of protection but later
accepted, Stewart said. Stewart declined to give details of
Jasmin's protection. It was ``nothing to suggest we're afraid, but
better safe than sorry,'' he said.
   The successful jailbreak by the eight inmates, four of them
convicted murderers, was the largest in state history. Nine other
inmates also tried to flee, authorities said.
   The penitentiary, five miles east of Eddyville on Lake Barkley,
is surrounded on three sides by water and on the fourth by woods,
but no wall or fence enclosed the cellblock from which the eight
fled.
   Waller said a boat, two police small airplanes, 20 troopers, a
dog team, local authorities and 60 prison officers were combing the
area. Guards with shotguns searched all vehicles leaving the
facility.
   Sherman told authorities he had gone off by himself after the
escape, then hid and did not move until Thursday night, Warden
William Seabold said, adding that Sherman appeared embarrassed when
told he was the first escapee caught.
   Sherman, 30, of Lilly, arrived back at the prison at 4:35,
shirtless and with his heavily tatooed back full of scratches. He
had been serving 15 years for robbery, escape, wanton endangerment
and promoting contraband.
   At least some of the inmates were thought to have fled in a
pickup truck stolen before dawn Thursday a quarter-mile from the
prison. State police investigated a reported sighting of the
vehicle Thursday night, but found nothing.
   In the North Carolina escape from the Cumberland County Jail,
authorities said Gregory Maurice Lee, 30, who had been serving time
for first-degree burglary, larceny and assault on a female,
surrendered to police in Fayetteville.
   ``The next time, I will get out of town,'' he told police. ``I
was too busy running.''
   Six people sawed through jail bars and dropped from a rope made
of sheets to escape from the jail Sunday night; one was captured
immediately, the second on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
