<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MrsLetterman     06-17 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mrs Letterman,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Mrs. Letterman' Declared Incompetent To Stand Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claimed to be the wife of talk
show host David Letterman after allegedly breaking into his home
and taking his car is incompetent to stand trial, a judge ruled
Friday.
   The ruling by Superior Court Judge James Bingham came after
testimony from a doctor that 36-year-old Margaret Ray is ``rambling
and has impaired judgment.''
   Bingham ordered that Ms. Ray be taken to a psychiatric hospital
and examined by a team of doctors. Meanwhile, he ruled that she was
not mentally able to stand trial because, ``she is able to
understand the charges against her, but she is unable to assist in
her own defense.''
   ``She was rambling, exhibited flight of ideas and was
delusional,'' the doctor, James Alexander of Bridgeport, said of
his 45-minute examination. ``She feels there is a power of some
kind controlling her behavior.''
   Ms. Ray testified that she was simply ``cold, tired and hungry''
from her jail stay.
   Ms. Ray has been jailed under $25,000 bond since her arrest May
22, when police said she was stopped driving Letterman's 1988
Porsche and tried to pass herself off as his wife. Police said they
later discovered Letterman's New Canaan home had been broken into
and it appeared someone had been living there for several days.
   Letterman, the host of ``Late Night With David Letterman,'' has
said he does not know Ms. Ray.
   Letterman declined to press charges following the first
incident. But Ms. Ray, who police say has no known address, was
arrested after she returned to Letterman's house a few days later.
   Police said that she was eating and writing what she decribed as
scripts for Letterman's show when police found her in his living
room during the second incident.
   She has been charged with two counts of second-degree burglary
and one court of first-degree larceny.
</TEXT>
