<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Wright 1stLd-Writethru a0657 06-17 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Wright, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inquiry Of Speaker's Ethics A Thorny Issue For Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 22-23 pvs, `In addition ... enforcement officer,'
with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Wright and comments about him at Texas
convention</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis insists an investigation of House
Speaker Jim Wright will not affect his presidential bid, but
Republicans who think otherwise are looking forward to pressing the
issue during what should be Dukakis' shining moment _ the
Democratic National Convention.
   Dukakis, the certain Democratic presidential nominee, wasted few
opportunities during the primary season to lambaste malfeasance in
the Reagan administration, delivering particularly harsh criticism
of embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Now Republicans, who successfully sought a House ethics
investigation of Wright's conduct, are firing back and trying to
neutralize the so-called GOP ``sleaze factor'' with attacks on the
nation's highest-ranking elected Democrat.
   Wright is chairman of the national convention in Atlanta and as
such will attract lots of national television time during the
three-day gathering.
   An embarrassment for Dukakis?
   ``I thought there was a presumption of innocence in this
country,'' was his reply when asked Thursday.
   That may be true in the courts; perhaps not in politics.
   ``In a politically charged atmosphere, it's going to take on a
life of its own,'' said Bob Beckel, who managed Walter F. Mondale's
1984 presidential campaign. ``The reality is that the Republicans
are going to make every bit of political hay out of this _ and they
should.''
   When the Democrats huddle next month to crown Dukakis as their
nominee and to set the tone for the campaign against Republican
George Bush, there will be plenty of GOP strategists on hand to
offer their perspective to the news media.
   Wright will be in the limelight _ and under the spotlight.
   ``He will be up there at the podium longer than Michael Dukakis
or anyone else, for all to see, and that is an embarrassment,''
said William Schneider, a political analyst at the American
Enterprise Institute.
   ``And every night we'll have (national GOP chairman) Frank
Fahrenkopf on television talking about the Democrats and their
`sleaze factor,''' said Schneider. ``Imagine if Ed Meese was
running the Republican convention.''
   Dukakis aides say there have been no attempts to reduce Wright's
visibility at the convention.
   ``The governor has talked to Speaker Wright and the speaker
assured him that this will move expeditiously and that the outcome
will be fine,'' said Chuck Campion, Dukakis' national political
director. ``We see no ramifications at all.''
   There may also be an independent investigation of allegations
Wright lobbied improperly on behalf of oil companies with which he
may have had financial relationships, questions surrounding
publication of a book for which he received a higher-than-usual
royalty and which was produced with the help of a congressionally
paid staffer, contacts with federal officials on behalf of Texas
savings and loans and the use of a condominium for which he paid no
monthly rent.
   Dukakis maintains the speaker's troubles are not comparable to
those of Meese or others in the Reagan administration who have been
convicted of or accused of wrongdoing _ pointing to Wright's
cooperation while saying many in the administration have tried to
stonewall investigators.
   And he sees no inconsistency in his demand that Meese resign
while he is making no such request of Wright.
   ``If you're attorney general of this country and you've stumbled
as often as he has and made as many mistakes as he has and provided
as weak leadership as he has, you ought to leave office,'' Dukakis
said.
   He insists otherwise, but the allegations against Wright must
trouble Dukakis, who built his reputation as a good-government
reformer by challenging entrenched Boston pols who openly relished
their power.
   ``It must irritate him wildly to see this thing happening to
Democratic leaders,'' said Schneider. ``One gets the impression
that he'd like to fire Jim Wright. This is just the type of thing
that drives Michael Dukakis crazy. He wants to keep a thousand
miles away from anything that associates him with the sleaze
factor.''
   That won't be possible.
   In addition to the convention, Dukakis might also run into
Wright this weekend at the Texas Democratic Convention. Dukakis
aides said they were not sure if the two would hold a private
meeting there.
   At the convention in Houston on Friday night, Wright drew a
standing ovation from delegates. He made no mention of the ethics
probe during a keynote speech, but ex-Gov. Mark White, who
introduced Wright, called on Republicans who levied the allegations
at Wright to ``clean up your own house before you slander the name
of Jim Wright.''
   Texas Democratic Chairman Bob Slagle said the allegations of
financial improprieties are based on party politics, saying, ``What
is really bothering the Republicans about Jim Wright is he is the
most effective speaker since Sam Rayburn died.''
   Dukakis was quick to criticize Meese when questioned Thursday.
But attacks on the attorney general were missing from Dukakis'
rhetoric during three Massachusetts events this week designed to
portray him as a tough crimefighter _ seemingly the perfect type of
forum to criticize the nation's top law enforcement officer.
   ``I think it's wise for him to do that now,'' said Schneider.
``What he has to do is talk about the yard-long list of indictments
and convictions in this administration, not just Ed Meese.''
   Beckel said the greatest test is how Dukakis handles himself at
the convention.
   ``Dukakis should keep his distance from Wright but not abandon
him,'' Beckel said. ``He's got enough to worry about right now. For
Dukakis, it's like walking into a mine field.''
</TEXT>
