<2ND_LINE>AM-Medellin Cartel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0788,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Say Drug Kingpin Tried To Set Up Colorado Cocaine Hub</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Authorities estimated ... to CLARIFY amount
of cocaine authorities have confiscated in the United States.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian alleged to be among the world's major
cocaine traffickers was indicted with five other people Friday in
an alleged attempt to establish a cocaine distribution center in
Colorado.
   The five-count indictment handed down in U.S. District Court
here alleges that Pablo Emilio Escobar-Gaviria, a principal in the
Medellin cartel of Colombian cocaine traffickers, and five others
planned to ship up to 800 kilograms of cocaine a week into the
Denver area.
   Authorities, who arrested four of the defendants and seized 738
pounds of cocaine in a May 25 motel raid, estimated that 800 kilos
of cocaine could have a street value of as much as $17 million.
   The indictment accuses the men of importing the cocaine with the
intent of distributing it in the United States.
   Escobar, 39, also is under indictment in the Southern District
of Florida, on charges of conspiracy to import and distribute
drugs, said U.S. Attorney Michael J. Norton.
   ``Escobar-Gaviria is considered by some to be one of the major
cocaine traffickers in the world,'' Norton said.
   Escobar-Gaviria and another man named in the indictment remain
at large. Four others named in the indictment were arrested May 25
at a motel in Boulder by agents of the FBI and Drug Enforcement
Administration and accused of trying to smuggle 335 kilograms _ or
about 738 pounds _ of cocaine into Colorado.
   ``The drug cartel told our informants that increased federal law
enforcement efforts in south Florida, south Texas and Southern
California had made them seek new distribution centers in the
U.S.,'' Norton said.
   Members of the cartel also complained that increased efforts by
law enforcement authorities in Colombia were hurting the cartel's
drug operations, Norton said.
   Norton said a three-month DEA investigation disrupted plans to
fly the cocaine from Colombia to Colorado for further distribution
in California and Florida ``as well as the fertile Rocky Mountain
area.''
   The cocaine would have been flown by a private twin-engine plane
into Jefferson County Airport at Broomfield, about 18 miles
northwest of Denver, Norton said.
</TEXT>
