<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti 1stLd-Writethru a0844 06-17 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0844,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Manigat Fires Armed Forces Chief for Insubordination</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CORRECT name Nicholas to Nicolas and
EXPAND on Paul's command duties. PICKS up 7th graf pvs, The
constitution ...</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ President Leslie Manigat fired the
commander in chief of the Haitian army and two other generals
Friday night, accusing them of insubordination.
   National television read a communique stating that Manigat had
retired Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, the commander, and two other members
of the general staff, brigadier generals Carl Michel Nicolas and
Wilton Cherisson.
   Col. Morton Gousse was promoted to brigadier general and named
acting commander in chief until the Senate names a new one, the
communique said.
   The president overruled Namphy on Wednesday by rescinding an
order issued the previous day transferring and retiring
high-ranking officers. Manigat said the order was unconsitutional
because it was done without consulting him.
   Manigat, alleged to be the army's candidate in junta-run
elections last January, has maintained that he rules independently.
   Namphy's order had included the transfer of Col. Jean-Claude
Paul, commander of the largest unit in Haiti's 6,000-man army, who
was indicted on drug trafficking charges by a federal grand jury in
Florida earlier this year.
   The constitution names the president as ``nominal'' commander in
chief of the armed forces and the head of the army as ``effective''
commander in chief.
   Manigat took over on Feb. 7 from Namphy as Haiti's chief
executive. Namphy had been president of a ruling junta for exactly
two years after President-for-Life Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to
exile in France.
   Manigat met for four hours Wednesday with the army general
staff, headed by Namphy, and obtained a statement from the general
staff pledging allegiance to Manigat's civilian government and
``tentatively'' accepting Manigat's decision to overrule Namphy,
according to local news reports.
   Manigat's decree said that despite their pledge on Wednesday,
Namphy and other members of the general staff ``began to execute
the order'' retiring and transferring officers.
   It said their action ``is a sort of insubordination ... toward
the constitutional commander in chief (the president).''
   The communique said all members of the Cabinet endorsed
Manigat's action, including Defense Minister Williams Regala.
   Regala was the other military member with Namphy of the
three-man junta that ruled Haiti until Manigat was inaugurated
following elections in January.
   Manigat's decision to rescind his top army commander's order
resulted in the first crisis between his civilian government and
the military, which has traditionally held power in this
improverished Caribbean nation.
   Namphy had ordered Col. Paul transferred as commander of the
700-man Dessalines Barracks, the most feared army unit in Haiti, to
assistant chief of staff, a largely administrative post. Paul
reportedly refused to accept the transfer.
   It was unclear why Namphy ordered the transfer, whether it
signified a power struggle within the army or whether the transfer
was linked to the charges of drug-running against Paul, who has
denied the charges.
   Soldiers under Paul's command were blamed for widespread
violence against voters that forced cancellation of last November's
independently adminstrated general elections and left more than 30
people dead.
   Gen. Nicolas, who was the army chief-of-staff, earlier this year
accused the foreign press of singling out Col. Paul, 49, for
attacks related to the drug allegations.
</TEXT>
