involvement; SUBS 3rd graf, `Cage said ... with 2 grafs to add
quote from lawyer about alleged Noriega role; SUBS 5th graf, `The
indictment ..., to clarify that 100 people facing further charges
are a subset of the 170; SUBS grafs 10-11 `Cage refused ... with
two grafs to add background; picks up 12th graf: `Each and ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal indictments unsealed Friday
charged 170 people as members of a huge, international drug ring
linked to Panama's Manuel Noriega that dealt in more than $1
billion worth of marijuana and cocaine.
   Noriega was not charged in the indictments, which disclosed that
that the Panamanian strongman allegedly laundered profits from the
sale of marijuana shipped to a Louisiana shipyard.
   ``This organization is sophisticated, well orchestrated and
rivals any multinational corporation,'' U.S. Attorney Joe Cage
said. ``Its sole motivation, greed and money, caused its scope and
influence to transcend local, national and international
boundaries.''
   Cage said the indictments resulted from the same federal
investigation that led to Noriega's indictment in Florida on
charges of laundering U.S. drug money through Panamanian banks.
   If Noriega had not been indicted already in Florida, ``in my
opinion, there would have been sufficient evidence for an
indictment'' here, said Judith Lombardino, lawyer for the federal
Organized Crime Drug Enforcement Task Force.
   Cage said the widespread, 2{-year-old federal investigation
extended into Florida, North Carolina and Michigan.
   The indictment alleges that 170 people conspired to import
nearly 1.5 million pounds of marijuana into the country. Of the
170, more than 100 also are accused of traveling to Lafayette to
arrange the importation of 280,000 pounds of marijuana.
   Cage said 500,000 pounds of marijuana was imported to and
distributed from Lafayette and several thousand pounds of cocaine
was flown to Shreveport.
   The Louisiana investigation centered to a large extent on
shipments of marijuana believed to have been unloaded at the
Intracoastal Drydock and Shipbuilding Co. on the Vermilion River
near the town of Bancker, La.
   The federal grand jury charged Abbeville, La., residents William
E. Faciane and James C. Faciane, both employees of the family owned
shipyard with importing 500,000 pounds of marijuana to the Bancker
site.
   Noriega is alleged to have laundered profits from the sale of
280,000 pounds of marijuana shipped there, the indictment alleges.
   Cage refused to comment on any details of Noriega's alleged
involvement with the drug ring or whether Colombia's Medellin
Cartel was involved. In a federal indictment handed up Feb. 4 in
Miami, Noriega was charged with taking protection money from the
cartel.
   Cage would not identify any of those indicted as ringleaders,
nor would he pinpoint a headquarters for the drug ring.
   ``Each and every individual named in the indictment allegedly
played a vital role in the success of this organization. There is
no such thing as a minimal role in planning and executing a network
of this size.''
   Many of those charged in the 131-page indictment were identified
as ``John Doe.''
   Among those indicted are several foreign nationals believed to
be involved in the systematic trafficking of marijuana and cocaine.
They include David Arrana, Cesar Cura, Vanderbilt Bowie Davis,
Lucio Cardona, all of Colombia;
   Edward ``Gill'' Bodden of the Cayman Islands; Felice Napolitano
of Panama; Ed Whyte, a Canadian citizen living in Jamaica; and
Carlos Zayas-Castro of Colombia and the Cayman Islands.
   Cage said several arrests have been made, but he refused to say
how many.
   He said the federal government's Organized Crime Drug
Enforcement Task Force headed up the investigation, code named
``The Bulldog.''
   The investigation resulted in the indictment of at least 82
other people in the federal judicial districts in North Carolina,
Florida and Michigan.
</TEXT>
