<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Byways-Taba Adv22   06-17 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Byways-Taba, Adv 22,0880</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs June 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WORLD BYWAYS: Taba _ Disputed Place with Only a Hotel and a Beach</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic dispatches
by Associated Press correspondents on life and customs in the
byways of the world. The writer is based in Cairo, Egypt's capital.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   TABA, Egypt-Israel Border (AP) _ Taba might be returned to Egypt
in a few months, but for now, it's as Israeli as a kibbutz. It
fact, it is Israel.
   Try popping over from Egypt's Sinai Peninsula for lunch at the
plush 327-room Aviya-Sonesta Beach Hotel, the only place that
really counts in the tiny enclave claimed by both Egypt and Israel.
   ``Are you going to Israel?'' asked the Egyptian policeman at the
gate of a chain-link fence a few hundred yards from the
white-painted, 10-story hotel.
   ``No, just to that hotel.''
   ``That,'' the policeman said, ``is Israel.''
   It took 30 minutes to complete paperwork required to get from
the Egyptian gate to a similar one 75 yards away where Israeli
customs inspectors waited.
   Lunch is delayed 90 minutes more.
   ``Did anybody in Egypt give you anything to deliver in Israel?''
one of the Israelis asked.
   No, I just want to have lunch in that hotel there.
   ``Did you buy anything in Egypt that you didn't see being
packed?''
   No, I live in Egypt. I just want to have lunch in that hotel
right there.
   ``They didn't try to tell you in Egypt that Taba is not
Israel's, did they?''
   Taba, where nobody lives permanently and the hotel, its guests
and the beach are all that matters, is a political curiosity left
over from war.
   At the extreme east-central edge of the Sinai Peninsula where
the Gulf of Aqaba ends, it fell to the Israelis in the 1967
Arab-Isaraeli war. The Israelis pulled out of the rest of Sinai in
1982 _ in accordance with the peace treaty signed three years
earlier _ but kept Taba, a squib of 250 acres just south of
Israel's Eilat and west of Jordan's Aqaba, both on the Gulf of
Aqaba.
   The crux of the competing claims is the location of Marker 91,
the southernmost marker delineating British-mandated Palestine in a
1906 agreement between the British and the Ottoman empires. The
Egyptians say their maps show the marker generally where Israel's
entry point is. Israel's maps put it at the Egyptian fence.
   After years of contention, Egypt and Israel agreed in September
1986 to appoint arbiters to sit down in Geneva and decide whether
Taba is extreme eastern Sinai (Egypt) or extreme southern Israel.
   Both sides summed up their arguments in April, and under the
arbitration agreement a judgment should be issued by midsummer, a
final, binding decision.
   Before the Israelis came, Taba basically comprised a
stone-and-sand beach at the end of a desert wadi.
   There's still precious little in Taba besides the Sonesta and
Rafi Nelson's Village, a swimming facility with a pub and snack bar
at the beach.
   Coiled barbed wire separates the hotel's swimming pool and
volleyball courts from the road. A hill with a guard tower at the
top commands one side of the hotel. On the other side are 800 yards
of Gulf of Aqaba beach and Rafi Nelson's Village. The employees of
the hotel and the village live in Eilat, a mile or so away.
   While on the face of it Taba hardly seems worth the fuss, it
seems clear that both governments went to the wall for their claims
with an eye to domestic politics.
   Egypt's leaders have said repeatedly that Israel will be ceded
``not one centimeter'' of Egyptian land. Thus, Taba either must be
returned, or it must be adjudged not to be Egyptian.
   As for the Israelis, they too undoubtedly would find a binding
legal verdict more palatable than a bilateral compromise. Publicly,
they say the enclave would be strategically critical for Eilat
should the Egyptians, the only Arabs at peace with Israel, turn
hostile again.
   Taba's guard tower is manned by the Multinational Force and
Observers, an international group organized under the 1979
U.S.-brokered peace treaty, which the arbitration agreement brought
into the enclave for the first time.
   The implication was that until sovereignty was determined, the
enclave would be a no man's land.
   Cairo never has told its people otherwise, and they can't learn
firsthand because their government has forbidden them to enter Taba
until the Egyptian claim is vindicated.
   As for the hotel, owned by Israeli Eli Papoushado and managed by
the Sonesta chain, nobody wants to talk about what might happen if
Taba becomes Egyptian. It's too sensitive an issue right now.
   In the meantime, Western women occasionally doff bikini tops
around the swimming pool and on the beach.
   But one indication of what might happen in an Egyptian Taba are
the signs at the gate going back to Egypt.
   No doffing of swimsuits at the Egyptian beach, they say.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs June 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
