<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Unions Divided, Adv 22,0888</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, June 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's Once-Militant Unions now Divided</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAKEFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-union laws, Japanese work
techniques and a scarcity of jobs have begun to transform Britain's
once-militant labor unions.
   Single-union and no-strike deals are spreading, provoking a
bitter fight among the country's declining unions and threatening
to split their umbrella organization, the Trades Union Congress _
the TUC.
   In this ugly red-brick, Yorkshire city of 59,000, a new
$93-million plant being built jointly by Coca-Cola Co. and Cadbury
Schweppes PLC is bringing 500 new jobs to a region where
unemployment is 12.7 percent, nearly 4 percentage points above the
national average.
   The plant's work force will be represented by a single union,
where past practice would have meant each worker category would
have had its own union.
   But while that may be bad news for the 120-year-old TUC, it is
no big issue in places like Wakefield, where the decline of
traditional coal and textile industries makes getting a job much
more important than defending union rights.
   ``Unions are on the way out,'' said Wakefield's Nigel Bilton, 22
years old and unemployed. ``I think unions should be abolished.''
   Thirty single-union deals, 10 of which include no-strike
provisions, have been struck in British industry, up from six
single-union deals and zero no-strike agreements five years ago,
according to the Amalgamated Engineering Union (AEU).
   ``The number is growing. We envision it doubling by the end of
this year,'' says John Mann, the union's research manager.
   Such deals, under which one union represents all the workers at
a plant and arbitration replaces strikes, are expected to multiply
even faster after a stunning defeat for the unions in Scotland this
past March.
   Japanese, then American, and now British companies have sought
these new single-union deals because they find it simpler and
cheaper to negotiate with one union rather than several.
   The 42,000 workers at Ford Motor Co. in Britain, for example,
have 12 different unions.
   Ford has scrapped plans to build an electronics plant in Dundee
in Scotland because it couldn't get its unions to accept the
single-union deal it had reached with the Amalgamated Engineering
Union.
   The dramatic reversal scuttled what would have been Ford's 23rd
British plant, cost 450 new jobs and provoked widespread anger
against what Scottish Secretary Malcolm Rifkind termed the unions'
``neanderthal attitudes.''
   Opponents of single-union deals maintain, however, that one
union cannot adequately represent a work force ranging from
engineers to typists.
   Championing the new union deals are the 800,000-member AEU and
the 360,000-member Electrical, Electronic, Telecommunication and
Plumbing Union (EETPU).
   Membership in the 84-union TUC has shrunk from 13 million to 9
million since 1979, and the government can now boast that the days
when Britain could be crippled by strikes are over. Days lost to
strikes have fallen from 29 million in 1979 to just 2.5 million in
the year up to March.
   Unemployment is one reason, but another is Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's legislation, which forces unions to take strike
votes and obtain a 55-percent yes-vote before calling a walkout.
The legislation also outlaws secondary picketing, and no longer
requires employers to recognize a union even if employees have
chosen it in a vote.
   The Trades Union Congress is threatening to expel the EETPU
electricians at its annual meeting in September over single-union
deals.
   At the same time, the EETPU is asking its members in a ballot
whether to pull out of the TUC and talking to the AEU about joining
forces to form their own breakaway organization that would take
away one-ninth of the TUC's membership.
   ``Such a split in the union movement would change the face of
industrial relations and have serious implications for the Labor
Party,'' the Independent newspaper wrote.
   The Labor Party is the main opposition to Mrs. Thatcher's
Conservative Party government, and the unions are the Laborites
power base.
   The Wakefield factory, which is Europe's newest soft-drink
plant, ``is going to mean a lot for the community of Wakefield,''
said Mayor George Parkinson.
   Dick Croft, a local official for the engineering union that will
represent the Wakefield plant workers, said the community was lucky
that Coke and Cadbury decided to have any union at all.
   The new style has been introduced largely by egalitarian-minded
Japanese companies that have abolished separate dress codes, put in
employee canteens and provided parking lots for hourly workers as
well as for management.
   They offer enticing wages in return for high productivity and
shopfloor moderation. British workers have embraced the change,
confounding those who accuse them of resisting change and upholding
class distinctions.
   Norman Willis, the TUC's general secretary, argues that
single-union deals encourage damaging competition among unions for
a smaller pool of members in the trade union movement.
   The 1.35-million-member Transport and General Workers Union,
Britain's largest, also is a major opponent of the new style for
pretty much the same reasons.
   But up here in Yorkshire, the engineering union's Croft said,
``The world is changing. We don't enjoy the same franchise we had a
few years ago.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, June 22</NOTE>
