<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:RogerRabbitRights Adv19   06-17 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Roger Rabbit Rights, Adv 19,0505</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Roger Rabbit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Untangling Rights for Cartoon Menagerie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer Steven Spielberg was able to land
Bugs Bunny, Betty Boop, Woody Woodpecker, Porky Pig and Daffy Duck,
but he couldn't get Popeye, Olive Oyl or Felix the Cat.
   It was all part of the difficult task of acquiring rights to
famous cartoon characters from five studios to appear in the movie,
``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.'' It's a cinematic first.
   ``I don't think anyone else in Hollywood except Steven Spielberg
could have done it,'' said director Robert Zemeckis.
   ``Because of the nature of the project and who was involved, it
wasn't as complicated as it might have been. Once we landed the
Warners characters (Bugs Bunny, Daffy Duck, Porky Pig), everyone
else came on board.''
   Since Spielberg produced ``Goonies,'' ``The Color Purple'' and
other moneymakers for Warner Bros., getting Bugs Bunny and other
Warners cartoon stars into the fold was a relatively easy sell.
   The $40 million movie is a project from the Walt Disney Co.'s
Touchstone Pictures, so using the beloved Disney animated
characters was no problem. Spielberg is an executive producer.
   He was able to enlist Woody Woodpecker from Universal, Betty
Boop from Paramount and the MGM stable. But he hit a roadblock on
Popeye and Olive Oyl, who declined the project on orders from their
copyright owners, King Features. Spielberg also couldn't snare the
pioneering Felix, whose origins date to 1914.
   Contracts for use of the cartoon characters were voluminous.
   ``They are very important stars at their own studios,'' said
Zemeckis. ``(The companies) wanted to know who the animators would
be, and they supervised the designs. They really look out for those
characters.
   ``Naturally, they wanted to be sure their stars would not be
portrayed in anything derogatory, such as drug dealing. But of
course we would never do anything like that.''
   The major restriction on Disney was that the loan-out stars
could not be featured in advertising. They are included in the
film's credits, but cannot be used in commercials. Not to worry;
the studio has a few characters of its own to use.
   On the whole, ``the other studios were very cooperative, giving
us style sheets to guide our animators,'' said Richard Williams,
who directed the animation.
   ``But I had plenty of style sheets myself, having collected them
over the years from many different sources.''
   Not all the cartoon stars for which rights were obtained ended
up in ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'': MGM's Tom and Jerry were
casualties of the cutting room.
   But at least 15 of them ended up with speaking parts, including
Daffy Duck, Tweety Bird, Bugs Bunny, Porky Pig and Sylvester, all
Mel Blanc's voice, and Betty Boop (Mae Questel), Yosemite Sam (Joe
Alaskey), Mickey Mouse (Wayne Allwine), Goofy (Tony Pope), Minnie
Mouse (Russi Taylor) and Pinocchio (Peter Westy).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
