<1ST_LINE>s w BC-Summit-OtherIssues Adv19   06-17 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Other Issues, Adv 19,0875</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drug Trade, East-West Relations Expected to Be Discussed at Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At his final round of economic summitry,
President Reagan will challenge his colleagues to deny hijackers a
refuge and to make it harder for drug dealers to keep their
ill-gotten profits.
   Economic problems will be the primary focus as the leaders of
the world's seven industrial democracies gather this week in
Toronto.
   But as they have tended to do over the years, the leaders
probably will be looking to a number of other concerns, such as
international trouble spots and East-West relations in the wake of
the Moscow summit.
   Such topics usually come up over meals, when the leaders have a
chance to talk informally, officials say.
   Reagan, in a recent address sketching his goals for the summit,
said he will ask the leaders of Canada, Britain, France, Italy,
Japan and West Germany to ``join together to attack the lifeblood
of one trade that should never be part of international trade _ the
international narcotics trade.''
   ``At this summit, we should join in a common offensive against
money laundering and the flow of drug profits through the world's
financial institutions,'' Reagan said. Through the so-called
practice of ``money laundering,'' drug dealers transfer their
illegal profits through legitimate banks.
   Secretary of State George Shultz has expressed hope the United
States will be able to enlist the leaders in ``a broad and
comprehensive effort'' on the problem.
   Shultz's top economics adviser, Undersecretary of State Allen
Wallis, said that he expected ``a general discussion of the whole
drug problem from beginning to end'' at the conference.
   Treasury Secretary James Baker III said that he hoped the summit
``could find a way to improve our cooperation'' on halting the
money laundering, as well as improving exchanges of intelligence
information to battle the drug problem.
   But for all the attention the issue may receive at the summit,
like many other matters, the outcome is uncertain.
   John D. Steinbruner, the director of foreign policy studies at
the Brookings Institution in Washington, said the drug issue ``is
emerging as the hottest immediate political topic, but nobody quite
knows what to do about it.''
   ``I think there will be a lot of debate, but not much
resolution,'' Steinbruner said.
   On a related subject, Shultz said he intended to use the summit
to discuss the drug trafficking of Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, who was indicted earlier this year in Florida on narcotics
charges. U.S. economic sanctions designed to help drive Noriega
from power have not borne fruit.
   Asked whether a new plan was in the works, Shultz said, ``We
don't have a new plan to get him out of Panama, but we can
certainly describe to (the leaders), and have, his association with
drug dealing and the great undesirability of having a person who is
that prominent in a country associated with drug dealing.''
   Terrorism is another topic expected to be discussed this week.
   At last year's Venice summit, the leaders basically reiterated a
statement, reached at the Tokyo summit in 1986, that condemns
states that deal with terrorists.
   But this time, Shultz said he expected the seven leaders to
exercise the ``no-place-to-hide'' doctrine and to call on all
countries around the world to deny fuel to airplane hijackers.
   The idea is to prevent hostage-holders from taking off with
their victims, Shultz said at a U.S. Information Agency telecast
and a White House briefing last week.
   ``It's a specific thing that if given broad endorsement might be
helpful,'' the secretary said.
   Shultz also predicted a serious discussion of a multilateral aid
package for the Philippines and said Western leaders were expected
to talk about assisting Afghan refugees who are attempting to
resettle in their nation as the Soviet invaders withdraw.
   Reagan, in his recent speech, discussed aid to restore the
economies of war-ravaged Afghanistan and the Philippines. But
Reagan said the Philippines need aid because of its ``communist-led
insurrection,'' and made no mention of the country's money woes in
the wake of the fall of longtime President Ferdinand Marcos.
   On South Africa, Shultz indicated that the United States would
resist any discussion of imposing stiffer economic sanctions on the
country that practices racial segregation.
   ``We don't see here in the United States that it is a good idea
to go further,'' Shultz said.
   Wallis of the State Department said the leaders also are
expected to quiz Reagan about his experiences from his meetings
with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``They will want to sound out the president on his visit to
Moscow,'' the State Department official said.
   And if they have the time, the leaders are expected to try a
novel approach and talk about the future _ both about problems they
foresee and ways to deal with them.
   ``This is an experiment. We haven't done this before,'' Wallis
said, explaining that while summit planners have attempted to make
time for such a topic before, it has never been accomplished.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
