   Texaco Inc. and Saudi Arabia say they jointly
will refine and market petroleum in the United States under a pact
that the troubled U.S. oil giant said would give it $2 billion in
cash and cost savings.
   The joint venture announced Thursday was the biggest ever
between a foreign supplier and a domestic oil company in the
``downstream'' end of the business, the process for changing crude
into gasoline and other products.
