<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Death Rumor Sparks Oil Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rumored death of Iranian leader Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini has pushed oil futures prices sharply higher.
   The unconfirmed rumor, which circulated in the oil market late
Thursday, turned a thin, lackluster trading day into a rally,
observers said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, finished 13 cents
higher to settle at $16.66 per barrel. The contract lost 30 cents
on Wednesday and slipped as low as $16.30 before the Khomeini rumor
hit on Thursday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, near-term
contracts for wholesale unleaded gasoline gained 0.96 cent a gallon
to 50.19 cents, and home heating oil advanced 0.70 cent to close at
44.12 cents a gallon. Both contracts had fallen along with crude in
the previous session.
   ``The feeling is that if and when he (Khomeini) dies, we'll
probably see some rapproachement between Iran and Iraq,'' said
Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc.
   The two nations have been at war for eight years, and Iraq has
refused to sign recent OPEC accords unless it is granted an oil
production quota equal to Iran's.
</TEXT>
