<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drought-LivestockPrices     06-17 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Livestock Prices,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Cattle Feeders See Possible Collapse of Market Due to Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Livestock prices took some of their sharpest
downturns ever this week, in a trend that could continue until
drought conditions ease, according to beef industry sources.
   ``I'd say it's a complete collapse of the feeder cattle
market,'' said Omaha cattle feeder Bob Gottsch. ``Weather will be
the determining factor in the forseeable future.''
   ``It's just kind of panic selling. There's been some panic and
fear come back into the marketplace,'' Gottsch said Thursday.
   Gottsch and others in the industry said cattlemen fear that a
continued decline in prices _ combined with high grain prices
caused by drought conditions _ will erase their profits and begin
to cause losses.
   Cattle prices remain at near-record levels, $70 per 100 pounds.
But cattlemen's costs for feed are rising just as fast.
   ``If it doesn't rain for the next three weeks, I'd say prices
could go to $65 with a danger of $60 on fat cattle,'' Gottsch said.
Fat cattle are animals that have been fed and are ready for
slaughter at packing houses.
   Gottsch said corn prices, now $2.50 per bushel, may rise to $4
per bushel and soybeans may hit $12 to $15 per bushel, up from the
current $9. He said nearly all producers and feeders would lose
money on cattle at those prices.
   In direct sales to packing houses on Wednesday, prices paid to
eastern Nebraska cattle feeders for steers and heifers started the
day $1 lower and finished $2 to $3 lower, the U.S. Department of
Agriculture reported.
   It marked the sharpest one-day price decline ever, USDA
officials said.
   Prices on the Chicago Board of Trade for cattle futures declined
mostly by the $1.50-per-100-pounds limit Wednesday following
declines the last several days. Livestock and meat futures
rebounded slightly on Thursday, in what analysts deemed mainly a
technical rally.
   Jim Rodenburg, executive secretary of the Omaha Livestock
Exchange, called the recent trend a ``rapid downturn.''
   ``I'm not going to call it a collapse yet. This thing could find
a level to stabilize and then straighten up,'' he said. ``But it's
certainly been kind of a rapid downturn.''
</TEXT>
