<HEAD>President of First RepublicBank Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of First RepublicBank Dallas has
become the latest of several senior managers to leave the troubled
bank.
   John Stuart announced his resignation Thursday, effective July
15, saying he wanted to persue ``numerous business opportunities in
Dallas.''
   A bank spokesman said Albert Casey, chairman and first executive
officer of the parent First RepublicBank Corp. and the Dallas bank,
would assume the post until a replacement is selected.
   First RepublicBank is the largest bank in Texas with $16.6
billion in assets, but the bank has contributed a large portion of
the problem real estate loans that caused the parent company to
seek a $1 billion federal bailout earlier this year.
   Stuart served as director of the company's real estate section
since it was formed a year ago by the merger of RepublicBank Corp.
and InterFirst Corp.
   Stuart, 51, joined Republic Bank as a credit analyst in 1961,
rising to executive vice president in 1971. He managed the bank's
real estate department for more than 10 years and was managing
director of the energy banking group from 1982 to 1984. He later
served as managing director of the corporation's gneeral banking
group.
   Other executives who have recently left First RepublicBank
include Gerald Fronterhouse, the holding company's chairman and
chief executive, who resigned in April, and Charles Pistor, the
Dallas bank chairman, who resigned in April.
</TEXT>
