<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ZZZZBest     06-17 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ZZZZ Best,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revised Indictment Adds Credit-Card Fraud to Minkow's Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities have revised their
charges against fallen carpet-cleaning whiz kid Barry Minkow by
filing a superseding indictment that adds conspiracy and
credit-card fraud counts to the original case.
   The revised 57-count indictment, filed Thursday, names the
22-year-old Minkow and three other defendants as participants in an
alleged conspiracy to commit securities fraud, obtain funds
fraudulently and falsify legal documents.
   The new indictment also alleges that Minkow's illegal conduct
began when the entrepreneur who founded the ZZZZ Best
carpet-cleaning empire was 18 years old _ at least two years
earlier than previously disclosed.
   An added count of credit card fraud alleges that as early as
October 1984, Minkow ``devised and participated in a scheme to
defraud by making unauthorized charges to credit-card numbers of
ZZZZ Best customers.''
   Minkow allegedly obtained more than $29,800 from 16 customers
through the credit-card scheme.
   Minkow's defense attorney, David Kenner, could not immediately
be reached for comment. But at a news conference a week ago, Kenner
declared that his client was a fall guy, ``nothing more than a
stepchild of organized crime.''
   A racketeering count, which carried a 20-year maximum sentence,
has been deleted from the new charges.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James Asperger said the racketeering
count allowed federal authorities to seize Minkow's assets. But
Asperger said those assets have become tied up in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court.
   The prosecutor said the revised indictment increases the maximum
prison term Minkow faces, if convicted, from 350 years to 403 years.
   The original indictment, which was unsealed Jan. 15, charged
Minkow and 10 other defendants with 54 counts of bank fraud, money
laundering, tax fraud and racketeering. A 12th defendant was named
in a separate complaint.
   Most of the previously filed counts are included in the new
case, although all but the four remaining defendants have pleaded
guilty or are expected to do so before trial.
   Minkow founded his ZZZZ Best carpet-cleaning company in his
parents garage in suburban Reseda when he was just 15.
   Four years later, in 1985, he incorporated the business and the
ZZZZ Best Co. became a publicly traded firm in the over-the-counter
market in January 1986.
   However, the revised indictment alleges that as early as March
1985, Minkow and other defendants falsely claimed ZZZZ Best was
performing restoration work on buildings damaged by water, fire and
other causes.
   ``At its height, the restoration work purportedly comprised over
90 percent, or $43.7 million of ZZZZ Best's annual revenues,'' the
indictment states. ``In fact, ZZZZ Best performed virtually no
restoration work.''
   When accusations concerning the fraudulent nature of Minkow's
carpet restoration work began surfacing in May 1987, the indictment
alleges Minkow ``orchestrated a cover-up in which he recruited
various persons to lie to attorneys, accountants and others who
were investigating'' the ZZZZ Best carpet-cleaning company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 0937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Northwest-TV     06-17 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest-TV,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline To Unveil TV-Equipped Jumbo Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines and a California company
plan next week to unveil a Boeing 747 jumbo jet equipped with
3-inch color TV sets fitted into the backs of 116 seats.
   Sheldon Presser, president of California-based Airvision Inc.,
said Thursday that passengers will be able to choose from six
programs on closed-circuit channels played via videocassette.
   The airline would not comment on the new television-equipped
aircraft except to say a news conference was scheduled Tuesday
aboard Observation Flight 5687 on a route over Canada. The airline
said it would tell reporters and photographers about ``an exciting
innovation in inflight entertainment.''
   The programs, Presser said, will include movies, sports, music,
news and, possibly, such programs as ``Night Court'' and
``Moonlighting.'' One channel will be devoted to foreign-language
programs, he said. Passengers will get the audio through earphones.
   Press said the installation is aimed primarily at testing the
system, developed with help from Warner Communications and Philips
N.V., a large Dutch electronics firm.
   Unlike traditional cathode-ray televisions, he said the airborne
sets have small liquid crystal display screens. ``It's really a new
business,'' he said.
   About 30 percent of the seats on the test aircraft will have the
television sets, both in first-class and coach areas.
   The programs will have commercials, Presser said, though
advertising rates have yet to be determined.
</TEXT>
