<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Arab-Airlines     06-17 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arab-Airlines,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Airlines Form Consortium To Purchase 220 Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen Arab air carriers and five financial
institutions have agreed to form a consortium to purchase up to 220
new planes, the chairman of the Kuwait Airways Corporation said.
   Ahmed Mishari said Thursday that studies by the consortium show
a need for the aircraft by the year 1995.
   Mishari, who also chairs the project's steering committee, said
the consortium will be named the Arab Aviation Finance Company and
will be formally inaugurated in 1989.
   In an interview, he said the group was in the process of
selecting a consulting firm to conduct a feasibility study for the
purchases, which could cost up to $10 billion.
   Aviation sources who declined to be identified by name said most
of Arab aircraft purchases in the coming decade would be from
Boeing Co. and the European Airbus consortium.
   In addition to Mishari, steering committee members include the
chairmen of the national airlines of Jordan and Morocco, the
secretary-general of the Arab Air Carriers Organization and
representatives of five banking establishments.
   They are the National Bank of Kuwait, the International Gulf
Bank, the Gulf Investment Establishment, the Arab Banking
Establishment and the Arab Bank for International Investment.
   Mishari said 50 of the new aircraft will be needed to meet
expansion plans while the other 170 planes will replace aging
aircraft.
   Mishari said that the venture was prompted in large part by the
aggressiveness of foreign airlines that sought to control the Arab
market.
</TEXT>
