<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Down, Factory Use and Inventories Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd graf to show starts at lowest level since
January, sted December.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction tumbled 12.2 percent in May for the
steepest drop in five months, the government said today in a report
that suggested rising interest rates have jolted the home-building
business.
   The drop dragged construction activity down to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.38 million units in May, the lowest level
since January, when 2,000 fewer units were begun, the Commerce
Department said. It was also the steepest drop since December, when
starts plunged 15.8 percent.
   The housing report showed how sensitive the home construction
industry is to interest rates, which rose sharply in recent months.
Rates on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages climbed from 10.05 percent at
the start of April to 10.58 percent at the end of May, according to
the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Although the housing report suggested economic weakness, it
added confusion to other statistics released Thursday that
indicated no clear trend.
   A report by the Federal Reserve Board said U.S. factories, mines
and utilities operated at 82.9 percent of capacity last month, a
0.2 percentage point increase over April. It was the sixth increase
in eight months and the highest operating level since March 1980
when the rate hit 83.7 percent.
   Some economists expressed concern that the trend will push
prices higher as manufacturers have difficulty producing enough to
meet demand. But others say the May report is good news, because
operating rates cooled in the hottest industries and increased in
sectors with excess capacity.
   A separate report Thursday by the Commerce Department showed
business inventories rose 0.5 percent in April, signaling slower
economic growth for the second quarter. Business sales fell 0.2
percent in the same month.
   Economists generally take rising inventories as a sign that
buying demand is declining and as an indication that manufacturers
may have to reduce production. But the report of higher factory
utilization rates, as well as other recent evidence of economic
strength, suggested no significant slowdown.
   Financial markets largely ignored the government reports
Thursday, focusing instead on the inflationary impact of an
agricultural drought that could raise food prices later this year.
   Severely dry weather in the farm states caused prices of corn,
soybean and oat futures to soar on the Chicago commodity exchanges,
which in turn incited runups in livestock and meat futures.
   There also was concern among stock and bond investors that
foreign banks might raise interest rates, which could intensify
pressure for higher rates in this country.
   In the bond market, a key barometer of inflation and
interest-rate trends, the 30-year Treasury issue dropped $12.50 per
$1,000 in face amount, and its yield jumped to 8.94 percent from
8.83 percent late Wednesday.
   The bond selloff spread to Wall Street, where the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials fell 37.16 points after rising 32 points
in the prior two trading days. Broader market indexes also fell.
   On foreign exchange markets, the dollar declined against most
key currencies, in response to the speculation of higher foreign
interest rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
