<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-USTrade 1stLd-Writethru   06-17 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-US Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Official Accuses US Of Seeking Confrontation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs on polyester dumping duties.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top trade official of the European
Economic Community on Friday accused the U.S. government of using
``confrontational tactics'' in trans-Atlantic trade policy talks.
   Willy De Clercq, the EEC external affairs commissioner, told the
European Parliament that the United States had become less
cooperative on trade issues.
   ``The willingness of the United States to find negotiated
solutions is diminishing,'' he said. ``Instead, they are trying to
obtain satisfaction on a number of issues through confrontational
tactics.''
   De Clercq said the EEC, or Common Market, was willing to
continue discussing trade matters with the U.S. government. ``But
it must be in a spirit of cooperation and not one of
confrontation,'' he said.
   De Clercq gave no examples of the tactics he ascribed to
Washington, but he recently has complained about a U.S. decision to
reduce the amount of farmland held out of production. The EEC
claims this move is likely to increase U.S. crop production at a
time of global surpluses.
   The EEC also has strongly objected to U.S. complaints that its
subsidies to soybean producers and processors are hurting American
soybean exports to Western Europe. On Thursday, the 96-nation
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which sets and monitors
world trade rules, accepted a U.S. request to establish a special
committee to hear the complaint.
   U.S.-European trade relations are expected to be one of the
topics at the Toronto summit meeting of leaders from the seven
largest industrialized nations that begins Sunday.
   De Clercq's comments were in response to a European Parliament
report that urged action to strengthen GATT procedures for settling
trade disputes.
   In another sign of trade trouble, the EEC said Friday it would
impose punitive duties of up to 28 percent on a range of polyester
products imported from the United States and six other countries.
   The action is in response to a yearlong EEC inquiry that
concluded polyester producers in these countries were selling their
products in the Community at prices below the cost of production.
   The EEC decided to impose duties ranging between 2.5 percent to
28 percent on imports of various polyester fibers imported from the
United States, Mexico, Romania, Taiwan, Turkey and Yugoslavia.
Duties of between 2.7 percent and 26 percent will be charged on
polyester yarns imported from Mexico, South Korea, Taiwan and
Turkey.
   The share of the EEC polyester fiber market held by companies in
these seven countries grew from 9.6 percent in 1984 to 17.8 percent
last year, the EEC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
