<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0348</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved higher today in extremely
heavy trading attributed to the year's second ``triple-witching
hour,'' the expiration of futures and options.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which slipped 37 points
on Thursday, was up 7.29 points at 2,101.53 in the first hour and a
half of trading.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 223.07 million shares. Gainers
led losers by about 11 to 8 with 712 up, 529 down and 536 unchanged
as of 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Traders said volume was typically very heavy as the
triple-witching hour got underway. Some stock-index contracts
expired at the opening, while others will expire at the close of
trading.
   ``There's some nervousness,'' said Peter Vandenberg, a trader
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``But the last few expirations
have been orderly, with no major problems.''
   Despite the heavy volume, stock prices held in a narrow range.
   Traders kept a sharp eye on the credit markets, where severely
depressed bond prices helped trigger Thursday's decline in stock
prices.
   Rumors that West Germany and possibly Japan might be preparing
to hike interest rates sparked fear that the Federal Reserve might
be pressed to do the same to support the dollar.
   ``The bond market could drag us down again today like it did
yesterday,'' Vandenber said.
   Occidental Petroleum accounted for almost half of the early
volume, down [ at 26|, with more than 103 million shares changing
hands. Much of the activity was related to the company's impending
quarterly dividend.
   Elsewhere, Texaco was up \ at 49}. The oil giant today holds its
annual meeting, where Carl Icahn will wage a proxy battle.
   IBM was unchanged at 117[, Smithkline Beckman was off 1 at 44},
and General Electric was up [ at 43].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.36 at 152.80. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 0.06 at 307.01.
