<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TexacoMeeting 3rdLd-Writethru   06-17 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco Meeting, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Annual Meeting Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to include DeCrane cutting off Icahn's
speech; picks up 4th graf, After months ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s annual meeting drew a packed
house today as a closely watched proxy war between the nation's
third largest oil company and financier Carl C. Icahn came to a
close.
   Stakes were high in the meeting, called to order by Texaco
Chairman Alfred C. DeCrane Jr., who told shareholders the company
was aggressively restructuring to put its legal and bankruptcy
ordeals into the past.
   ``The bottom line of all of this is we're reshaping your company
as reflected in Texaco's new advertising theme, `Up ahead there's
Texaco, star of the American road,''' DeCrane said. ``That theme
expresses what we intend to be in this industry.''
   Later, DeCrane cut off Icahn when the financier ran past his
10-minute speaking limit, and Icahn responded, ``I think this is a
manifestation of the inflexibility that caused Texaco its
problems.'' The crowd of more than 1,000 responded with a mixture
of scattered boos and cheers.
   After months of invective, lawsuits, charges and
counter-charges, shareholders have cast millions of votes on
whether to support management or Icahn, Texaco's largest
stockholder who has offered to acquire the company in the biggest
corporate buyout in American history.
   Results will not be known for weeks, because it will take that
long to count the proxy ballots.
   Icahn, holder of 14.8 percent of Texaco's 243 million shares,
was running with four allies for the five seats up for election to
the company's 14-member board.
   He seeks the seats to pressure the company to let stockholders
vote on his offer to buy the Texaco shares he does not already own
for $60 each, or about $12.4 billion. Adding the $1.2 billion he
already paid for his stake would raise the acquisition cost to
$13.6 billion, the biggest sum ever paid in a corporate buyout.
   After nearly four weeks of voting, the race widely was believed
to be close.
   Several major institutions were reported to have sided with
Icahn, while others were said to be leaning toward Texaco.
Traditionally, individuals tend to vote for management, but various
sources said it was impossible to assume anything this time.
   Texaco President James W. Kinnear and other top executives
plannedto address shareholders, company spokesman K. Peter Maneri
said, adding: ``Certainly Mr. Icahn, as the largest shareholder,
will also have a chance to speak.''
   Icahn said previously that if he lost, he would sell his stake
and ``go away,'' but he in recent days he also said he might try a
hostile takeover bid.
   Texaco and Icahn each have lawsuits pending against the other
and have engaged in months of verbal warfare, Texaco being
ever-mindful of Icahn's long record as a successful corporate
takeover strategist.
   Icahn began buying up Texaco shares last fall, while the company
was struggling to overcome a $10.3 billion judgment won by Pennzoil
Co. in a court fight over Texaco's acquisition of Getty Oil Co. The
ruling ultimately led to Texaco's filing for bankruptcy court
reorganization in April 1987.
   Pennzoil agreed in December to settle the case for $3 billion in
a deal that was the keystone of the Texaco reorganization plan
ultimately approved by the court in April.
   Texaco officials, calling for shareholder support, touted the
plan as the vehicle for a ``new'' more profitable Texaco to come.
   Icahn accused Texaco management of incompetence, charging it was
seeking to entrench itself, while ignoring the interests of its
shareholders.
   In response, management accused him of looking out only for his
own interests _ at the expense of other shareholders _ and of
seeking to bleed the company for the highest short-term profit
possible.
   Icahn gained some support from stockholders in his fight.
   As a result, Texaco agreed to include a vote on certain
``corporate governance'' issues on the proxy ballot, including,
among others, restrictions on the adoption of takeover defenses, an
anti-greenmail provision and more participation by shareholders in
choosing directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
