<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Scotus-Garnish 1stLd-Writethru f0085 06-17 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Garnish, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0085,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier To Garnish Some Employee Benefits in Georgia
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf to give complete citation; Also moved on
general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier for
creditors to garnish employee benefits from workers covered by the
federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA).
   By a 5-4 vote in a case from Georgia, the court said ERISA
benefits are not shielded from garnishment even when a state law
seeks to protect the benefits from being obtained from creditors.
   Justice Byron R. White, in his opinion for the court, said ERISA
pre-empts state laws in such cases.
   The court ruled in favor of the Lanier Collection Agency &
Service, which represents people owed money by 23 longshoremen.
   The longshoremen received vacation and holiday benefits from the
South Atlantic@ILA Vacation and Holiday Fund. The fund provides
benefits to longshoremen in North and South Carolina, Georgia and
Florida.
   A Georgia law exempts from garnishment most benefits covered by
ERISA plans.
   But the Supreme Court said the state law conflicts with ERISA
and is pre-empted by the federal law.
   The decision upheld a ruling by the Georgia Supreme Court.
   Dissenting today were Justices Anthony M. Kennedy, Harry A.
Blackmun, Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
   The case is Mackey vs. Lanier Collection Agency, 86-1387.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
