<DOCNO> AP880617-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     06-17 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0437</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market receded slightly today and
trading slowed from a brisk early pace that was attributed in part
to the year's second ``triple-witching hour,'' the expiration of
futures and options.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which slipped 37 points
on Thursday, was off 4.09 points at 2,090.15 at mid-afternoon.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 283.15 million shares. Losers
led by about 10 to 9 with 647 up, 695 down and 548 unchanged as of
2 p.m on Wall Street.
   Volume exceeded the previous first-hour record just 45 minutes
after the opening bell but had slowed considerably at midday.
Trading in Occidental Petroleum accounted for almost half of the
early volume, with more than 103 million shares changing hands.
Much of the activity was related to the company's impending
quarterly dividend.
   In addition, traders said volume was typically heavy as the
quarterly triple-witching hour got underway. Some stock-index
contracts expired at the opening, while others will expire at the
close of trading.
   ``There's some nervousness,'' said Peter Vandenberg, a trader
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``But the last few expirations
have been orderly, with no major problems.''
   Alfred Goldman, director of technical market analysis at A.G.
Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis, called the activity typical and
noted that the triple-witching hour rendered the market's movements
``meaningless. It is totally controled by non-market, non-economic
factors.''
   On Thursday, severely depressed bond prices helped trigger a
decline in stock prices.
   Rumors that West Germany and possibly Japan might be preparing
to hike interest rates sparked fears that the Federal Reserve might
be pressed to do the same to support the dollar.
   But Goldman said that despite the activity in the credit
markets, the stock market was overdue for a selloff.
   The Dow ``had been up 200 points in just two and a half weeks,''
he noted. ``The market was overbought, and we needed a crack to
clear out some of the optimism.''
   Among actively traded issues, Texaco was up | at 50[. The oil
giant held its annual meeting, where Carl Icahn addressed
shareholders in his quest to win their votes in a proxy battle with
Texaco management.
   IBM was down | at 116{, Merck was off ~ at 54|, and General
Electric was off ] at 42~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.16 at 152.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was off 0.85 at 306.22.
</TEXT>
