<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     06-17 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed In Europe, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed at varying levels in Europe on
Friday after trading in a narrow range all day. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said there was little activity as their
markets were waiting to see whether significant results would
emerge from the Toronto summit of the industrially developed
countries, which starts Sunday.
   Banks and financial markets were shut for a holiday in West
Germany, which also kept conditions quiet.
   The British pound fell in London on reports that the British
trade deficit in the first quarter of this year appeared to be $5
billion and not $3.4 billion as estimated earlier.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7827 late Friday, cheaper
for buyers than Thursday's late $1.7900.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with late
Thursday: 1.7530 West German marks, up from 1.7505; 1.4575 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4580; 5.9120 French francs, up from 5.9005;
1.9695 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9650; 1,301.35 Italian lire, up
from 1,299.50; 1.2130 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2160.
   In Tokyo earlier, the dollar closed at 125.73 Japanese yen, down
from 125.98. Late in London the dollar traded at 125.85 yen.
   Gold bullion closed in London, the major European market, at a
bid $450 a troy ounce, down from $452.80 Thursday.
   The Zurich price was $450.40 bid, down from $452.50.
   Gold had closed earlier in Hong Kong at a bid $452.15, down from
$454.52.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $7.08 a troy
ounce, down from $7.21.
