<HEAD>London Shares End Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading activity; No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell Friday on the London Stock
Exchange as the market was hit by worries about interest-rate
increases.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished down
11.8 points, or 0.63 percent, at 1,850.1.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up
0.89 point at 2,095.13 as the London trading session drew to a
close, after opening 3.38 points higher.
   Of the FT-SE 100 shares, 16 were higher, while 73 were in
negative territory and 11 showed no change at the end of the
session.
   London analysts said the market was upset by the perception that
the British government would increase interest rates to douse an
overheating economy.
   ``We know the authorities would love to tickle up interest rates
a fraction if they only have the opportunity,'' said one trading
floor manager at a large British brokerage.
   British economic indicators released at midday Friday did
nothing to allay the interest-rate worries, dealers said.
Industrial production rose 1.5 percent in April from March and was
up 4.3 percent from a year earlier, while retail prices rose 0.4
percent in May from April and were 4.2 percent higher than in May
1987.
   The rise in London share prices over the week was another source
of concern, analysts said, as they questioned the speed of the
ascent.
   ``We ran up too far and too fast this week and it just wasn't
sustainable,'' one dealer said.
   In addition, the upcoming three-day Toronto economic summit kept
players guessing about the intentions of the leaders of the Group
of Seven major economic nations.
   ``The G-7 may agree on some policy to push up interest rates to
wring some of the excess liquidity out of the system,'' one dealer
said, ``especially with worries about the potential for disaster
with the worsening drought in the U.S.''
</TEXT>
