<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ScotusRdp     06-17 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus Rdp,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Placement of Newsracks Is Protected by First Amendment, Court Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A version on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court made it more difficult
Friday for communities to regulate the placement of newspaper boxes
on public sidewalks.
   By a 4-3 vote, the court said placement of the boxes, called
newsracks, is a form of expression in a public forum protected by
the Constitution's First Amendment.
   The decision struck down as unconstitutional a Lakewood, Ohio,
ordinance because it gave the suburban city's mayor too much
discretion in deciding which newsracks would be allowed.
   In other decisions, the court:
   _Struck down, by an 8-1 vote, an Ohio law that exempted from any
deadlines the filing of lawsuits against out-of-state defendants.
The justices said the law unduly interfered with interstate
commerce.
   _Made it easier, on a 5-4 vote, for creditors to garnish
employee benefits from workers covered by the federal Employee
Retirement Income Security Act. The court said ERISA benefits are
not shielded from garnishment even when a state law seeks to
protect the benefits from being obtained from creditors.
   _Resolved a jurisdictional tug-of-war between two federal
appeals courts involving an antitrust dispute over the M-16, the
U.S. military standard rifle. The justices unanimously ruled the
Chicago-based 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals should rule in the
case, not the Washington-based U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Federal Circuit.
   Writing for the court in the newsrack decision, Justice William
J. Brennan said the ordinance could allow a mayor to deny permits
for newsracks based on a newspaper's content.
   Nothing in Friday's decision, however, necessarily prevents a
community from banning all newsracks.
   Such a ban would not be based on content, Brennan noted, and if
challenged could be upheld if found to be a reasonable restriction
on the time, place or manner of constitutionally protected
expression.
   Three justices voted to uphold the Lakewood ordinance, and said
communities should be free to ban newsracks from all public
property.
   But Brennan said the court's majority was not going to discuss
the validity of such a ban.
   About Lakewood's ordinance, Brennan said ``a law or policy
permitting communication in a certain manner for some but no for
others raises the specter of content and viewpoint censorship.''
   The Lakewood controversy began in 1982 when The Plain Dealer, a
Cleveland newspaper, was refused permission to place coin-operated
newsracks in various locations throughout the suburban city.
   The newspaper sued, and a federal trial judge and the 6th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals invalidated the ordinance. The appeals
court, however, ruled that Lakewood could charge rent for newsracks
placed on public property and could ban newsracks from residential
neighborhoods.
   Plain Dealer Publisher Thomas Vail said Friday, ``the Supreme
Court has recognized that improper restrictions on newsracks are
subject to prompt constitutional challenge. This is an important
application of First Amendment principles to the public interest in
convenient and effective access to the nation's newspapers.''
   Jerry W. Friedheim, president of American Newspaper Publishers
Association, said the ruling ``underlined what numerous lower
courts, legal scholars and newspapers have always believed: The
distribution of news deserves the highest First Amendment
protection. By reminding public officials that they have strictly
limited powers when they regulate newspaper distribution, the court
gives both newspapers and municipal governments a strong impetus to
find the best ways of keeping the public informed.''
   The decision produced a lively exchange between Brennan and
Justice Byron R. White, author of a combative, 27-page dissenting
opinion.
   While Brennan compared regulating newsracks to regulating people
who pass out leaflets, White said the better comparison was the
regulation of newsracks and soft-drink vending machines.
   ``The First Amendment does not create a right of newspaper
publishers to take a portion of city property to erect a structure
to distribute their papers,'' White wrote for himself and Justices
John Paul Stevens and Sandra Day O'Connor.
   But Brennan's view, joined by Justices Thurgood Marshall, Harry
A. Blackmun and Antonin Scalia, prevailed.
   ``The effectiveness of the newsrack as a means of distribution,
especially for low-budget, controversial neighborhood newspapers,
means that the twin threats of self-censorship and undetectable
censorship are, if anything, greater for newsracks than for
pamphleteers,'' Brennan said.
   The justices sent the Lakewood case back to a federal appeals
court, which must determine whether the ordinance can survive
constitutional attack if the mayoral-discretion aspect is dropped.
   Several similar legal fights are pending in lower courts.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Anthony M.
Kennedy did not participate in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ClioAwards     06-17 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clio Awards,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motel 6, American Express Ads Win Top Clio Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The folksy radio commercials for Motel 6 and the
American Express ad series that features photos of some of its most
famous card members took 1988 Clio awards Friday as the best
national radio and print campaigns.
   The television Clios are to be announced Monday night.
   Richards Group, a Dallas advertising agency, won the national
radio campaign Clio for its ads for Motel 6, which operates a chain
of budget-priced motels.
   The ads use low-key humor to describe the advantages of staying
at Motel 6 and conclude with the promise, ``We'll leave the light
on for you.''
   Among other advertising agencies and production houses that won
radio Clios, the big winner was Dick Orkin's Radio Ranch of Los
Angeles.
   Orkin won three Clios with ads for Kroger Co. in the local large
campaign category, for Blue Cross-Blue Shield of Ohio in health
care services and Sheffield Hotel in the travel segment.
   The ad agencies Campbell-Mithun of Chicago, W.B. Doner & Co. of
Baltimore, Hal Riney & Partners of San Francisco and Chiat-Day
Advertising of Los Angeles each won two radio Clios.
   A total of 28 Clios were awarded in the U.S. radio competition.
   Ogilvy & Mather of New York won the national print campaign Clio
for its American Express ad series called ``Portraits.'' The
campaign has featured striking photographs of some of its
best-known card members, including former House Speaker Thomas P.
O'Neill, ex-baseball pitcher Tom Seaver, actress Candice Bergen and
singer Ella Fitzgerald.
   The agency winning the most Clios for print advertising was
Fallon McElligott of Minneapolis with 11. Its winning work included
ads for the University of Minnesota athletic department, First
Tennesee Bank and the Children's Defense Fund.
   The agencies Martin-Williams of Minneapolis and Chiat-Day, which
has offices in New York and San Francisco as well as Los Angeles,
each won three print Clios. There were 37 Clios awarded in the U.S.
print competition.
   In U.S. packaging design, Gerstman-Myers Inc., a New York design
firm, was the only multiple winner with two Clios. Buntin
Advertising of Nashville was the only multiple winner in U.S.
specialty design competition with two Clios.
   The awards program is administered by Clio Awards, a private
company based in New York that has overseen the competition for 29
years.

</TEXT>
