<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennwalt Sale,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Wants To Work Out A Friendly Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. said Friday it is exploring
the sale of its pharmaceuticals and equipment divisions and refused
comment on an investment partnership's takeover offer.
   Centaur Partners, which holds 6.5 percent of Pennwalt's common
stock, sent a letter to Pennwalt Chairman Edwin Tuttle on Friday
offering to buy the company ``on a friendly basis at a significant
premium to the market price.''
   Centaur demanded a response by Tuesday and told Tuttle, ``If you
refuse to meet with us or to respond to this letter, we must
reserve the right to pursue all options available to us.'' That
would include a hostile tender offer.
   Pennwalt's stock rose $2.87{ a share to $81 a share Friday in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading. The stock had jumped
$9.25 a share in the preceding two sessions.
   Since there are slightly more than 12 million shares
outstanding, Friday's closing price gives Pennwalt a market value
of nearly $1 billion.
   Centaur is composed of Melvyn J. Estrin of Washington, D.C., a
financier and real estate investor and former chairman of American
Health Services; Abbey J. Butler, president of C.B. Equities with
assets in access of $500 million, and former chairman of Financial
World magazine; and Robert Nederlander, a lawyer and president of
Nederlander Organization Corp., which owns Broadway theaters, and
also part owner of the New York Yankees of the American League.
   Combined they reportedly have assets in excess of $300 million,
which includes the $52.9 million they currently hold in Pennwalt
stock. The group also is reported to have a financing commitment
from Citicorp, the nation's largest banking conglomerate, should
they have to make a tender offer.
   Tuttle said Pennwalt's investment bankers, Goldman, Sachs & Co.,
have been directed to continue discussions with possible buyers of
the pharmaceutical division and to explore the possible sale of the
equipment group.
   Pennwalt's pharmaceuticals division accounted for about 11
percent of sales and 14 percent of operating earnings last year,
while the equipment division accounted for 14 percent of sales and
11 percent of operating earnings.
   Pennwalt spokeswoman Ann Carmandy declined to comment on whether
there were any offers for any of the Pennwalt divisions offered for
sale.
   The company's biggest unit, chemicals and natural resources, is
not up for sale. Last year the entire company earned $52.4 million
on revenue of $1.14 billion.
   Pennwalt has 9,600 employees worldwide and current management
owns only 1.3 percent of the stock.
</TEXT>
