<HEAD>Saatchi Agrees To Buy Gartner Group for $90.3 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saatchi & Saatchi Co. PLC, the British
communications giant, said Friday it agreed to acquire Gartner
Group Inc., a Connecticut-based information technology consultant,
for $90.3 million.
   Saatchi said Gartner's board had approved the deal, which had
been a topic of speculation all week. Gartner had announced Monday
that it was talking to a potential buyer and speculation soon
focused on Saatchi.
   Saatchi has been developing its line of consulting services
since growing into the world's biggest ad holding company through
acquisitions.
   Saatchi said a wholly owned subsidiary plans to begin a tender
offer of $22.50 a share for all of Gartner's 4.1 million shares of
common stock. The offer is conditioned on a majority of the shares
of Gartner being tendered to Saatchi.
   The companies said in a statement that holders of about 30
percent of Gartner common stock, including Chairman Gideon Gartner,
had agreed to tender their shares to Saatchi.
   Saatchi said Gartner and two executive vice presidents also
agreed to eneter into long-term employment deals.
   Gartner Group, which had closed at $13.50 a share last week,
rose $4.25 a share on Friday to $22 in over-the-counter trading.
   Gartner specializes in analyzing and making forecasts of the
information technology market. It provides information services to
vendors and users of technolgy-related products and services.
   Saatchi said Gartner had a pre-tax profit of $3.8 million on
revenue of $40 million in the year ended March 31.
</TEXT>
