<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-17 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Up In New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mixed Friday in slow
foreign-exchange trading, which brokers attributed largely to their
reluctance to speculate in currencies before the Toronto economic
summit.
   Gold prices rose in the United States on inflation fears after
falling abroad. Republic National Bank of New York quoted gold at
$454.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $450 late Thursday.
   Foreign-exchange brokers said the dollar was supported by signs
of economic strength in the United States, notably the report of a
shrunken monthly trade deficit earlier in the week.
   At the same time, the dollar was hurt by moves toward higher
interest rates in West Germany and Japan. This made investments
denominated in Japanese yen and West German marks relatively more
valuable.
   The slack trading volume was largely blamed on the slight chance
that leaders of the seven major industrialized democracies meeting
this Sunday in Toronto would make statements or take action that
would affect currency values. As a result, most traders weren't
willing to make speculative moves.
   ``It's just a precautionary measure,'' said Robert Hatcher, vice
president of corporate trading at Barclays Bank PLC's New York
branch. ``One never can be certain what might emerge from the
meeting. Rather than stick your neck out, you assume a defensive
positon. You wait for their communique.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 125.73 yen, down from 125.98 yen
late Thursday. Later in London the dollar traded at 125.85 yen. By
the time trading concluded in New York, the dollar was quoted at
125.74 yen, up from 125.52 yen.
   The pound fell in London on reports that the British trade
deficit in the first quarter of this year was higher than
originally estimated. Later in New York, the pound traded at
$1.7837, cheaper than $1.7912 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with levels late
Thursday, included: 1.7486 West German marks, down from 1.7489;
1.4557 Swiss francs, down from 1.4566; 1.2137 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2131; 5.9010 French francs, up from 5.8982; and 1,298.50
Italian lire, down from 1,298.75.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.7530 West German marks, up from 1.7505;
1.4575 Swiss francs, down from 1.4580; 5.9120 French francs, up
from 5.9005; 1.9695 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9650; 1,301.35
Italian lire, up from 1,299.50; 1.2130 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2160.
   Rising gold prices in the United States reflected fears of
drought-spawned domestic inflation, which has been pushing grain
and meat prices sharply higher. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, bullion for current delivery rose $4.50 a troy ounce to
$454.50.
   Earlier in London, gold fell to $450 a troy ounce, down from
$452.80 late Thursday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold fetched
$450.40, down from $452.50 Thursday, and in Hong Kong gold fetched
$452.15 compared with $454.52 Thursday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $7.08 a troy ounce, down
from $7.21. On the New York Comex, bullion for current delivery was
quoted at $7.235 an ounce, up 12 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1756EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NewspageStocks     06-17 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage Stocks,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trading Volume Surges to a High for the Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YOKR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late rally pushed the stock market higher
Friday as trading surged to its fastest pace of the year.
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange totaled 343.92 million
shares, with much of the action attributed to dividend-related
purchases and to trading associated with the ``triple-witching
hour,'' which marks the quarterly expiration of stock futures and
options contracts.
   The volume surpassed the 310.03 million shares that changed
hands June 8.
   Prices were down most of the day, but stocks rallied late in the
session.
   The Dow Jones industrial average, down almost 17 points a
half-hour before the close, ended the session up 9.78 at 2,104.02.
Four stocks rose in price for every three that fell on the NYSE.
   Trading in Occidental Petroleum accounted for almost a third of
the day's volume, with more than 104 million shares traded. Friday
was the last day for shareholders to be eligible for the company's
impending quarterly dividend.
   In addition, the heavy volume was typical for a triple-witching
hour session, traders noted. Some stock-index contracts expired at
the opening, while others expired at the close of trading.
</TEXT>
