<DOCNO> AP880617-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1816EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Gucci     06-17 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gucci,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Grandson from Using Gucci Name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The international family feud over use of the
Gucci name for retail sales was partially settled Friday, with a
federal judge ruling the grandson of the company's founder cannot
use his own name as a trademark.
   Gucci is barred from designing and selling merchandise under the
company name ``Paolo Gucci,'' as he has in the past, the judge said.
   But U.S. District Judge William C. Conner, in a 33-page
decision, ruled Paolo Gucci can attach his name to other
trademarked products.
   Paolo's name can follow an existing trademark _ for example,
``American Tourister Luggage by Paolo Gucci,'' the judge wrote. But
his name cannot be more prominent than the trademark, and there
must be a disclaimer that he does not work for Gucci, Conner said.
   ``It is clear ... that if Paolo Gucci were to continue to use
his name as a trademark or a trade name, an appreciable number of
consumers would confuse his goods with those of the defendant,''
Conner wrote in his ruling.
   An attorney for Gucci Shops, Inc., which has 21 stores around
the United States, was in a meeting at his Washington office and
was unavailable for comment on the ruling. The company sought to
block Paolo from using the Gucci name on competing products.
   Paolo, 57, is now designing lamps, sunglasses, furniture,
sleepwear, bedding accessories, wall covering, lingerie, plates and
flatware.
   ``I just got off the phone with Paolo from London, and he's
thrilled, totally ecstatic,'' said his attorney, Randy Lipsitz.
``He considers this a complete victory.''
   Paolo, the grandson of company founder Guccio Gucci, was ousted
from the company following a family dispute in 1978. Despite
attempts to patch things up with his cousin Maurizio _ now owner of
50 percent of the company _ the pair have instead ended up in court
settling their differences.
   The suit settled Friday was filed five years ago; the cousins
are embroiled in another legal fight currently before an
arbitration panel in Geneva, Switzerland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
