<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Perot-PostalContract     06-17 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Perot-Postal Contract,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Firms Complain of No-Bid Contract Award To Perot's Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies have asked the General Services
Administration to void a contract between a firm owned by Dallas
billionaire Ross Perot and the U.S. Postal Service, which
maintained Friday the deal was proper.
   Electronic Data Systems Corp. of Dallas and Planning Research
Corp. of McLean, Va., filed a complaint with the GSA Board of
Contract Appeals, saying they didn't have a chance to bid on the
$500,000 contract awarded Perot Systems Corp.
   The complaint alleges that the no-bid contract, under which
Perot Systems will review the Postal Service's cost-cutting
procedures, violated federal contract procedures.
   Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, in a prepared statement,
said Friday, ``It is our position that we did not do anything wrong
or improper,'' regarding the contract.
   But Bill Wright, a spokesman for EDS, said, ``Any time these
kind of contracts occur, there's potential busines you can't have.
It takes us out of the market.''
   Planning Research Corp. spokesman Chuck Taylor said the company
would not comment on the complaint while it is in litigation.
   A secretary for Perot said he was out of the country and could
not be reached.
   The complaints were filed under the Brooks Act, which is more
than 20 years old. The act gives the GSA review authority over
federal data-processing contracts. The GSA board, which has 45
working days to issue a ruling, has the power to revise, revoke or
suspend the contract. Its ruling can be appealed to federal court.
   The EDS complaint alleges that the Postal Service failed to open
the contract to review and bidding and included several unusual
provisions in the contract that would favor Perot Systems, the
Dallas Morning News reported.
   Perot announced June 2 that he had formed Perot Systems, a
Washington-based computer services company with several former EDS
mid-level executives.
   Under the contract, Perot Systems is to conduct a study of the
Postal Service's performance regarding transportation, telephone
systems, delivery, revenue protection and transportation equipment
duties.
</TEXT>
