<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DisposableLenses     06-17 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disposable Lenses,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disposable Contact Lenses Branching Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disposable contact lens, introduced
on a limited basis in this country only last year, will be much
more visible this summer.
   On Friday, Bausch & Lomb, the nation's leading maker of contact
lenses and related solutions, introduced its entry into the
disposable market called SeeQuence.
   The lenses, designed for replacement every one to two weeks,
will cost a customer between $300 and $500 a year and will be test
marketed in six cities in California and Florida.
   They are a further extension of the company's ``Fresh Lens''
frequent replacement program, started in 1985, which calls for
periodic office visits and new lenses every month or several months.
   About 75,000 patients are enrolled in that program in the United
States and overseas.
   ``We see that the entire concept of dispoale contact lenses has
a lot going for it,'' said Franklin Jepson, a spokesman for Bausch
& Lomb. ``We think people are realizing there's other reasons to
replace a contact lens besides having lost one, torn one or not
being able to see out of one.''
   Meanwhile, the company that first brought disposable contact
lenses to the Untied States, Vistakon Inc. of Jacksonville, Fla., a
wholly owned subsidiary of Johnson & Johnson, is planning a news
conference on Tuesday to announce that its ACUVUE lenses will be
available nationally in July.
   Vistakon has been ``quite pleased'' with its sales so far in
Florida and California, where it launched the disposable lenses
last year, said Dr. Sheldon Wechsler, a company vice president.
   Disposable soft contact lenses are being touted as healthier for
the eye and easier to use than both daily-wear lenses, which have
to be disinfected each night, and extended-wear lenses, which have
been cited as contributing to some eye ailments because they're
worn for long periods of time.
   The disposable lenses are not significantly different than
lenses currently on the market, said Irving Aarons, an analyst who
follows the eye care industry for Arthur D. Little Inc. in
Cambridge, Mass.
   The difference between conventional and disposable lenses stems
from the cost of making and packaging them, Aarons said. The
wholesale cost of soft contact lenses is about $8 to $12, but
Vistakon sells its disposable lenses for about $2.50 a pair, Aarons
said.
   Bausch & Lomb is ``following on the coattails'' of Vistakon with
its disposable lenses, but wants to make sure it has something on
the market in case disposable contact lenses skyrocket, Aarons said.
   The disposable contact lens concept started in Denmark in the
mid-1980s and has been used there and in Scandanavia since.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880617-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1843EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AlleghenyInternational     06-17 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Board Approves Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of Allegheny
International Inc. approved Friday a bankruptcy reorganization plan
calling for shareholders to retain 25 percent of the restructured
company's common stock.
   The Pittsburgh-based consumer products company also said it
welcomed any proposals or plans of reorganization from qualified
buyers, opening the door to a Los Angeles investor interested in
purchasing the company.
   The plan provides for all creditors of three of the company's
subsidiaries _ Sunbeam Corp., Almet-Lawnlite Inc. and Chemetron
Corp. _ to be paid in full.
   Unsecured creditors of Allegheny International are to receive
varying percentages of their claims, payable in cash, notes and
common stock.
   The plan, which will be filed Monday, is subject to approval by
shareholders and the bankruptcy court.
   Chairman Oliver S. Travers said the plan is ``a strong step
forward in the company's emergence from Chapter 11 protection and
for the continuing focus on AI's consumer products business.''
   Allegheny International filed for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the U.S. bankruptcy laws on Feb. 20, 1988.
   The filing of the plan has been eagerly awaited by Los Angeles
investor David Murdock, who runs food processor Castle & Cooke.
   Murdock said he wanted to see management's own reorganization
plan before he makes a formal proposal to acquire Allegheny
International.
   A group of dissidents, supported by New York investor Bennett
LeBow, wanted to gain control of the board before management
submitted its reorganization plan to bankruptcy court. LeBow had
said he may propose a plan that would give him control of Allegheny
International while paying shareholders more than their stock is
now worth on the market.
   A proxy vote for seven of 13 board seats is scheduled for Monday.
   A federal appeals court has ordered the company to take no
action on its reorganization plan until at least late July, when
the court will consider a suit filed by creditors aimed at halting
the proxy battle.
</TEXT>
