<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ArkansasBest     06-17 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arkansas Best,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arkansas Best Signs Merger Agreement with Kelso</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arkansas Best Corp. said it has signed a
$316 million merger agreement with a merchant banking firm in an
effort to head off a takeover attempt by Razorback Acquisition Corp.
   The announcement was made late Thursday after a meeting of the
Arkansas Best board of directors. The company said it had signed an
agreement with Kelso & Co. whereby Kelso would acquire Arkansas
Best's stock for $26 a share.
   That's $3 a share more than the most recent offer of Razorback
Acquisition.
   The board met to consider proposals relating to the acquisition
of the trucking and furniture company and found a ``white knight''
in Kelso & Co., a merchant banking firm with offices in New York,
Newport Beach, Calif., and San Francisco. Kelso specializes in
leveraged buyout transactions involving employee stock-ownership
plans.
   According to a news release, a Kelso subsidiary will acquire
Arkansas Best for $26 per share of common stock and $1,002.31 per
$1,000 principal amount of 7 percent convertible subordinated
debentures due 2011. The amounts will be paid in cash.
   The current offer by Razorback Acquisition, a New York-based
firm that incorporated specifically to take over Arkansas Best, is
$23 a share and $886.66 for each $1,000 convertible bond.
Razorback's first tender offer was for $20 a share.
   Arkansas Best's stock closed | higher Friday at $25.63 a share.
   In its offer, Kelso said it has high regard for the management
of Arkansas Best and agreed that it would maintain the company's
headquarters in Fort Smith. Kelso also said it would provide
employees with benefits which are about the same as those currently
provided by Arkansas Best.
   Under the merger agreement, a cash tender offer will be made for
all outstanding common stock and debentures of Arkansas Best.
   With its offer, Kelso submitted loan commitment letters from
Chemical Bank for $230 million and from First Boston Securities
Corp., an affiliate of First Boston Corp., for $120.62 million.
   The $45 million of common equity required for the transaction
will be provided by Kelso and its affiliates.
   Razorback Acquisition raised its tender offer after the Arkansas
Best board rejected the initial $20 offer as inadequate. The $23
offer was also rejected, but the board left the door open for
negotiations and last week signed a confidentiality agreement
allowing Razorback Acquisition access to non-public information
about Arkansas Best.
   The New York firm had said that it would consider raising its
current offer if it had access to the confidential information.
</TEXT>
