<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TWAFine     06-17 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TWA Fine,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Fined $100,000 by Environmental Protection Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. has been fined
$100,000 for mishandling hazardous wastes and must submit plans by
the end of August for cleaning up an area near its overhaul base at
Kansas City International Airport.
   The fine was levied by the Environmental Protection Agency after
a consent agreement was reached in which the airline neither
admitted nor denied guilt.
   Violations cited by the EPA included dumping paint wastes into a
ditch in a ravine south of the overhaul base, failing to monitor
groundwater contamination, failing to have approved plans for
closing the waste site and monitoring it for pollution, and failing
to provide financial assurances for cleanup.
   TWA must also conduct environmental audits at Lambert-St. Louis
International Airport, Kennedy International Airport in New York
and Los Angeles International Airport.
   TWA was fined $250,000 by the state of Missouri two years ago
and ordered to establish a $500,000 scholarship fund at the
University of Missouri for illegally dumping hazardous wastes in
several pits at the overhaul base.
</TEXT>
