<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 1953EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-InsuranceRegulation     06-17 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insurance Regulation,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance Commissioners Want to Dump Collision Waivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance commissioners from throughout the
country voted Friday to endorse model legislation to eliminate
collision damage waivers charged by car rental companies.
   Under the model drawn up at the National Association of
Insurance Commissioners conference, rental car companies would no
longer be able to sell collision damage waiver insurance and they,
not the customer, would be liable for any damage to a rental car.
   The model legislation is aimed at keeping car rental companies
from selling consumers insurance they do not need. The
commissioners believe that many car rental customers are covered
under their private auto policies.
   Nebraska Insurance Commissioner William McCartney, head of the
national group's Market Conduct Surveillance Task Force, said the
NAIC subgroup on rental car insurance began looking into the
problem more than a year ago.
   The investigation was prompted by hundreds of calls from
consumers who said they were talked into buying collision damage
waivers, known as CDWs, which cost an average of about $10 a day.
   McCartney said the group concluded the waivers were too
expensive, the contracts too vague and that they allow for such a
broad interpretation that the coverage may be worthless.
   The result is the proposal endorsed Friday at the end of the
week-long national conference held in New York.
   The primary drawback to the proposal is that rental companies
would likely hike basic rental fees to cover the cost of assuming
responsibility for damaged cars.
   McCartney said he hoped that would not be the case and that the
proposed legislation would ``protect consumers from the confusion
and abuses inherent in the current practices of selling CDWs.''
   The commissioners will now take the proposal back to their state
legislatures in hopes of having it enacted.
   ``We are definitely in support of legislation that would result
in the abolishment of CDWs and have been working with people on the
state level about this issue for some time,'' said Demetria Mudar,
a spokeswoman for Avis, based in Garden City, N.Y.
   ``We certainly endorse anything that moves us closer to the
elimination of CDWs all across the United States,'' said Joseph
Russo of Hertz.
   He said Hertz, based in Park Ridge, N.J., was concerned that
some car rental companies ``were not treating CDWs as an option and
were in fact using coercion and intimidation, making it virtually
mandatory for customers to buy CDWs, instead of the option that it
should be.''
   Not all of the companies favored the proposal.
   Liz Clarke, of Alamo-Rent-a-Car, said the consumer would end up
paying in the end.
   ``No car rental company can absorb the full cost of damages to
its fleet without passing substantial increases in rental rates to
100 percent of its rental base,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
