<DOCNO> AP880617-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-88 2306EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Farmers-Batus 2ndLd-Writethru f0334 06-17 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0334,0605</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new grafs 5-6 to UPDATE with Batus response, threatening
to sue; picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, Government investors ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California insurance regulators on Friday
denied Batus Inc.'s application to buy Farmers Insurance Group
Inc., dealing a potential death blow to the Kentucky company's $4.5
billion hostile takeover bid.
   Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie said the decision was
based on a section of the state insurance code that forbids
ownership of an insurer by government agencies.
   ``There are governmental entities or agencies that together own
more than 10 percent of BAT's stock,'' Ms. Gillespie said in a news
release, referring to Batus' British parent, BAT Industries PLC.
   ``We're delighted,'' said Farmers spokesman Tom Welch.
   Batus announced that it would sue to have the decision reversed.
   ``Batus believes the department's interpretation is
unconstitutional and will promptly take appropriate legal action to
reverse the department's decision,'' the company said in a news
release. Farmers and many other California insurance companies
count government entities among their shareholders, said Batus
spokesman Wilson Wyatt.
   Government investors in BAT include British city councils and
pension funds and foreign governments, including some Arab
governments, Ms. Gillespie said. The government entities together
own more than 10 percent of the company but no one entity owns more
than 2 percent, she said. She didn't know the exact percentage of
government ownership of Batus.
   Management of Farmers, the nation's third-largest auto and home
insurer, opposes the takeover, which Batus has been pressing in a
3{-month tender offer of $63 a share for all outstanding Farmers
stock. Before the decision was publicized Friday, Batus announced
that holders of 28 percent of Farmers stock had offered to sell at
that price.
   If Batus were able to acquire a controlling interest in Farmers,
it would still need approval of insurance regulators in nine states
in which Farmers does business. California's approval was
considered pivotal, since Farmers is based in Los Angeles.
   Arizona, the only other state to rule on the matter, approved
Batus' application.
   Ms. Gillespie rejected to Farmers' arguments that Batus was
unfit to own an insurance company because it also owns cigarette
companies, she said in a telephone interview from her San Francisco
office.
   Nor was she swayed by a parade of elected state and municipal
officials who publicly denounced the takeover because BAT has
business interests in racially segregated South Africa.
   Farmers had suggested that its non-smoker discounts wouldn't
continue under Batus, and that tobacco product liability suits
could drain Batus' resources.
   ``We did take a look at those issues but we did not find against
BAT on those issues,'' she said.
   Aside from the government ownership, Batus met all the tests for
eligibility to own a California insurer, Ms. Gillespie said.
   She declined to speculate on the rationale for the prohibition
on government ownership of an insurer, but said the commission
staff always interprets the code to mean the 10 percent limit
applies to aggregate ownership by government entities.
   ``This narrow approach has always been the approach of the staff
in these cases,'' Ms. Gillespie said.
   Batus owns Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp., maker of Kool,
Viceroy, Raleigh and Belair cigarettes and retailers including Saks
Fifth Avenue in New York.
   Farmers, with $11 billion in assets, is the nation's
third-biggest home and auto insurer and seventh-largest property
and casualty insurer.
   Batus had extended the deadline on its tender offer, which was
set to expire Thursday, until July 14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
